{"title_page": "Because They Hate", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{more citations needed|date=March 2020}}\n{{mergeto|Brigitte Gabriel|discuss=Talk:Brigitte Gabriel#Merger proposal|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox Book \n| name          = Because They Hate: A Survivor of Islamic Terror Warns America\n| title_orig    = \n| translator    = \n| image         = \n| image_caption = \n| author        = [[Brigitte Gabriel]]\n| illustrator   = \n| cover_artist  = \n| country       = United States\n\n| subject       = [[Islamophobia]], [[criticism of Islam]]\n| genre         = \n| publisher     = [[St. Martin's Press]]\n| release_date  = September 5, 2006\n| english_release_date =\n| media_type    = Hardcover\n| pages         = 272 \n| isbn          = 978-0312358389\n| preceded_by   = \n| followed_by   = [[They Must Be Stopped]]\n}}\n\n'''Because They Hate: A Survivor of Islamic Terror Warns America''' is a book by [[Brigitte Gabriel]], a Lebanese journalist and founder of the anti-Islam group [[American Congress For Truth]]. It describes traumatic childhood experiences of the author in Lebanon and justifies negative stereotypes of Islam by characterizing Islam as a 'religion of violence' and claiming that Muslims want to conquer the world with [[sharia law]] and also to take over America and destroy it.\n\nThe book reached number 12 on the [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times'' Best Seller list]] for political books, becoming one of the leading works to reflect the tendency towards [[Islamophobia]] in Western culture after the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/17/books/16blog-polibooks.html|title=Hardcover Best Seller List|date=November 17, 2006|access-date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter this book, she released another similar book, \"''They Must Be Stopped''\".<ref>Goodstein, Laurie [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/08/us/08gabriel.html Drawing U.S. Crowds With Anti-Islam Message] ''The New York Times''</ref>\n\n==Content==\nThe book begins with events from her childhood in [[Lebanon]], where she was raised by her parents as a [[Maronites|Maronite]] Christian, a minority group in a mainly Muslim country. During the [[Israeli\u2013Lebanese conflict]] in the 1980s, their house was hit by missiles, causing them to move to a barracks, and eventually to an Israeli hospital. With the help of Israeli people, she was able to start a new life, becoming a journalist and a presenter for the Israeli television World News program.\n\nIn the book, she claims that Islamic governments in Middle East are spreading negative prejudices towards \"[[infidel]]s\" (non-Muslims, mostly Christians and Jews), and she argues that Muslims around the world are engaging in [[jihad]] against Christians and Jews, branding Islam as threat.<ref>[https://www.cartercenter.org/resources/pdfs/peace/conflict_resolution/countering-isis/cr-countering-the-islamophobia-industry.pdf Countering The Islamophobia Industry] ''Jimmy Carter Center</ref>\n\nShe explains her view of \"Muslim hatred\" against West and other religions, writing:\n{{blockquote|''Because they hate. They hate our way of life. They hate our freedom. They hate our democracy. They hate the practice of every religion but their own. They don't just disagree. They hate. Not just Judaism. Not just Christianity. In various parts of the world today, Islamists are also waging terror war against Hindus, Buddhists, and all other \"infidels.\" The imposition of Islam upon the entire world is not merely their goal. It is their religious duty. They are following the word of their holy book, the Koran, which is the guide to hatred of infidels, waging war, and victory through slaughter''.}}\n\n==Responses==\nThe book received mixed responses from critics, some feeling that it provided a critical analysis of Islam and a warning to the American people, while other criticized the tone and the biased view of the author and her description of Islam as a 'horrible religion.'<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishindependent.ca/archives/Dec09/archives09Dec18-06.html |publisher=Jewish Independent |date=December 18, 2009 |title=Use the anti-Semitism test |first=Mira | last=Sucharov |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101019234806/http://www.jewishindependent.ca/archives/Dec09/archives09Dec18-06.html |archivedate=October 19, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/among-republicans-polls-show-fear-of-islam-is-always-on-high-simmer/2015/10/01/1b60b29c-66bf-11e5-9223-70cb36460919_story.html|title=Among Republicans, polls show, fear of Islam is always on \u2018high simmer\u2019|last=Tucker|first=Neely|date=October 1, 2015|work=The Washington Post|access-date=|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\nMilitary analyst [[Paul E. Vallely]] praised Gabriel's book as a \"dire warning\" to the Western world.<ref>[https://us.macmillan.com/books/9780312358389 BECAUSE THEY HATE] Macmillan</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[The Truth About Muhammad]] by [[Robert B. Spencer|Robert Spencer]]\n*[[Islamophobia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.c-span.org/video/?194639-1/because-hate C-SPAN Q&A interview about Because They Hate]\n\n[[Category:2011 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Books critical of Islam]]\n[[Category:Islamophobia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{more citations needed|date=March 2020}}\n{{mergeto|Brigitte Gabriel|discuss=Talk:Brigitte Gabriel#Merger proposal|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox Book \n| name          = Because They Hate: A Survivor of Islamic Terror Warns America\n| title_orig    = \n| translator    = \n| image         = \n| image_caption = \n| author        = [[Brigitte Gabriel]]\n| illustrator   = \n| cover_artist  = \n| country       = United States\n\n| subject       = [[Islamophobia]], [[criticism of Islam]]\n| genre         = \n| publisher     = [[St. Martin's Press]]\n| release_date  = September 5, 2006\n| english_release_date =\n| media_type    = Hardcover\n| pages         = 272 \n| isbn          = 978-0312358389\n| preceded_by   = \n| followed_by   = [[They Must Be Stopped]]\n}}\n\n'''Because They Hate: A Survivor of Islamic Terror Warns America''' is a book by [[Brigitte Gabriel]], a Lebanese journalist and founder of the anti-Islam group [[American Congress For Truth]]. It describes traumatic childhood experiences of the author in Lebanon and justifies negative stereotypes of Islam by characterizing Islam as a 'religion of violence' and claiming that Muslims want to conquer the world with [[sharia law]] and also to take over America and destroy it.\n\nThe book reached number 12 on the [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times'' Best Seller list]] for political books, becoming one of the leading works to reflect the tendency towards [[Islamophobia]] in Western culture after the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/17/books/16blog-polibooks.html|title=Hardcover Best Seller List|date=November 17, 2006|access-date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter this book, she released another similar book, \"''They Must Be Stopped''\".<ref>Goodstein, Laurie [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/08/us/08gabriel.html Drawing U.S. Crowds With Anti-Islam Message] ''The New York Times''</ref>\n\n==Content==\nThe book begins with events from her childhood in [[Lebanon]], where she was raised by her parents as a [[Maronites|Maronite]] Christian, a minority group in a mainly Muslim country. During the [[Israeli\u2013Lebanese conflict]] in the 1980s, their house was hit by missiles, causing them to move to a barracks, and eventually to an Israeli hospital. With the help of Israeli people, she was able to start a new life, becoming a journalist and a presenter for the Israeli television World News program.\n\nIn the book, she claims that Islamic governments in Middle East are spreading negative prejudices towards \"[[infidel]]s\" (non-Muslims, mostly Christians and Jews), and she argues that Muslims around the world are engaging in [[jihad]] against Christians and Jews, branding Islam as threat.<ref>[https://www.cartercenter.org/resources/pdfs/peace/conflict_resolution/countering-isis/cr-countering-the-islamophobia-industry.pdf Countering The Islamophobia Industry] ''Jimmy Carter Center</ref>\n\nShe explains her view of \"Muslim hatred\" against West and other religions, writing:\n{{blockquote|''Because they hate. They hate our way of life. They hate our freedom. They hate our democracy. They hate the practice of every religion but their own. They don't just disagree. They hate. Not just Judaism. Not just Christianity. In various parts of the world today, Islamists are also waging terror war against Hindus, Buddhists, and all other \"infidels.\" The imposition of Islam upon the entire world is not merely their goal. It is their religious duty. They are following the word of their holy book, the Koran, which is the guide to hatred of infidels, waging war, and victory through slaughter''.}}\n\n==Responses==\nThe book received mixed responses from critics, some feeling that it provided a critical analysis of Islam and a warning to the American people, while other criticized the tone and the biased view of the author and her description of Islam as a 'horrible religion.'<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishindependent.ca/archives/Dec09/archives09Dec18-06.html |publisher=Jewish Independent |date=December 18, 2009 |title=Use the anti-Semitism test |first=Mira | last=Sucharov |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101019234806/http://www.jewishindependent.ca/archives/Dec09/archives09Dec18-06.html |archivedate=October 19, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/among-republicans-polls-show-fear-of-islam-is-always-on-high-simmer/2015/10/01/1b60b29c-66bf-11e5-9223-70cb36460919_story.html|title=Among Republicans, polls show, fear of Islam is always on \u2018high simmer\u2019|last=Tucker|first=Neely|date=October 1, 2015|work=The Washington Post|access-date=|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\nMilitary analyst [[Paul E. Vallely]] praised Gabriel's book as a \"dire warning\" to the Western world.<ref>[https://us.macmillan.com/books/9780312358389 BECAUSE THEY HATE] Macmillan</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[The Truth About Muhammad]] by [[Robert Spencer]]\n*[[Islamophobia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.c-span.org/video/?194639-1/because-hate C-SPAN Q&A interview about Because They Hate]\n\n[[Category:2011 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Books critical of Islam]]\n[[Category:Islamophobia]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toRobert Spencer(link changed toRobert B. Spencer) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Because_They_Hate"}
{"title_page": "Botswana at the 2019 African Games", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox country at games\n| NOC               =  BOT\n| NPC               = \n| IAAF              = \n| CGA               = \n| NF                = \n| country           = Botswana\n| year              = 2019\n| games             = African Games\n| games_link        = 2019 African Games\n| flag              = \n| flagcaption       = [[Flag of Botswana]]\n| alt               = \n| oldcode           = \n| NOCname           = [[Botswana National Olympic Committee]]\n| NPCname           = \n| CGAname           = \n| NFname            = \n| fedname           = \n| website           = \n| location          = Rabat, Morocco\n| start_date        = {{Start date|2019|08|19|df=y}}\n| end_date          = {{End date|2019|08|31|df=y}}\n| date              = \n| competitors       = 103\n| competitors_men   = 60\n| competitors_women = 43\n| sports            = 12\n| events            = \n| flagbearer        = \n| flagbearer_open   = \n| flagbearer_close  = \n| rank              = 13\n| gold              = 5\n| silver            = 3\n| bronze            = 6\n| officials         = \n| appearances       = \n| app_begin_year    = \n| app_interval      = \n| summerappearances = \n| winterappearances = \n| youthappearances  = \n| seealso           = \n| previous          = \n| next              = \n}}\n'''[[Botswana]]''' competed at the '''[[2019 African Games]]''' held from 19 to 31 August 2019 in [[Rabat]], Morocco.<ref name=\"oc_ultimate_guide\">{{cite web|url=https://www.olympicchannel.com/en/stories/features/detail/rabat-2019-morocco-african-games-preview/|title=Things you need to know about the Rabat 2019 African Games|date=27 July 2019|publisher=Olympic Channel|accessdate=27 July 2019|archive-date=27 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727185045/https://www.olympicchannel.com/en/stories/features/detail/rabat-2019-morocco-african-games-preview/|url-status=live}}</ref> In total 103 athletes represented Botswana at the games.<ref name=\"botswana_gov_to_fund\">{{cite web|url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1083304/botswana-govt-funds-african-games-preps|title=Botswana Government fund country's team to compete in African Games|date=10 August 2019|publisher=Inside the games|accessdate=10 August 2019|archive-date=10 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190810171356/https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1083304/botswana-govt-funds-african-games-preps|url-status=live}}</ref> Athletes representing Botswana won five gold medals, three silver medals and six bronze medals and the country finished in 13th place in the medal table.\n\n== Medal summary ==\n\n=== Medal table ===\n\n{{col begin}}\n| \u00a0style=\"text-align:left; width:78%; vertical-align:top;\"|\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:95%\"\n|-\n! Medal\n! Name\n! Sport\n! Event\n! Date\n|-\n| {{gold medal}} || {{sortname|Leungo|Scotch}} || [[Athletics at the 2019 African Games|Athletics]] || [[Athletics at the 2019 African Games \u2013 Men's 400 metres|Men's 400 metres]] || {{dts|28 August}}\n|-\n| {{gold medal}} || {{sortname|Galefele|Moroko}} || [[Athletics at the 2019 African Games|Athletics]] || [[Athletics at the 2019 African Games \u2013 Women's 400 metres|Women's 400 metres]] || {{dts|28 August}}\n|-\n| {{gold medal}} || [[Zibani Ngozi]]<br>[[Ditiro Nzamani]]<br>[[Onkabetse Nkobolo]]<br>[[Leungo Scotch]] || [[Athletics at the 2019 African Games|Athletics]] || [[Athletics at the 2019 African Games \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 400 metres relay|Men's 4 \u00d7 400 metres relay]] || {{dts|29 August}}\n|-\n| {{gold medal}} || {{sortname|Mohamed|Otukile}} || [[Boxing at the 2019 African Games|Boxing]] || Men's flyweight (52 kg) || {{dts|29 August}}\n|-\n| {{gold medal}} || {{sortname|Keamogetse|Kenosi}} || [[Boxing at the 2019 African Games|Boxing]] || Women's featherweight (57 kg) || {{dts|29 August}}\n|-\n| {{silver medal}} || {{sortname|