a Planeta]].\n* '''Nauka 2.0''' ''(Science 2.0)'' - blocks of programmes from [[Nauka 2.0]].\n\n=== Others ===\n* '''Feature films''' (thrillers and adventures)\n* '''90x60x90''' (entertainment)\n\n=== Sports events broadcast by channel ===\n* [[Biathlon World Cup]]\n* [[FIA Formula One World Championship]]\n* [[KHL]]\n* [[Premier League]]\n* [[Russian Premier League]]\n* [[The FA Cup]]\n* [[M-1 Global]], [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]], [[Bellator Fighting Championship|Bellator MMA]], [[ONE Championship]], and other MMA Promotions\n\n==External links==\n*[http://russia2.tv Official site]\n\n{{Television in Russia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rtr Sport}}\n[[Category:Defunct television channels in Russia]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 2010]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations disestablished in 2015]]\n[[Category:2010 establishments in Russia]]\n[[Category:2015 disestablishments in Russia]]\n[[Category:Sports television networks]]\n[[Category:Russian-language television stations]]\n[[Category:Sports television in Russia]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "broadcasted > broadcast", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russia-2"}
{"title_page": "Black the Ripper", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|British rapper and cannabis activist}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Black the Ripper\n| birth_name       = Dean West\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Blacktheripper2019.png\n| caption          = Black the Ripper, April 2019\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|df=yes|1986|12|28}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BdQPP8iFvO4/|title=Samson on Instagram: \"It's my birthday today \ud83c\udf81. You know I gotta do it properly \ud83d\udd25. 170g in 1 joint cos man can\u2019t be bothered to keep billin' it \ud83d\ude24\"|website=Instagram}}</ref>{{better source|date=April 2020}}\n| birth_place      = [[Edmonton, London|Edmonton]], London, England\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2020|4|4|1986|12|28}}\n| death_place      = St. Johns, [[Montserrat]]\n| alias            = {{flatlist|\n* Ital Samson\n* Blackaveli\n}}\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[British hip hop]]\n* [[Grime (music genre)|grime]]\n* [[political hip hop]] \n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist| \n* Rapper\n* singer\n* songwriter }}\n| instrument       = Vocals\n| years_active     = 2003\u20132020\n| label            = Dank of England (D.O.E.)\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Chip (rapper)|Chip]]|[[Akala (rapper)|Akala]]|[[Sway (Rapper)|Sway]]|[[Lowkey]]|[[Big Narstie]]|[[Popcaan]]|[[Ghetts]]|[[Frisco (rapper)|Frisco]]|[[Footsie (MC)|Footsie]]|[[Nafe Smallz]]}}\n| website          = {{Official website|https://dankofengland.net/}}\n}}\n\n'''Dean West''' (28 December 1986&nbsp;\u2013 4 April 2020), better known by his stage name '''Black the Ripper''', was a British rapper, [[grime (music genre)|grime]] MC, entrepreneur, and [[cannabis activist]] from \nEdmonton, London, England. He ran his own record label, Dank of England (formerly known as Black Magic Entertainment), which expanded into a clothing line and marijuana accessory company. He was also known for his viral stunts of smoking cannabis in public places, which he hoped would lead to the outcome of legalised [[cannabis in the United Kingdom]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kulturehub.com/black-the-ripper-weed-england/|title=Meet Black the Ripper, the English weed advocate lighting up everywhere|date=14 August 2018|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212159/https://kulturehub.com/black-the-ripper-weed-england/|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWest was one of the earliest artists to adopt the grime genre, where he gained recognition from his mixtapes ''Afro Samurai'' (2006), ''Summer Madness'' (2007), and ''Holla Black'' (2007). He was also one of the earliest artists to have been featured on the British urban music channel [[SB.TV]]. West released multiple mixtapes series during his career, most notably ''Outlaw'' and ''Black Is Beautiful''. He gained mainstream attention whilst campaigning for the legality of cannabis in the United Kingdom in 2015 with the launch of his debut EP ''Excuse Me Whilst I Kiss Sky''. He went on to release 2 more EPs: ''[[In Dank We Trust]]'' and ''Doe or Die'' before the release of his debut studio album ''[[Money Grows on Trees]]'', which was released in August 2018 via his independent label, Dank of England.\n\n==Early life ==\nWest was born to parents of [[Guyanese people|Guyanese]] and [[Montserrat|Montserratian]] descent within the north London suburb of [[Edmonton, London|Edmonton]] in 1987.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techday24.com/black-the-ripper-useless-5-quick-info-you-must-know/|title=Black the Ripper Useless: 5 Quick Info You Must Know|first=Muhammad Naeem|last=Malik|website=Techday24.com|date=7 April 2020|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407024905/https://techday24.com/black-the-ripper-useless-5-quick-info-you-must-know/|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> During his teen years he attended [[Aylward School]]; however, he dropped out at the age of 16. Although he stated that he was not really a football fan, he was a loyal supporter of [[Arsenal F.C.]] and had been since a young age as his father was also a supporter of the team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soccersouls.com/shocking-arsenal-fan-smoking-weed-at-emirates-after-fa-cup-victory/|title=SHOCKING! Arsenal Fan Smoking Weed At Emirates After FA Cup Victory|date=31 May 2015|website=Soccersouls|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407114915/https://www.soccersouls.com/shocking-arsenal-fan-smoking-weed-at-emirates-after-fa-cup-victory/|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===2003\u20132007: Career beginnings===\nWest made his music career debut in 2003 at the age of 15. He did so by participating in grime battles at pirate radio station Axe FM, where he had [[Rap battle|clashes]] against various competitors consistently. Black frequented the station with grime collectives Rowdy Squad and X Camp but it was when Axe FM owner Pabz created a clash competition that gained West considerable attention.<ref>https://www.plugsville.com/black-the-ripper-tribute/</ref> In an interview with [[MTV]], he stated that [[Tupac Shakur]], [[Biggie Smalls]], [[Mobb Deep]], [[Busta Rhymes]], [[Nas]] and [[Bob Marley]] inspired him to make music.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141011071608/http://www.mtv.co.uk/music/urban/201700-black-the-ripper-the-interview|title=BLACK THE RIPPER: THE INTERVIEW! &#124; MTV UK|date=11 October 2014|website=Web.archive.org}}</ref> When asked about his passion for making music, West declared that he had a love for music. His most notable single during this time was \"Death is Promised\" released in 2005.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2c_0dJtXfXM|title=Black The Ripper - Death Is Promised (Unreleased Video 2005)|access-date=18 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190428184950/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2c_0dJtXfXM|archive-date=28 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> West also stated that his music is inspired by historical and often political figures such as [[Malcolm X]] and [[Martin Luther King Jr.]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PjEwWzlJ47Q |title=Black The Ripper Vs Wario (AXE FM CLASHES 2005 |access-date=18 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421103058/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PjEwWzlJ47Q |archive-date=21 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He released his debut mixtape ''Motivation Music: Volume 1''<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/motivation-music-vol-1/1213105825|title=\u200eMotivation Music, Vol.1 by Black the Ripper, Chipmunk & Cookie|website=Music.apple.com|access-date=18 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222071144/https://music.apple.com/gb/album/motivation-music-vol-1/1213105825|archive-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> on New Years Day 2007, sophomore mixtape ''Motivation Music: Volume 2'' on 1 March 2007, third mixtape ''Summer Madness'' on 7 February 2007 to little success<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/summer-madness/1204674156|title=\u200eSummer Madness by Black the Ripper|website=Music.apple.com|access-date=18 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222071148/https://music.apple.com/gb/album/summer-madness/1204674156|archive-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/black-the-ripper-death-tributes_uk_5e8c2c52c5b6e1d10a6930f7|title=Black The Ripper Remembered By Skepta, Dave And Maya Jama Following His Death, Aged 32|last=Welsh|first=Daniel|date=|website=[[Huffington Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> His fourth mixtape ''Holla Black'' followed on 7 March 2007 and is now considered a classic album in the genre of [[Grime (music genre)|grime]].<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/holla-black/1206190044|title=\u200eHolla Black by Black the Ripper|website=Music.apple.com|access-date=18 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301232911/https://music.apple.com/gb/album/holla-black/1206190044|archive-date=1 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref>https://www.thelinkup.com/content/1275/throwbackthursday-looking-back-at-black-the-ripper-s-classic-holla-bla</ref>\n\n===2008\u20132012: Rise to fame===\nWest was one of the earliest artists to record for [[SB.TV]], having released numerous freestyles and bars session alongside ASB, [[Chip (rapper)|Chip]], [[Ghetts]] amongst others. Many of these freestyles were compiled and put on his debut [[compilation album]] ''The Edmonton Dream'', released on 28 December 2009. The album contained 60 tracks with features from numerous grime MC's including [[DJ Ironik]], [[Wiley (musician)|Wiley]] and [[Chip (rapper)|Chip]], amongst others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/the-edmonton-dream/340175565|title=\u200eThe Edmonton Dream by Black the Ripper|website=Music.apple.com|access-date=18 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222072704/https://music.apple.com/gb/album/the-edmonton-dream/340175565|archive-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dankledankledankle.wordpress.com/2009/12/24/black-the-ripper-the-edmonton-dream-60-tracks/|title=Black The Ripper \u2013 The Edmonton Dream (60 Tracks)|date=24 December 2009|access-date=18 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200218215321/https://dankledankledankle.wordpress.com/2009/12/24/black-the-ripper-the-edmonton-dream-60-tracks/|archive-date=18 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe was featured on the [[All-star|All Stars]] remix of the single \"SB.TV\" by Flexplicit and [[Royce da 5'9\"]] alongside [[Lady Leshurr]], [[Mic Righteous]] & Shotty released on January 2011.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eE_otbKM-28 |title=Archived copy |access-date=18 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200122200611/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eE_otbKM-28 |archive-date=22 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> During the time of the [[2011 London riot]], West spoke out on the scenario, asserting how he didn't support it, stating that those who weren't living in affected areas, had no right to comment on the riots, and that the action of those involved was selfish and inconsiderate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dummymag.com/news/grime-artists-respond-to-london-riots/|title=The music world responds to the London riots on Twitter|website=DummyMag|access-date=3 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303183802/https://www.dummymag.com/news/grime-artists-respond-to-london-riots/|archive-date=3 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He released his sixth mixtape ''Outlaw: Volume 1'' on 28 March 2011 with vocal features from [[Wiley (musician)|Wiley]], [[Frisco (rapper)|Frisco]] and more.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Black-The-Ripper-Outlaw-Volume-One/release/5604281|title=Black The Ripper - Outlaw Volume One|website=Discogs|access-date=18 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190616212234/https://www.discogs.com/Black-The-Ripper-Outlaw-Volume-One/release/5604281|archive-date=16 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Black is Beautiful: Volume 1', which was initially released in 2005, was made available for digital download the same day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/black-is-beautiful/1208330479|title=\u200eBlack Is Beautiful by Black the Ripper|via=music.apple.com|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407123322/https://music.apple.com/gb/album/black-is-beautiful/1208330479|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\nWest performed at A Day In Dam with English Frank and [[Big Narstie]] in 2013 and the Hip Hop Kemp Festival in Czech Republic.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lineup for Hip Hop Kemp 2013 |url=http://magazine.ilikemusic.com/Hip_Hop_Kemp_2013 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140320165351/http://magazine.ilikemusic.com/Hip_Hop_Kemp_2013 |url-status=dead |archive-date=20 March 2014 |website=Archive.is|accessdate=18 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe following year he released three more mixtapes. This includes his eighth; ''Married to Marijuana'' which included 13 tracks of his love to marijuana, and the compilation album ''Unreleased S**t: Volume 3''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/married-to-marijuana/1213058445|title=\u200eMarried to Marijuana by Black the Ripper|via=music.apple.com|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229160314/https://music.apple.com/gb/album/married-to-marijuana/1213058445|archive-date=29 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/unreleased-s-t-vol-3/1213059379|title=\u200eUnreleased S**t, Vol. 3 by Black the Ripper|via=music.apple.com|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407123959/https://music.apple.com/gb/album/unreleased-s-t-vol-3/1213059379|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> His tenth mixtape; ''Black Is Beautiful: Volume 2'' was released on 31 October 2012. The 13 track mixtape, contained features from [[Dot Rotten]], Loudmouth, [[Shystie]], amongst others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://linkuptvofficial.bandcamp.com/album/black-is-beautiful-vol-2|title=Black Is Beautiful Vol. 2, by Black The Ripper|website=Link Up|access-date=18 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200218215408/https://linkuptvofficial.bandcamp.com/album/black-is-beautiful-vol-2|archive-date=18 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2013\u20132016: Excuse Me Whilst I Kiss Sky===\n[[File:BlacktheRipper2015.png|thumb|left|Black the Ripper on stage with Iron Barz]]\nRipper's 11th mixtape, ''High End Weed Music'' was a joint effort with Iron Barz and was released on 20 April 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/high-end-weed-music/1200249854|title=\u200eHigh End Weed Music by Black the Ripper & Iron Barz|via=music.apple.com|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407123141/https://music.apple.com/gb/album/high-end-weed-music/1200249854|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was his second work to be dedicated to cannabis culture. On 29 August 2014, West released the second installment to his [[Political hip hop]] mixtape series ''Outlaw''. Volume 2 contained features from [[Lowkey]], [[Akala (rapper)|Akala]], [[Jaja Soze]], Benny Banks and more.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/outlaw-vol-2/895114667|title=\u200eOutlaw, Vol. 2 by Black the Ripper|via=music.apple.com|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223063232/https://music.apple.com/gb/album/outlaw-vol-2/895114667|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> ''High End 2'' followed on 14 December 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/high-end-2/935318574|title=\u200eHigh End 2 by Black the Ripper & Iron Barz|via=music.apple.com|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223063230/https://music.apple.com/gb/album/high-end-2/935318574|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWest released his debut EP titled ''Excuse Me Whilst I Kiss Sky''. The seven-track EP was released on 4 May 2015 and featured vocal appearances from Iron Barz, L Skinz, and Jyager.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/excuse-me-while-i-kiss-the-sky/1207552533|title=\u200eExcuse Me While I Kiss the Sky by Black the Ripper|via=music.apple.com|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407163608/https://music.apple.com/us/album/excuse-me-while-i-kiss-the-sky/1207552533|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Black gained national recognition for a viral stunt with [[Trollstation]] to create a music video on the [[London Eye]] at [[420 (cannabis culture)|4:20 pm]], where they filmed each other smoking and dancing inside the enclosure on November 2016.<ref name=\"auto5\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/everything-you-need-know-trollstation-9343999|title=Trollstation have a long history of taking pranks to the absolute limit|first1=James|last1=Caven|first2=Greg|last2=Wilford|first3=Suchandrika|last3=Chakrabarti|date=26 November 2016|website=mirror|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217215310/https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/everything-you-need-know-trollstation-9343999|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2016/04/21/someone-hotboxed-a-pod-on-the-london-eye-for-420-5830705/|title=Someone hotboxed a pod on the London Eye for 4/20|date=21 April 2016|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212159/https://metro.co.uk/2016/04/21/someone-hotboxed-a-pod-on-the-london-eye-for-420-5830705/|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> West released a \"Weed Remix\" of ''[[Uber Everywhere]]'' entitled \"Light Up Everywhere\" in April 2016.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6PB2chqwFjc|title=Black The Ripper - Light Up Everywhere|website=YouTube|language=en|accessdate=18 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225032434/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6PB2chqwFjc|archive-date=25 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2017\u20132020: ''Money Grows on Trees''===\n[[File:BigNarstieBlackTheRipper.jpg|thumb|Black the Ripper (right) with [[Big Narstie]]]]\nWest was featured on Benny Banks and [[Joe Black]]'s collaborative mixtape ''BNB'' released in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2017/11/benny-banks-joe-black-bnb|title=Benny Banks And Joe Black Release Long-Awaited 'BNB' Mixtape|website=Complex|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212158/https://www.complex.com/music/2017/11/benny-banks-joe-black-bnb|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> West made national headlines again on 20 April 2017 ([[420 (cannabis culture)|420]]) when he was smoking cannabis whilst a [[police officer]] posed for a selfie with him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailystar.co.uk/news/latest-news/cannabis-weed-marijuana-420-day-17014504|title=Police officer poses for SELFIE with rapper smoking WEED at London cannabis fest|first=Nicholas|last=Bieber|date=21 April 2017|website=Dailystar.co.uk|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212202/https://www.dailystar.co.uk/news/latest-news/cannabis-weed-marijuana-420-day-17014504|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In celebration of 420, West released a surprise EP titled ''[[In Dank We Trust]]''.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Black-The-Ripper-In-Dank-We-Trust/release/10191448|title=Black The Ripper - In Dank We Trust|website=Discogs|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190616212232/https://www.discogs.com/Black-The-Ripper-In-Dank-We-Trust/release/10191448|archive-date=16 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Another independently released album, West enlisted Iron Barz, Stoner, [[Footsie (MC)|Footsie]] and others to provide vocal features on the album. On 1 October 2017, West released his second EP ''Doe or Die: Volume 1''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.itunescharts.net/uk/artists/music/black-the-ripper/albums/doe-or-die-vol-1/|title=iTunesCharts.net: 'Doe or Die, Vol. 1' by Black the Ripper (British Albums iTunes Chart)|website=www.itunescharts.net|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407171502/http://www.itunescharts.net/uk/artists/music/black-the-ripper/albums/doe-or-die-vol-1/|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> West strategically sold the album at a price of \u00a34.20, in light of the cannabis culture once again.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dankofengland.net/products/doe-or-die-vol-1-cd|title=DOE Or Die Vol 1 CD|website=Dank Of England Official|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407200154/https://dankofengland.net/products/doe-or-die-vol-1-cd|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, West released the single \"Bill It\", with vocal features from [[Big Narstie]], [[Chip (rapper)|Chip]] and Smasher.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://respect-mag.com/2018/07/black-the-ripper-big-narstie-chip-bill-it/|title=Black The Ripper, Big Narstie, Chip & Smasher Light Up in \"Bill It\" Visual|date=16 July 2018|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212202/https://respect-mag.com/2018/07/black-the-ripper-big-narstie-chip-bill-it/|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> West made an appearance on the single ''Marijuana'' by Chip and [[Mist (rapper)|Mist]], a song that was voted as one of the best grime songs of 2018 by [[Capital XTRA]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.capitalxtra.com/playlists/best-2018/uk-grime-hip-hop-songs/|title=The Best Grime & UK Hip Hop Songs Of 2018|website=Capital XTRA|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212159/https://www.capitalxtra.com/playlists/best-2018/uk-grime-hip-hop-songs/|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://respect-mag.com/2018/09/big-narstie-shizzio-panjabi-mc/|title=Big Narstie Connects with Shizzio & Panjabi MC for \"How You Dance\" Visual|date=2 September 2018|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212158/https://respect-mag.com/2018/09/big-narstie-shizzio-panjabi-mc/|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The single went on to be the lead single on his new project; ''[[Money Grows on Trees]]'' released in August 2018. His love of marijuana is a running theme throughout the album. The album opens with the song \"My Name is Black The Ripper\" in which West introduces his persona to new fans over a few seconds long intro. The song acts as a quick introduction to the artist before the start of the album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/black-the-ripper-money-grows-on-trees|title=Black the Ripper - Money Grows on Trees|website=[[GRM Daily]] - Grime, Rap music and Culture|access-date=18 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200218211628/http://grmdaily.com/black-the-ripper-money-grows-on-trees|archive-date=18 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> West's Money Grows on Trees has been cited as an influence to the new generation of UK rap, including Capo Lee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/02/capo-lee-interview|title=Meet Capo Lee, The North London Emcee With Grime In His Bones|website=Complex|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212200/https://www.complex.com/music/2018/02/capo-lee-interview|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019, West performed at the Colours Community Festival held in February.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theguideliverpool.com/colours-community-festival-is-back-this-saturday-at-princes-park/|title=Colours Community Festival is back this Saturday at Princes Park|date=31 July 2019|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212202/https://theguideliverpool.com/colours-community-festival-is-back-this-saturday-at-princes-park/|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Durung that time he announced that he was working on the sequel to his last EP ''Doe or Die''. Shortly after, it was announced that ''Doe or Die: Volume 2'' would be released on 12 October 2019. The album was another collaborative effort with Iron Barz.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/5C4Ddj8jZQwB0c4k1Boe88|title=Doe Or Die, Vol. 2|via=open.spotify.com|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212207/https://open.spotify.com/album/5C4Ddj8jZQwB0c4k1Boe88|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Ventures==\n===Dank of England (D.O.E.)===\n\nIn 2015, West launched his own company known as Dank of England (D.O.E.). Dank of England runs as an [[independent record label]] and produces a clothing line, as well as smoking accessories.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dankofengland.net/|title=Shop &#124; Dank Of England &#124; DOE Gang|website=Dank Of England Official|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212159/https://dankofengland.net/|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It runs as a reboot of his former independent label, Black Magic Entertainment. The launch has been very successful, and alongside co-founder and partner; Screechtree, the pair had been running pop-up shops on a seasonal basis since 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/black-rippers-business-partner-pays-21825692|title=Black the Ripper's business partner's tribute as mystery shrouds cause of death|first=Verity|last=Sulway|date=7 April 2020|website=mirror|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407083106/https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/black-rippers-business-partner-pays-21825692|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cambstimes.co.uk/news/black-ripper-dank-england-march-1-5668292|title=UK rap artist Black The Ripper holds a pop up shop in March as part of a UK tour talking to people about legalising cannabis|first=Kath|last=Sansom|website=Cambs Times|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212158/https://www.cambstimes.co.uk/news/black-ripper-dank-england-march-1-5668292|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dankofengland.net/pages/pop-ups|title=Pop Ups|website=Dank Of England Official|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212201/https://dankofengland.net/pages/pop-ups|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Black gained national recognition for a viral stunt with [[Trollstation]] to create a music video on the [[London Eye]] at [[420 (cannabis culture)|4:20pm]], where they filmed each other smoking and dancing inside the enclosure on November 2016.<ref name=\"auto5\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/> Black's D.O.E. was noted for being \"the most pro-cannabis and British a company can get\" by ''[[The Irish News]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.irishnews.com/magazine/2017/01/12/news/how-drugs-have-found-their-way-into-fashion-882225/|title=How drugs have found their way into fashion|date=12 January 2017|website=The Irish News}}</ref> During this time West was featured in [[Vice (magazine)|''Vice'']]'s documentary; ''How Weed Laws are Failing the UK'' released on 24 October 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://video.vice.com/en_us/video/how-decriminalization-has-shaped-britains-weed-culture/57a1ccea7d44272540c4391e|title=How Weed Laws Are Failing the UK|website=Video|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190811225339/https://video.vice.com/en_us/video/how-decriminalization-has-shaped-britains-weed-culture/57a1ccea7d44272540c4391e|archive-date=11 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> West credited his weed smoking as an influence on his business success and that his stunts were a form of activism to legalise weed. [[EasyJet UK|EasyJet]] banned Black for smoking on the plane to which he responded \"I prefer [[RyanAir]] anyways.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/london/blog/the-big-smoke-how-would-legalising-cannabis-change-london-110217|title=The Big Smoke: how would legalising cannabis change London?|website=Time Out London|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212200/https://www.timeout.com/london/blog/the-big-smoke-how-would-legalising-cannabis-change-london-110217|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Black also smoked weed in his local [[Asda]] store.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://consent.yahoo.com/collectConsent?sessionId=1_cc-session_916b7bf9-09de-4cd1-8c8b-a3dc383149ca&lang=en-gb&inline=false|title=HuffPost is now a part of Verizon Media|website=consent.yahoo.com}}</ref> West released a \"Weed Remix\" of ''[[Uber Everywhere]]'' entitled \"Light Up Everywhere\" in April 2016<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\n==Death==\nIt was reported that West died on 4 April 2020 while on holiday in [[Montserrat]]. According to sources, he was found dead in the vacation home he was staying in.<ref>https://loudnewsnet.com/uk-rapper-and-cannabis-activist-black-the-ripper-dead-at-32/</ref> His cause of death is currently unconfirmed.<ref>{{cite web |title=British Grime Legend Black The Ripper Dead At 32 |url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/04/black-the-ripper-dead-at-32 |website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |date=6 April 2020 |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407004408/https://www.complex.com/music/2020/04/black-the-ripper-dead-at-32 |archive-date=7 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The following day an autopsy was ordered by a coroner and the Royal Montserrat Police launched a full investigation into the cause of his death.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/07/black-ripper-autopsy-ordered-montserrat-rapper-dies-aged-32-12522345/|title=Black The Ripper autopsy ordered after rapper dies aged 32|date=7 April 2020|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407195625/https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/07/black-ripper-autopsy-ordered-montserrat-rapper-dies-aged-32-12522345/|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Aftermath===\nLongtime collaborators [[Chip (rapper)|Chip]], [[Lowkey]] and [[Ghetts]] were among those who paid tribute to West, as well as [[Novelist (MC)|Novelist]], [[Skepta]], [[Krept (rapper)|Krept]], [[Lethal Bizzle]], [[Michael Dapaah]], [[Yungen]], [[Nadia Rose]], [[AJ Tracey]] and [[Ambush (rapper)|Ambush]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |first=Will |last=Lavin |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/tributes-paid-to-uk-rapper-black-the-ripper-who-has-died-at-32-2642072 |title=Tributes paid to UK rapper Black The Ripper, who has died at 32 |magazine=[[NME]] |date=6 April 2020 |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> Musician [[Jammer (MC)|Jammer]] released a tribute single titled \"Hope Dealers\" in light of the death of West. The single was co-produced by Jammer and Skully with Jammer delivering downtempo lyrics.<ref>https://www.complex.com/music/2020/04/jammer-hope-dealers-black-the-ripper-tribute</ref> In light of the [[420 (cannabis culture)|cannabis culture]], Chip released a tribute titled \"0420\" for Black the Ripper on 20 April, 2020. The tribute sampled Black the Ripper's classic single \"Missing You\".<ref>http://grmdaily.com/video/chip-0420-rip-black-the-ripper</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Black the Ripper discography}}\n===Studio albums===\n*2018: ''[[Money Grows on Trees]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/black-the-ripper-money-grows-on-trees|title=Black the Ripper - Money Grows on Trees|website=[[GRM Daily]]|access-date=18 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200218211628/http://grmdaily.com/black-the-ripper-money-grows-on-trees|archive-date=18 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Extended plays===\n*2015: ''Excuse Me Whilst I Kiss Sky''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kkbox.com/sg/en/album/VeuyF037.BcQu0F1NPo.009H-index.html|title=Excuse Me While I Kiss the Sky|via=www.kkbox.com|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407194244/https://www.kkbox.com/sg/en/album/VeuyF037.BcQu0F1NPo.009H-index.html|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*2017: ''[[In Dank We Trust]]''<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n*2017: ''Doe or Die: Volume 1''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/Black-the-ripper-doe-or-die-lyrics|title=Black The Ripper (Ft. Iron Barz) \u2013 Doe or Die|via=genius.com|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407194154/https://genius.com/Black-the-ripper-doe-or-die-lyrics|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*2019: ''Doe or Die: Volume 2''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kkbox.com/sg/en/album/9WyugiRBxUCUG0F3o71A009H-index.html|title=Doe Or Die, Vol. 2|via=[[KKBox]]|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407194250/https://www.kkbox.com/sg/en/album/9WyugiRBxUCUG0F3o71A009H-index.html|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://dankofengland.net/}}\n{{Sister project links |wikt=no |commons=Category:Black the Ripper |b=no |n=Black the Ripper |q=Black the Ripper |s=no |v=no |species=no |d=Q85438609 |display=Black the Ripper}}\n{{Portal|Cannabis}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Black British male rappers]]\n[[Category:British people of Montserratian descent]]\n[[Category:Cannabis activists]]\n[[Category:English male rappers]]\n[[Category:Grime music artists]]\n[[Category:People from Edmonton, London]]\n[[Category:Political activists]]\n[[Category:Rappers from London]]\n[[Category:English people of Guyanese descent]]\n[[Category:Cannabis music]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|British rapper and cannabis activist}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Black the Ripper\n| birth_name       = Dean West\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Blacktheripper2019.png\n| caption          = Black the Ripper, April 2019\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|df=yes|1986|12|28}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BdQPP8iFvO4/|title=Samson on Instagram: \"It's my birthday today \ud83c\udf81. You know I gotta do it properly \ud83d\udd25. 170g in 1 joint cos man can\u2019t be bothered to keep billin' it \ud83d\ude24\"|website=Instagram}}</ref>{{better source|date=April 2020}}\n| birth_place      = [[Edmonton, London|Edmonton]], London, England\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2020|4|4|1986|12|28}}\n| death_place      = St. Johns, [[Montserrat]]\n| alias            = {{flatlist|\n* Ital Samson\n* Blackaveli\n}}\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[British hip hop]]\n* [[Grime (music genre)|grime]]\n* [[political hip hop]] \n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist| \n* Rapper\n* singer\n* songwriter }}\n| instrument       = Vocals\n| years_active     = 2003\u20132020\n| label            = Dank of England (D.O.E.)\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Chip (rapper)|Chip]]|[[Akala (rapper)|Akala]]|[[Sway (Rapper)|Sway]]|[[Lowkey]]|[[Big Narstie]]|[[Popcaan]]|[[Ghetts]]|[[Frisco (rapper)|Frisco]]|[[Footsie (MC)|Footsie]]|[[Nafe Smallz]]}}\n| website          = {{Official website|https://dankofengland.net/}}\n}}\n\n'''Dean West''' (28 December 1986&nbsp;\u2013 4 April 2020), better known by his stage name '''Black the Ripper''', was a British rapper, [[grime (music genre)|grime]] MC, entrepreneur, and [[cannabis activist]] from \nEdmonton, London, England. He ran his own record label, Dank of England (formerly known as Black Magic Entertainment), which expanded into a clothing line and marijuana accessory company. He was also known for his viral stunts of smoking cannabis in public places, which he hoped would lead to the outcome of legalised [[cannabis in the United Kingdom]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kulturehub.com/black-the-ripper-weed-england/|title=Meet Black the Ripper, the English weed advocate lighting up everywhere|date=14 August 2018|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212159/https://kulturehub.com/black-the-ripper-weed-england/|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWest was one of the earliest artists to adopt the grime genre, where he gained recognition from his mixtapes ''Afro Samurai'' (2006), ''Summer Madness'' (2007), and ''Holla Black'' (2007). He was also one of the earliest artists to have been featured on the British urban music channel [[SB.TV]]. West released multiple mixtapes series during his career, most notably ''Outlaw'' and ''Black Is Beautiful''. He gained mainstream attention whilst campaigning for the legality of cannabis in the United Kingdom in 2015 with the launch of his debut EP ''Excuse Me Whilst I Kiss Sky''. He went on to release 2 more EPs: ''[[In Dank We Trust]]'' and ''Doe or Die'' before the release of his debut studio album ''[[Money Grows on Trees]]'', which was released in August 2018 via his independent label, Dank of England.\n\n==Early life ==\nWest was born to parents of [[Guyanese people|Guyanese]] and [[Montserrat|Montserratian]] descent within the north London suburb of [[Edmonton, London|Edmonton]] in 1987.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techday24.com/black-the-ripper-useless-5-quick-info-you-must-know/|title=Black the Ripper Useless: 5 Quick Info You Must Know|first=Muhammad Naeem|last=Malik|website=Techday24.com|date=7 April 2020|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407024905/https://techday24.com/black-the-ripper-useless-5-quick-info-you-must-know/|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> During his teen years he attended [[Aylward School]]; however, he dropped out at the age of 16. Although he stated that he was not really a football fan, he was a loyal supporter of [[Arsenal F.C.]] and had been since a young age as his father was also a supporter of the team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soccersouls.com/shocking-arsenal-fan-smoking-weed-at-emirates-after-fa-cup-victory/|title=SHOCKING! Arsenal Fan Smoking Weed At Emirates After FA Cup Victory|date=31 May 2015|website=Soccersouls|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407114915/https://www.soccersouls.com/shocking-arsenal-fan-smoking-weed-at-emirates-after-fa-cup-victory/|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===2003\u20132007: Career beginnings===\nWest made his music career debut in 2003 at the age of 15. He did so by participating in grime battles at pirate radio station Axe FM, where he had [[Rap battle|clashes]] against various competitors consistently. Black frequented the station with grime collectives Rowdy Squad and X Camp but it was when Axe FM owner Pabz created a clash competition that gained West considerable attention.<ref>https://www.plugsville.com/black-the-ripper-tribute/</ref> In an interview with [[MTV]], he stated that [[Tupac Shakur]], [[Biggie Smalls]], [[Mobb Deep]], [[Busta Rhymes]], [[Nas]] and [[Bob Marley]] inspired him to make music.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141011071608/http://www.mtv.co.uk/music/urban/201700-black-the-ripper-the-interview|title=BLACK THE RIPPER: THE INTERVIEW! &#124; MTV UK|date=11 October 2014|website=Web.archive.org}}</ref> When asked about his passion for making music, West declared that he had a love for music. His most notable single during this time was \"Death is Promised\" released in 2005.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2c_0dJtXfXM|title=Black The Ripper - Death Is Promised (Unreleased Video 2005)|access-date=18 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190428184950/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2c_0dJtXfXM|archive-date=28 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> West also stated that his music is inspired by historical and often political figures such as [[Malcolm X]] and [[Martin Luther King Jr.]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PjEwWzlJ47Q |title=Black The Ripper Vs Wario (AXE FM CLASHES 2005 |access-date=18 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421103058/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PjEwWzlJ47Q |archive-date=21 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He released his debut mixtape ''Motivation Music: Volume 1''<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/motivation-music-vol-1/1213105825|title=\u200eMotivation Music, Vol.1 by Black the Ripper, Chipmunk & Cookie|website=Music.apple.com|access-date=18 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222071144/https://music.apple.com/gb/album/motivation-music-vol-1/1213105825|archive-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> on New Years Day 2007, sophomore mixtape ''Motivation Music: Volume 2'' on 1 March 2007, third mixtape ''Summer Madness'' on 7 February 2007 to little success<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/summer-madness/1204674156|title=\u200eSummer Madness by Black the Ripper|website=Music.apple.com|access-date=18 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222071148/https://music.apple.com/gb/album/summer-madness/1204674156|archive-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/black-the-ripper-death-tributes_uk_5e8c2c52c5b6e1d10a6930f7|title=Black The Ripper Remembered By Skepta, Dave And Maya Jama Following His Death, Aged 32|last=Welsh|first=Daniel|date=|website=[[Huffington Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> His fourth mixtape ''Holla Black'' followed on 7 March 2007 and is now considered a classic album in the genre of [[Grime (music genre)|grime]].<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/holla-black/1206190044|title=\u200eHolla Black by Black the Ripper|website=Music.apple.com|access-date=18 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301232911/https://music.apple.com/gb/album/holla-black/1206190044|archive-date=1 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref>https://www.thelinkup.com/content/1275/throwbackthursday-looking-back-at-black-the-ripper-s-classic-holla-bla</ref>\n\n===2008\u20132012: Rise to fame===\nWest was one of the earliest artists to record for [[SB.TV]], having released numerous freestyles and bars session alongside ASB, [[Chip (rapper)|Chip]], [[Ghetts]] amongst others. Many of these freestyles were compiled and put on his debut [[compilation album]] ''The Edmonton Dream'', released on 28 December 2009. The album contained 60 tracks with features from numerous grime MC's including [[DJ Ironik]], [[Wiley (musician)|Wiley]] and [[Chip (rapper)|Chip]], amongst others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/the-edmonton-dream/340175565|title=\u200eThe Edmonton Dream by Black the Ripper|website=Music.apple.com|access-date=18 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222072704/https://music.apple.com/gb/album/the-edmonton-dream/340175565|archive-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dankledankledankle.wordpress.com/2009/12/24/black-the-ripper-the-edmonton-dream-60-tracks/|title=Black The Ripper \u2013 The Edmonton Dream (60 Tracks)|date=24 December 2009|access-date=18 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200218215321/https://dankledankledankle.wordpress.com/2009/12/24/black-the-ripper-the-edmonton-dream-60-tracks/|archive-date=18 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe was featured on the [[All-star|All Stars]] remix of the single \"SB.TV\" by Flexplicit and [[Royce da 5'9\"]] alongside [[Lady Leshurr]], [[Mic Righteous]] & Shotty released on January 2011.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eE_otbKM-28 |title=Archived copy |access-date=18 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200122200611/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eE_otbKM-28 |archive-date=22 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> During the time of the [[2011 London riot]], West spoke out on the scenario, asserting how he didn't support it, stating that those who weren't living in affected areas, had no right to comment on the riots, and that the action of those involved was selfish and inconsiderate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dummymag.com/news/grime-artists-respond-to-london-riots/|title=The music world responds to the London riots on Twitter|website=DummyMag|access-date=3 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303183802/https://www.dummymag.com/news/grime-artists-respond-to-london-riots/|archive-date=3 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He released his sixth mixtape ''Outlaw: Volume 1'' on 28 March 2011 with vocal features from [[Wiley (musician)|Wiley]], [[Frisco (rapper)|Frisco]] and more.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Black-The-Ripper-Outlaw-Volume-One/release/5604281|title=Black The Ripper - Outlaw Volume One|website=Discogs|access-date=18 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190616212234/https://www.discogs.com/Black-The-Ripper-Outlaw-Volume-One/release/5604281|archive-date=16 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Black is Beautiful: Volume 1', which was initially released in 2005, was made available for digital download the same day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/black-is-beautiful/1208330479|title=\u200eBlack Is Beautiful by Black the Ripper|via=music.apple.com|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407123322/https://music.apple.com/gb/album/black-is-beautiful/1208330479|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\nWest performed at A Day In Dam with English Frank and [[Big Narstie]] in 2013 and the Hip Hop Kemp Festival in Czech Republic.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lineup for Hip Hop Kemp 2013 |url=http://magazine.ilikemusic.com/Hip_Hop_Kemp_2013 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140320165351/http://magazine.ilikemusic.com/Hip_Hop_Kemp_2013 |url-status=dead |archive-date=20 March 2014 |website=Archive.is|accessdate=18 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe following year he released three more mixtapes. This includes his eighth; ''Married to Marijuana'' which included 13 tracks of his love to marijuana, and the compilation album ''Unreleased S**t: Volume 3''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/married-to-marijuana/1213058445|title=\u200eMarried to Marijuana by Black the Ripper|via=music.apple.com|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229160314/https://music.apple.com/gb/album/married-to-marijuana/1213058445|archive-date=29 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/unreleased-s-t-vol-3/1213059379|title=\u200eUnreleased S**t, Vol. 3 by Black the Ripper|via=music.apple.com|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407123959/https://music.apple.com/gb/album/unreleased-s-t-vol-3/1213059379|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> His tenth mixtape; ''Black Is Beautiful: Volume 2'' was released on 31 October 2012. The 13 track mixtape, contained features from [[Dot Rotten]], Loudmouth, [[Shystie]], amongst others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://linkuptvofficial.bandcamp.com/album/black-is-beautiful-vol-2|title=Black Is Beautiful Vol. 2, by Black The Ripper|website=Link Up|access-date=18 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200218215408/https://linkuptvofficial.bandcamp.com/album/black-is-beautiful-vol-2|archive-date=18 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2013\u20132016: Excuse Me Whilst I Kiss Sky===\n[[File:BlacktheRipper2015.png|thumb|left|Black the Ripper on stage with Iron Barz]]\nRipper's 11th mixtape, ''High End Weed Music'' was a joint effort with Iron Barz and was released on 20 April 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/high-end-weed-music/1200249854|title=\u200eHigh End Weed Music by Black the Ripper & Iron Barz|via=music.apple.com|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407123141/https://music.apple.com/gb/album/high-end-weed-music/1200249854|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was his second work to be dedicated to cannabis culture. On 29 August 2014, West released the second installment to his [[Political hip hop]] mixtape series ''Outlaw''. Volume 2 contained features from [[Lowkey]], [[Akala (rapper)|Akala]], [[Jaja Soze]], Benny Banks and more.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/outlaw-vol-2/895114667|title=\u200eOutlaw, Vol. 2 by Black the Ripper|via=music.apple.com|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223063232/https://music.apple.com/gb/album/outlaw-vol-2/895114667|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> ''High End 2'' followed on 14 December 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/high-end-2/935318574|title=\u200eHigh End 2 by Black the Ripper & Iron Barz|via=music.apple.com|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223063230/https://music.apple.com/gb/album/high-end-2/935318574|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWest released his debut EP titled ''Excuse Me Whilst I Kiss Sky''. The seven-track EP was released on 4 May 2015 and featured vocal appearances from Iron Barz, L Skinz, and Jyager.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/excuse-me-while-i-kiss-the-sky/1207552533|title=\u200eExcuse Me While I Kiss the Sky by Black the Ripper|via=music.apple.com|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407163608/https://music.apple.com/us/album/excuse-me-while-i-kiss-the-sky/1207552533|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Black gained national recognition for a viral stunt with [[Trollstation]] to create a music video on the [[London Eye]] at [[420 (cannabis culture)|4:20 pm]], where they filmed each other smoking and dancing inside the enclosure on November 2016.<ref name=\"auto5\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/everything-you-need-know-trollstation-9343999|title=Trollstation have a long history of taking pranks to the absolute limit|first1=James|last1=Caven|first2=Greg|last2=Wilford|first3=Suchandrika|last3=Chakrabarti|date=26 November 2016|website=mirror|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217215310/https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/everything-you-need-know-trollstation-9343999|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2016/04/21/someone-hotboxed-a-pod-on-the-london-eye-for-420-5830705/|title=Someone hotboxed a pod on the London Eye for 4/20|date=21 April 2016|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212159/https://metro.co.uk/2016/04/21/someone-hotboxed-a-pod-on-the-london-eye-for-420-5830705/|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> West released a \"Weed Remix\" of ''[[Uber Everywhere]]'' entitled \"Light Up Everywhere\" in April 2016.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6PB2chqwFjc|title=Black The Ripper - Light Up Everywhere|website=YouTube|language=en|accessdate=18 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225032434/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6PB2chqwFjc|archive-date=25 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2017\u20132020: ''Money Grows on Trees''===\n[[File:BigNarstieBlackTheRipper.jpg|thumb|Black the Ripper (right) with [[Big Narstie]]]]\nWest was featured on Benny Banks and [[Joe Black]]'s collaborative mixtape ''BNB'' released in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2017/11/benny-banks-joe-black-bnb|title=Benny Banks And Joe Black Release Long-Awaited 'BNB' Mixtape|website=Complex|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212158/https://www.complex.com/music/2017/11/benny-banks-joe-black-bnb|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> West made national headlines again on 20 April 2017 ([[420 (cannabis culture)|420]]) when he was smoking cannabis whilst a [[police officer]] posed for a selfie with him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailystar.co.uk/news/latest-news/cannabis-weed-marijuana-420-day-17014504|title=Police officer poses for SELFIE with rapper smoking WEED at London cannabis fest|first=Nicholas|last=Bieber|date=21 April 2017|website=Dailystar.co.uk|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212202/https://www.dailystar.co.uk/news/latest-news/cannabis-weed-marijuana-420-day-17014504|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In celebration of 420, West released a surprise EP titled ''[[In Dank We Trust]]''.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Black-The-Ripper-In-Dank-We-Trust/release/10191448|title=Black The Ripper - In Dank We Trust|website=Discogs|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190616212232/https://www.discogs.com/Black-The-Ripper-In-Dank-We-Trust/release/10191448|archive-date=16 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Another independently released album, West enlisted Iron Barz, Stoner, [[Footsie (MC)|Footsie]] and others to provide vocal features on the album. On 1 October 2017, West released his second EP ''Doe or Die: Volume 1''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.itunescharts.net/uk/artists/music/black-the-ripper/albums/doe-or-die-vol-1/|title=iTunesCharts.net: 'Doe or Die, Vol. 1' by Black the Ripper (British Albums iTunes Chart)|website=www.itunescharts.net|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407171502/http://www.itunescharts.net/uk/artists/music/black-the-ripper/albums/doe-or-die-vol-1/|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> West strategically sold the album at a price of \u00a34.20, in light of the cannabis culture once again.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dankofengland.net/products/doe-or-die-vol-1-cd|title=DOE Or Die Vol 1 CD|website=Dank Of England Official|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407200154/https://dankofengland.net/products/doe-or-die-vol-1-cd|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, West released the single \"Bill It\", with vocal features from [[Big Narstie]], [[Chip (rapper)|Chip]] and Smasher.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://respect-mag.com/2018/07/black-the-ripper-big-narstie-chip-bill-it/|title=Black The Ripper, Big Narstie, Chip & Smasher Light Up in \"Bill It\" Visual|date=16 July 2018|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212202/https://respect-mag.com/2018/07/black-the-ripper-big-narstie-chip-bill-it/|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> West made an appearance on the single ''Marijuana'' by Chip and [[Mist (rapper)|Mist]], a song that was voted as one of the best grime songs of 2018 by [[Capital XTRA]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.capitalxtra.com/playlists/best-2018/uk-grime-hip-hop-songs/|title=The Best Grime & UK Hip Hop Songs Of 2018|website=Capital XTRA|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212159/https://www.capitalxtra.com/playlists/best-2018/uk-grime-hip-hop-songs/|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://respect-mag.com/2018/09/big-narstie-shizzio-panjabi-mc/|title=Big Narstie Connects with Shizzio & Panjabi MC for \"How You Dance\" Visual|date=2 September 2018|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212158/https://respect-mag.com/2018/09/big-narstie-shizzio-panjabi-mc/|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The single went on to be the lead single on his new project; ''[[Money Grows on Trees]]'' released in August 2018. His love of marijuana is a running theme throughout the album. The album opens with the song \"My Name is Black The Ripper\" in which West introduces his persona to new fans over a few seconds long intro. The song acts as a quick introduction to the artist before the start of the album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/black-the-ripper-money-grows-on-trees|title=Black the Ripper - Money Grows on Trees|website=[[GRM Daily]] - Grime, Rap music and Culture|access-date=18 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200218211628/http://grmdaily.com/black-the-ripper-money-grows-on-trees|archive-date=18 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> West's Money Grows on Trees has been cited as an influence to the new generation of UK rap, including Capo Lee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/02/capo-lee-interview|title=Meet Capo Lee, The North London Emcee With Grime In His Bones|website=Complex|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212200/https://www.complex.com/music/2018/02/capo-lee-interview|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019, West performed at the Colours Community Festival held in February.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theguideliverpool.com/colours-community-festival-is-back-this-saturday-at-princes-park/|title=Colours Community Festival is back this Saturday at Princes Park|date=31 July 2019|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212202/https://theguideliverpool.com/colours-community-festival-is-back-this-saturday-at-princes-park/|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Durung that time he announced that he was working on the sequel to his last EP ''Doe or Die''. Shortly after, it was announced that ''Doe or Die: Volume 2'' would be released on 12 October 2019. The album was another collaborative effort with Iron Barz.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/5C4Ddj8jZQwB0c4k1Boe88|title=Doe Or Die, Vol. 2|via=open.spotify.com|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212207/https://open.spotify.com/album/5C4Ddj8jZQwB0c4k1Boe88|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Ventures==\n===Dank of England (D.O.E.)===\n\nIn 2015, West launched his own company known as Dank of England (D.O.E.). Dank of England runs as an [[independent record label]] and produces a clothing line, as well as smoking accessories.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dankofengland.net/|title=Shop &#124; Dank Of England &#124; DOE Gang|website=Dank Of England Official|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212159/https://dankofengland.net/|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It runs as a reboot of his former independent label, Black Magic Entertainment. The launch has been very successful, and alongside co-founder and partner; Screechtree, the pair had been running pop-up shops on a seasonal basis since 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/black-rippers-business-partner-pays-21825692|title=Black the Ripper's business partner's tribute as mystery shrouds cause of death|first=Verity|last=Sulway|date=7 April 2020|website=mirror|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407083106/https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/black-rippers-business-partner-pays-21825692|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cambstimes.co.uk/news/black-ripper-dank-england-march-1-5668292|title=UK rap artist Black The Ripper holds a pop up shop in March as part of a UK tour talking to people about legalising cannabis|first=Kath|last=Sansom|website=Cambs Times|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212158/https://www.cambstimes.co.uk/news/black-ripper-dank-england-march-1-5668292|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dankofengland.net/pages/pop-ups|title=Pop Ups|website=Dank Of England Official|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212201/https://dankofengland.net/pages/pop-ups|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Black gained national recognition for a viral stunt with [[Trollstation]] to create a music video on the [[London Eye]] at [[420 (cannabis culture)|4:20pm]], where they filmed each other smoking and dancing inside the enclosure on November 2016.<ref name=\"auto5\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/> Black's D.O.E. was noted for being \"the most pro-cannabis and British a company can get\" by ''[[The Irish News]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.irishnews.com/magazine/2017/01/12/news/how-drugs-have-found-their-way-into-fashion-882225/|title=How drugs have found their way into fashion|date=12 January 2017|website=The Irish News}}</ref> During this time West was featured in [[Vice (magazine)|''Vice'']]'s documentary; ''How Weed Laws are Failing the UK'' released on 24 October 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://video.vice.com/en_us/video/how-decriminalization-has-shaped-britains-weed-culture/57a1ccea7d44272540c4391e|title=How Weed Laws Are Failing the UK|website=Video|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190811225339/https://video.vice.com/en_us/video/how-decriminalization-has-shaped-britains-weed-culture/57a1ccea7d44272540c4391e|archive-date=11 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> West credited his weed smoking as an influence on his business success and that his stunts were a form of activism to legalise weed. [[EasyJet UK|EasyJet]] banned Black for smoking on the plane to which he responded \"I prefer [[RyanAir]] anyways.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/london/blog/the-big-smoke-how-would-legalising-cannabis-change-london-110217|title=The Big Smoke: how would legalising cannabis change London?|website=Time Out London|access-date=17 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217212200/https://www.timeout.com/london/blog/the-big-smoke-how-would-legalising-cannabis-change-london-110217|archive-date=17 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Black also smoked weed in his local [[Asda]] store.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://consent.yahoo.com/collectConsent?sessionId=1_cc-session_916b7bf9-09de-4cd1-8c8b-a3dc383149ca&lang=en-gb&inline=false|title=HuffPost is now a part of Verizon Media|website=consent.yahoo.com}}</ref> West released a \"Weed Remix\" of ''[[Uber Everywhere]]'' entitled \"Light Up Everywhere\" in April 2016<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\n==Death==\nIt was reported that West died on 4 April 2020 while on holiday in [[Montserrat]]. According to sources, he was found dead in the vacation home he was staying in.<ref>https://loudnewsnet.com/uk-rapper-and-cannabis-activist-black-the-ripper-dead-at-32/</ref> His cause of death is currently unconfirmed.<ref>{{cite web |title=British Grime Legend Black The Ripper Dead At 32 |url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/04/black-the-ripper-dead-at-32 |website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |date=6 April 2020 |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407004408/https://www.complex.com/music/2020/04/black-the-ripper-dead-at-32 |archive-date=7 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The following day an autopsy was ordered by a coroner and the Royal Montserrat Police launched a full investigation into the cause of his death.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/07/black-ripper-autopsy-ordered-montserrat-rapper-dies-aged-32-12522345/|title=Black The Ripper autopsy ordered after rapper dies aged 32|date=7 April 2020|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407195625/https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/07/black-ripper-autopsy-ordered-montserrat-rapper-dies-aged-32-12522345/|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Aftermath===\nLongtime collaborators [[Chip (rapper)|Chip]], [[Lowkey]] and [[Ghetts]] were among those who paid tribute to West, as well as [[Novelist (MC)|Novelist]], [[Skepta]], [[Krept (rapper)|Krept]], [[Lethal Bizzle]], [[Michael Dapaah]], [[Yungen]], [[Nadia Rose]], [[AJ Tracey]] and [[Ambush (rapper)|Ambush]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |first=Will |last=Lavin |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/tributes-paid-to-uk-rapper-black-the-ripper-who-has-died-at-32-2642072 |title=Tributes paid to UK rapper Black The Ripper, who has died at 32 |magazine=[[NME]] |date=6 April 2020 |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> Musician [[Jammer (MC)|Jammer]] released a tribute single titled \"Hope Dealers\" in light of the death of West. The single was co-produced by Jammer and Skully with Jammer delivering downtempo lyrics.<ref>https://www.complex.com/music/2020/04/jammer-hope-dealers-black-the-ripper-tribute</ref> In light of the [[420 (cannabis culture)|cannabis culture]], Chip released a tribute titled \"0420\"\n for Black the Ripper on 20 April, 2020. The tribute sampled Black the Ripper's classic single \"Missing You\".<ref>http://grmdaily.com/video/chip-0420-rip-black-the-ripper</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Black the Ripper discography}}\n===Studio albums===\n*2018: ''[[Money Grows on Trees]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/black-the-ripper-money-grows-on-trees|title=Black the Ripper - Money Grows on Trees|website=[[GRM Daily]]|access-date=18 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200218211628/http://grmdaily.com/black-the-ripper-money-grows-on-trees|archive-date=18 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Extended plays===\n*2015: ''Excuse Me Whilst I Kiss Sky''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kkbox.com/sg/en/album/VeuyF037.BcQu0F1NPo.009H-index.html|title=Excuse Me While I Kiss the Sky|via=www.kkbox.com|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407194244/https://www.kkbox.com/sg/en/album/VeuyF037.BcQu0F1NPo.009H-index.html|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*2017: ''[[In Dank We Trust]]''<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n*2017: ''Doe or Die: Volume 1''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/Black-the-ripper-doe-or-die-lyrics|title=Black The Ripper (Ft. Iron Barz) \u2013 Doe or Die|via=genius.com|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407194154/https://genius.com/Black-the-ripper-doe-or-die-lyrics|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*2019: ''Doe or Die: Volume 2''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kkbox.com/sg/en/album/9WyugiRBxUCUG0F3o71A009H-index.html|title=Doe Or Die, Vol. 2|via=[[KKBox]]|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407194250/https://www.kkbox.com/sg/en/album/9WyugiRBxUCUG0F3o71A009H-index.html|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://dankofengland.net/}}\n{{Sister project links |wikt=no |commons=Category:Black the Ripper |b=no |n=Black the Ripper |q=Black the Ripper |s=no |v=no |species=no |d=Q85438609 |display=Black the Ripper}}\n{{Portal|Cannabis}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Black British male rappers]]\n[[Category:British people of Montserratian descent]]\n[[Category:Cannabis activists]]\n[[Category:English male rappers]]\n[[Category:Grime music artists]]\n[[Category:People from Edmonton, London]]\n[[Category:Political activists]]\n[[Category:Rappers from London]]\n[[Category:English people of Guyanese descent]]\n[[Category:Cannabis music]]\n", "name_user": "TwinTurbo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAftermath", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_the_Ripper"}
{"title_page": "Ten Tunnels Deviation", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2012}}\n{{Infobox tunnel\n| name          = Ten Tunnels Deviation\n| image         = Lithgow zig zag map.jpg\n| image_size    = 300\n| alt           = \n| caption       = A 1958 map of the [[Lithgow Zig Zag]] and deviation\n| official_name = \n| other_name    = \n| line          = [[Main Western railway line|Main Western]]\n| location      = [[Lithgow, New South Wales]]\n| coordinates   = {{coord|-33.4925858296|150.2184178820|region:AU-NSW|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| os_grid_ref   = \n| status        = \n| system        = \n| crosses       = \n| start         = [[Newnes Junction railway station|Newnes Junction station]]\n| end           = [[Zig Zag railway station|Zig Zag station]]\n| stations      = \n| startwork     = {{start date|1908|06|01|df=y}}\n| opened        = {{start date|1910|10|16|df=y}}\n| closed        = \n| rebuilt       = \n| reopened      = \n| owner         = [[RailCorp]]\n| operator      = [[NSW TrainLink]]\n| traffic       = \n| character     = \n| engineer      = \n| construction  = \n| length        = Ten tunnels of varying length from {{convert|70|to|825|m}}\n| linelength    = {{convert|9.2|km}}\n| tracklength   = \n| notrack       = 2\n| gauge         = {{Railgauge|1435mm}}\n| el            = \n| speed         = \n| hielevation   = \n| lowelevation  = \n| height        = \n| width         =\n| depth_below_water =\n| shipping_clearance_above = \n| grade         = \n| map           = \n| extra         = \n{{Designation list\n | embed = yes\n | designation1 = New South Wales State Heritage Register\n | designation1_offname = Great Zig Zag Railway deviation tunnels; Bell to Zig Zag Ten Tunnel Railway Deviation\n | designation1_type = State heritage (complex / group)\n | designation1_date = 2 April 1999\n | delisted1_date = \n | designation1_partof = \n | designation1_number = 1037\n | designation1_criteria = [[New South Wales State Heritage Register#Criteria|a., c., e., f., g.]]\n | designation1_free1name =  Type\n | designation1_free1value = Railway Tunnel\n | designation1_free2name =  Category\n | designation1_free2value = Transport - Rail\n | designation1_free3name = Builders\n | designation1_free3value = NSW Government Railways\n }}\n}}\nThe '''Ten Tunnels Deviation''' is a heritage-listed {{convert|9.2|km|adj=on}} section of the [[Main Western railway line, New South Wales|Main Western Line]] between [[Newnes Junction railway station|Newnes Junction]] and [[Zig Zag railway station|Zig Zag]] stations in [[Lithgow]], [[New South Wales]], Australia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nswrail.net/lines/show.php?name=NSW:main_west |title=Main Western Line |work=NSWrail.net |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024154450/http://www.nswrail.net/lines/show.php?name=NSW:main_west |archive-date=24 October 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It was designed and built by the [[New South Wales Government Railways]] and built from 1 June 1908 and 16 October 1910. It is also known as '''Great Zig Zag Railway deviation tunnels''' and '''Bell to Zig Zag Ten Tunnel Railway Deviation'''. It was added to the [[New South Wales State Heritage Register]] on 2 April 1999.<ref name=nswshr-1037>{{cite NSW SHR|5012082|Great Zig Zag Railway deviation tunnels|hr=01037|fn=H98/00287/03; 10/18296|accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nWhen they opened in 1910, the tunnels replaced the [[Lithgow Zig Zag]], which limited the length of trains over the mountains and required two changes in direction.<ref name=network>{{cite journal |title=Ugrading the Zig Zag Tunnels |journal=[[Network (periodical)|Network]] |date=April 1978 |pages=7\u201311}}</ref> The deviation comprises ten tunnels of varying length from {{convert|70|to|825|m}} over {{convert|3.7|km}}. The work also included the excavation of a {{convert|200|ft|m|adj=on|order=flip}} cutting, the deepest cutting on the NSW rail system. Journey times were reduced by between 20 and 30 minutes.<ref name=nswshr-1037/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article63105576 |title=The Zig Zag Great Western Railway|newspaper=[[Illustrated Sydney News|Illustrated Sydney News and New South Wales Agriculturalist & Grazier]] |volume=X |issue=10 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=28 March 1874 |page=14 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article15192332 |title=Passing of the Zig Zag |newspaper=[[Sydney Morning Herald]] |issue=22,701 |date=17 October 1910 |page=8 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe original 1869 Main Western single line headed north from [[Mount Victoria, New South Wales|Mount Victoria]] along the ridge known as the Darling Causeway. It then turned west and entered the Dargan's Creek valley. After climbing out the head of this valley it reached an escarpment where the Zigzag was constructed to reach the valley floor. The Zig Zag was created by the track switching back on itself twice to reach the bottom of the [[Great Dividing Range]]. From here it continued west to Lithgow. This section was opened on 18 October 1869.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\nThe 1869 Zig Zag became a bottleneck to the flow of traffic and as early as 1885, consideration was given to its replacement. In 1897, the first major change was made, known as Dargan's Creek Deviation. This involved traversing the Dargan's Creek Valley on the northern side of the creek instead of the south. The line was still single-track at this point, and this soon became a bottleneck. In order to alleviate this, electric staff crossing loops were added at Edgecombe in 1901 (between [[Clarence, New South Wales|Clarence]] and Top Points) and Dargan's in 1902 (between [[Bell, New South Wales|Bell]] and Clarence).<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\nIn 1906, a new junction and station were constructed at the first Newnes Junction Station. The junction was for the private [[Newnes railway line]].<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\nBy 1910, it had become evident that a new route was required for the descent to Lithgow. Accordingly, a new route, known as the Ten Tunnels Deviation, was built and the Dargan's Creek Deviation was closed. The existing stations were all closed, with Newnes Junction relocated closer to [[Sydney]], and a new Clarence station built where the line goes under the [[Bells Line of Road]]. The Newnes Line closed after 25 years of operation in 1932, and only the formation remains.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\nThe Ten Tunnel Deviation started at Newnes Junction and finished at Bottom Points (now Zig Zag platform). As its name suggests, it featured 10 new tunnels, and it bypassed the Zig Zag. The new route broadly followed the previous one as far as Newnes Junction, before turning south and taking a more circuitous route via the tunnels to emerge from the final one near the base of the Zig Zag.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\nSupplies to the line during construction were provided by a funicular railway that descended {{convert|350|ft|m|0|order=flip}} from the ridge to a location near No. 10 tunnel. Up to 1500 day employees worked on the project.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\nThe deviation was a part of the duplication of the Main Western Railway between [[Penrith, New South Wales|Penrith]] and Lithgow. Upon completion the deviation comprised ten tunnels of varying length from {{convert|77|to|902|yd|m|0|order=flip}}. The work also included the excavation of the deepest cutting of {{convert|200|ft|m|0|order=flip}} on the NSW rail system. Journey times were reduced by between 20 and 30 minutes. Also, the gradient was reduced from 1 in 42 to 1 in 90, thereby allowing a doubling in the loads of trains.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\nIn 1972, a group of enthusiasts formed the Zig Zag Cooperative, and took over the track between the original Clarence station and Bottom Points and today the [[Zig Zag Railway]] is a successful tourist operation based at the restored Clarence station. A new Cityrail platform, Zig Zag was constructed on the Main Western line to allow public transport access to the Zig Zag. The previous stations at Newnes Junction and Clarence have closed, with little trace of the latter remaining.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\n==Construction==\n[[File:Lithgow funicular.jpg|thumb|A [[funicular]] rail line was used for supplies.]]\nThe Act approving the construction of the double line deviation was passed by the New South Wales Parliament in December 1906.<ref name=network/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.legislation.nsw.gov.au/sessionalview/sessional/act/1906-36.pdf | title=Great Western Railway Deviation (Lithgow Zigzag) Act, 1906 }}</ref> Construction started near the former Oakey Park Colliery on the 1 in 42 Bottom Road, which had already been duplicated in 1880. It eventually passed Bottom Points before entering a series of ten tunnels. Originally eleven were planned, but one of them was opened out instead, owing to the discovery of rock faults, leaving the deepest cutting on the New South Wales rail system. The headquarters for the works was at nearby [[Clarence, New South Wales|Clarence]], where many of the [[Navvy|navvies]] were temporarily housed. Here a temporary power station was established for rock drills, lighting, compressors, etc.<ref name=sing>{{cite journal |title=The Railway Crossing of the Blue Mountains |author1=Wylie, R. F. |author2=Singleton, C. C. |journal=[[Australian Railway History|Australian Railway Historical Society Bulletin]] |date=November 1958 |pages=171\u2013173 }}</ref>\n\nAccess to the tunnel locations and the short open sections between the cliffs was extremely difficult. At one isolated point, horses and drays were placed on to the worksite by means of a crane and long jibs. There they remained until the tunnels were completed to provide them with a way out.<ref name=network/> The supply of materials for tunnels 8, 9 and 10 was expedited by the construction of a {{convert|350|ft|m|adj=on|order=flip}} [[funicular]]<ref name=nswshr-1037/> of the 4-rail type from near Mount Sinai on the original line.<ref name=sing/> Only experienced miners were employed on the more dangerous tunnelling activities, which were carried out by day and night;<ref name=network/> with approximately 1,500 employees working each day.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\nThe tunnels were situated on a maximum grade of 1 in 90. The line curves towards Newnes Junction after leaving the tunnels at the eastern end. Newnes Junction also had to be moved {{convert|660|m}} to its current place, and two more tracks were also constructed for the [[Commonwealth Oil Corporation]]'s Newnes railway line.<ref name=network/> When the deviation was completed, much of the equipment was moved to the deviation of the [[Lapstone Zig Zag]], as well as the navvies. As a result, the population of Clarence declined rapidly.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\nThe deviation was electrified along with the rest of the line in 1957.<ref name=nswshr-1037/> In 1978, the roadbed of the Ten Tunnels was lowered to allow [[NSW TrainLink V set|double deck V sets]] to operate on the line.<ref name=network/><ref>\"NSW slab track installation completed\" ''[[Railway Gazette International]]'' January 1979 page 31</ref> In 2018, modifications are planned to accommodate the [[NSW TrainLink D set|D sets]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20180205162128/https://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/projects/current-projects/new-intercity-fleet-program-ten-tunnels New Intercity Fleet Program Ten Tunnels Deviation Modifications] Transport for NSW 5 February 2018</ref>\n\n== Description ==\nThe deviation comprises ten tunnels of varying length from {{convert|77|to|902|yd|m|0|order=flip}}. The work also included the excavation of the deepest cutting of {{convert|200|ft|m|0|order=flip}} on the New South Wales rail system. The tunnels are numbered from the Sydney end of the deviation. The tunnel portals are elliptically shaped with concrete used for floor and up to the start of the arch and [[brickwork]] for the arches. The tunnels are of masonry (brick) construction.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\n=== Condition ===\n\nAs at 28 April 2010, generally good condition.<ref name=nswshr-1037/> A 2007 structural report notes the following:\n*No. 1, 3, 4 tunnel water seepage,\n*No. 6 hairline cracks at Sydney end,\n*No. 9 hairline cracks and water stains,\n*No. 10 water seepage from crown.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\nThe Ten Tunnel Deviation is intact and has high integrity.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\n=== Modifications and dates ===\n*1952: Land was acquired for a further deviation between Bottom Points (now Zig Zag platform) and Coal Stage signal box in Lithgow but electrification in 1957 eliminated the need for the deviation.\n*1978: The conventional use of individual track sleepers in all tunnels was replaced by a continuous concrete bed and was upgraded in 2002/03.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\n== Heritage listing ==\nAs at 28 April 2010, the Ten Tunnel Deviation is of state significance due to its historical associations with the second phase of railway crossing across the Great Dividing Range. It is of a high level of technical significance as a large scale engineering achievement of the early 20th century including excavation of the deepest cutting on the NSW rail system. The project was one of the great railway deviations constructed throughout NSW, and was a success in reducing both journey time and track gradient, and continues to be in use today. The tunnels form part of a larger railway landscape in the Lithgow area and across the [[Blue Mountains (New South Wales)|Blue Mountains]] including the Zig Zag railway, Dargan's Creek Deviation, Eskbank Goods Yard and the State Mine Colliery railway.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\nTen Tunnels Deviation was listed on the [[New South Wales State Heritage Register]] on 2 April 1999 having satisfied the following criteria.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\n'''The place is important in demonstrating the course, or pattern, of cultural or natural history in New South Wales.'''\n\nThe Ten Tunnel Deviation is historically significant as the second phase of the Great Dividing Range railway crossing. The project was one of the great railway deviations and is still in use today. The tunnels form part of a larger railway landscape in the Lithgow area and across the Blue Mountains including the Zig Zag railway, Dargan's Creek Deviation, Eskbank Goods Yard and the State Mine Colliery railway.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\n'''The place is important in demonstrating aesthetic characteristics and/or a high degree of creative or technical achievement in New South Wales.'''\n\nThe Ten Tunnel Deviation illustrates high level technical achievement for tunnelling, engineering and railway building practices. The work included excavation of the deepest cutting on the NSW rail system. The construction involved up to 1500 employees per day. It resulted in journey times reduced by 30 minutes and the track gradient reduced from 1 in 41 to 1 in 90 which allowed a doubling in the load of trains.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\n'''The place has potential to yield information that will contribute to an understanding of the cultural or natural history of New South Wales.'''\n\nThe Ten Tunnel Deviation has research significance in providing evidence on the techniques of tunnel construction in the first decade of the 1900s.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\n'''The place possesses uncommon, rare or endangered aspects of the cultural or natural history of New South Wales.'''\n\nThe Ten Tunnel Deviation is a major engineering achievement in the early 1900s and is rare in this regard.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\n'''The place is important in demonstrating the principal characteristics of a class of cultural or natural places/environments in New South Wales.'''\n\nThe Bell to Zig Zag Ten Tunnel Deviation is representative of brick-arch construction used for tunnelling during the early 20th century railway deviations in NSW.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{portal|New South Wales|Railways}}}}\n*[[List of tunnels in Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Attribution===\n{{NSW-SHR-CC-contains|name=Great Zig Zag Railway deviation tunnels|dno=5012082|id=01037|year=2018|accessdate=2 June 2018}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Citation | author1=Beckhaus, John | author2=Halgren, Stephen, (Author.) | title=Sydney's Electric Trains | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/26593412 | publication-date=2007 | publisher=Australian Railway Historical Society - New South Wales Division | isbn=978-0-9757870-8-3 }}\n* {{Citation | author1=Belbin, Phillip | author2=Burke, David, 1927- | title=Full steam across the mountains | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/9551751 | publication-date=1981 | publisher=Methuen Australia | isbn=978-0-454-00278-2 }}\n* {{Citation | author1=Langdon, Mark | title=Conquering the Blue Mountains | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/version/24447037 | publication-date=2006 | publisher=Eveleigh Press | isbn=978-1-876568-30-6 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Ten Tunnels Deviation}}\n\n{{City of Lithgow topics|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:1910 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 1910]]\n[[Category:Railway tunnels in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Standard gauge railways in Australia]]\n[[Category:New South Wales State Heritage Register]]\n[[Category:Lithgow, New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Main Western railway line, New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Articles incorporating text from the New South Wales State Heritage Register]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2012}}\n{{Infobox tunnel\n| name          = Ten Tunnels Deviation\n| image         = Lithgow zig zag map.jpg\n| image_size    = 300\n| alt           = \n| caption       = A 1958 map of the [[Lithgow Zig Zag]] and deviation\n| official_name = \n| other_name    = \n| line          = [[Main Western railway line|Main Western]]\n| location      = [[Lithgow, New South Wales]]\n| coordinates   = {{coord|-33.4925858296|150.2184178820|region:AU-NSW|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| os_grid_ref   = \n| status        = \n| system        = \n| crosses       = \n| start         = [[Newnes Junction railway station|Newnes Junction station]]\n| end           = [[Zig Zag railway station|Zig Zag station]]\n| stations      = \n| startwork     = {{start date|1908|06|01|df=y}}\n| opened        = {{start date|1910|10|16|df=y}}\n| closed        = \n| rebuilt       = \n| reopened      = \n| owner         = [[RailCorp]]\n| operator      = [[NSW TrainLink]]\n| traffic       = \n| character     = \n| engineer      = \n| construction  = \n| length        = Ten tunnels of varying length from {{convert|70|to|825|m}}\n| linelength    = {{convert|9.2|km}}\n| tracklength   = \n| notrack       = 2\n| gauge         = {{Railgauge|1435mm}}\n| el            = \n| speed         = \n| hielevation   = \n| lowelevation  = \n| height        = \n| width         =\n| depth_below_water =\n| shipping_clearance_above = \n| grade         = \n| map           = \n| extra         = \n{{Designation list\n | embed = yes\n | designation1 = New South Wales State Heritage Register\n | designation1_offname = Great Zig Zag Railway deviation tunnels; Bell to Zig Zag Ten Tunnel Railway Deviation\n | designation1_type = State heritage (complex / group)\n | designation1_date = 2 April 1999\n | delisted1_date = \n | designation1_partof = \n | designation1_number = 1037\n | designation1_criteria = [[New South Wales State Heritage Register#Criteria|a., c., e., f., g.]]\n | designation1_free1name =  Type\n | designation1_free1value = Railway Tunnel\n | designation1_free2name =  Category\n | designation1_free2value = Transport - Rail\n | designation1_free3name = Builders\n | designation1_free3value = NSW Government Railways\n }}\n}}\nThe '''Ten Tunnels Deviation''' is a heritage-listed {{convert|9.2|km|adj=on}} section of the [[Main Western railway line, New South Wales|Main Western Line]] between [[Newnes Junction railway station|Newnes Junction]] and [[Zig Zag railway station|Zig Zag]] stations in [[Lithgow]], [[New South Wales]], Australia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nswrail.net/lines/show.php?name=NSW:main_west |title=Main Western Line |work=NSWrail.net |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024154450/http://www.nswrail.net/lines/show.php?name=NSW:main_west |archive-date=24 October 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It was designed and built by the [[New South Wales Government Railways]] and built from 1 June 1908 and 16 October 1910. It is also known as '''Great Zig Zag Railway deviation tunnels''' and '''Bell to Zig Zag Ten Tunnel Railway Deviation'''. It was added to the [[New South Wales State Heritage Register]] on 2 April 1999.<ref name=nswshr-1037>{{cite NSW SHR|5012082|Great Zig Zag Railway deviation tunnels|hr=01037|fn=H98/00287/03; 10/18296|accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nWhen they opened in 1910, the tunnels replaced the [[Lithgow Zig Zag]], which limited the length of trains over the mountains and required two changes in direction.<ref name=network>{{cite journal |title=Ugrading the Zig Zag Tunnels |journal=[[Network (periodical)|Network]] |date=April 1978 |pages=7\u201311}}</ref> The deviation comprises ten tunnels of varying length from {{convert|70|to|825|m}} over {{convert|3.7|km}}. The work also included the excavation of a {{convert|200|ft|m|adj=on|order=flip}} cutting, the deepest cutting on the NSW rail system. Journey times were reduced by between 20 and 30 minutes.<ref name=nswshr-1037/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article63105576 |title=The Zig Zag Great Western Railway|newspaper=[[Illustrated Sydney News|Illustrated Sydney News and New South Wales Agriculturalist & Grazier]] |volume=X |issue=10 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=28 March 1874 |page=14 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article15192332 |title=Passing of the Zig Zag |newspaper=[[Sydney Morning Herald]] |issue=22,701 |date=17 October 1910 |page=8 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe original 1869 Main Western single line headed north from [[Mount Victoria, New South Wales|Mount Victoria]] along the ridge known as the Darling Causeway. It then turned west and entered the Dargan's Creek valley. After climbing out the head of this valley it reached an escarpment where the Zigzag was constructed to reach the valley floor. The Zig Zag was created by the track switching back on itself twice to reach the bottom of the [[Great Dividing Range]]. From here it continued west to Lithgow. This section was opened on 18 October 1869.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\nThe 1869 Zig Zag became a bottleneck to the flow of traffic and as early as 1885, consideration was given to its replacement. In 1897, the first major change was made, known as Dargan's Creek Deviation. This involved traversing the Dargan's Creek Valley on the northern side of the creek instead of the south. The line was still single-track at this point, and this soon became a bottleneck. In order to alleviate this, electric staff crossing loops were added at Edgecombe in 1901 (between [[Clarence, New South Wales|Clarence]] and Top Points) and Dargan's in 1902 (between [[Bell, New South Wales|Bell]] and Clarence).<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\nIn 1906, a new junction and station were constructed at the first Newnes Junction Station. The junction was for the private [[Newnes railway line]].<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\nBy 1910, it had become evident that a new route was required for the descent to Lithgow. Accordingly, a new route, known as the Ten Tunnels Deviation, was built and the Dargan's Creek Deviation was closed. The existing stations were all closed, with Newnes Junction relocated closer to [[Sydney]], and a new Clarence station built where the line goes under the [[Bells Line of Road]]. The Newnes Line closed after 25 years of operation in 1932, and only the formation remains.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\nThe Ten Tunnel Deviation started at Newnes Junction and finished at Bottom Points (now Zig Zag platform). As its name suggests, it featured 10 new tunnels, and it bypassed the Zig Zag. The new route broadly followed the previous one as far as Newnes Junction, before turning south and taking a more circuitous route via the tunnels to emerge from the final one near the base of the Zig Zag.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\nSupplies to the line during construction were provided by a funicular railway that descended {{convert|350|ft|m|0|order=flip}} from the ridge to a location near No. 10 tunnel. Up to 1500 day employees worked on the project.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\nThe deviation was a part of the duplication of the Main Western Railway between [[Penrith, New South Wales|Penrith]] and Lithgow. Upon completion the deviation comprised ten tunnels of varying length from {{convert|77|to|902|yd|m|0|order=flip}}. The work also included the excavation of the deepest cutting of {{convert|200|ft|m|0|order=flip}} on the NSW rail system. Journey times were reduced by between 20 and 30 minutes. Also, the gradient was reduced from 1 in 42 to 1 in 90, thereby allowing a doubling in the loads of trains.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\nIn 1972, a group of enthusiasts formed the Zig Zag Cooperative, and took over the track between the original Clarence station and Bottom Points and today the [[Zig Zag Railway]] is a successful tourist operation based at the restored Clarence station. A new Cityrail platform, Zig Zag was constructed on the Main Western line to allow public transport access to the Zig Zag. The previous stations at Newnes Junction and Clarence have closed, with little trace of the latter remaining.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\n==Construction==\n[[File:Lithgow funicular.jpg|thumb|A [[funicular]] rail line was used for supplies.]]\nThe Act approving the construction of the double line deviation was passed by the New South Wales Parliament in December 1906.<ref name=network/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.legislation.nsw.gov.au/sessionalview/sessional/act/1906-36.pdf | title=Great Western Railway Deviation (Lithgow Zigzag) Act, 1906 }}</ref> Construction started near the former Oakey Park Colliery on the 1 in 42 Bottom Road, which had already been duplicated in 1880. It eventually passed Bottom Points before entering a series of ten tunnels. Originally eleven were planned, but one of them was opened out instead, owing to the discovery of rock faults, leaving the deepest cutting on the New South Wales rail system. The headquarters for the works was at nearby [[Clarence, New South Wales|Clarence]], where many of the [[Navvy|navvies]] were temporarily housed. Here a temporary power station was established for rock drills, lighting, compressors, etc.<ref name=sing>{{cite journal |title=The Railway Crossing of the Blue Mountains |author1=Wylie, R. F. |author2=Singleton, C. C. |journal=[[Australian Railway History|Australian Railway Historical Society Bulletin]] |date=November 1958 |pages=171\u2013173 }}</ref>\n\nAccess to the tunnel locations and the short open sections between the cliffs was extremely difficult. At one isolated point, horses and drays were placed on to the worksite by means of a crane and long jibs. There they remained until the tunnels were completed to provide them with a way out.<ref name=network/> The supply of materials for tunnels 8, 9 and 10 was expedited by the construction of a {{convert|350|ft|m|adj=on|order=flip}} [[funicular]]<ref name=nswshr-1037/> of the 4-rail type from near Mount Sinai on the original line.<ref name=sing/> Only experienced miners were employed on the more dangerous tunnelling activities, which were carried out by day and night;<ref name=network/> with approximately 1,500 employees working each day.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\nThe tunnels were situated on a maximum grade of 1 in 90. The line curves towards Newnes Junction after leaving the tunnels at the eastern end. Newnes Junction also had to be moved {{convert|660|m}} to its current place, and two more tracks were also constructed for the [[Commonwealth Oil Corporation]]'s Newnes railway line.<ref name=network/> When the deviation was completed, much of the equipment was moved to the deviation of the [[Lapstone Zig Zag]], as well as the navvies. As a result, the population of Clarence declined rapidly.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\nThe deviation was electrified along with the rest of the line in 1957.<ref name=nswshr-1037/> In 1978, the roadbed of the Ten Tunnels was lowered to allow [[NSW TrainLink V set|double deck V sets]] to operate on the line.<ref name=network/><ref>\"NSW slab track installation completed\" ''[[Railway Gazette International]]'' January 1979 page 31</ref> In 2018, modifications are planned to accommodate the [[NSW TrainLink D set|D sets]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20180205162128/https://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/projects/current-projects/new-intercity-fleet-program-ten-tunnels New Intercity Fleet Program Ten Tunnels Deviation Modifications] Transport for NSW 5 February 2018</ref>\n\n== Description ==\nThe deviation comprises ten tunnels of varying length from {{convert|77|to|902|yd|m|0|order=flip}}. The work also included the excavation of the deepest cutting of {{convert|200|ft|m|0|order=flip}} on the New South Wales rail system. The tunnels are numbered from the Sydney end of the deviation. The tunnel portals are elliptically shaped with concrete used for floor and up to the start of the arch and [[brickwork]] for the arches. The tunnels are of masonry (brick) construction.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\n=== Condition ===\n\nAs at 28 April 2010, generally good condition.<ref name=nswshr-1037/> A 2007 structural report notes the following:\n*No. 1, 3, 4 tunnel water seepage,\n*No. 6 hairline cracks at Sydney end,\n*No. 9 hairline cracks and water stains,\n*No. 10 water seepage from crown.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\nThe Ten Tunnel Deviation is intact and has high integrity.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\n=== Modifications and dates ===\n*1952: Land was acquired for a further deviation between Bottom Points (now Zig Zag platform) and Coal Stage signal box in Lithgow but electrification in 1957 eliminated the need for the deviation.\n*1978: The conventional use of individual track sleepers in all tunnels was replaced by a continuous concrete bed and was upgraded in 2002/03.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\n== Heritage listing ==\nAs at 28 April 2010, the Ten Tunnel Deviation is of state significance due to its historical associations with the second phase of railway crossing across the Great Dividing Range. It is of a high level of technical significance as a large scale engineering achievement of the early 20th century including excavation of the deepest cutting on the NSW rail system. The project was one of the great railway deviations constructed throughout NSW, and was a success in reducing both journey time and track gradient, and continues to be in use today. The tunnels form part of a larger railway landscape in the Lithgow area and across the [[Blue Mountains (New South Wales)|Blue Mountains]] including the Zig Zag railway, Dargan's Creek Deviation, Eskbank Goods Yard and the State Mine Colliery railway.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\nTen Tunnels Deviation was listed on the [[New South Wales State Heritage Register]] on 2 April 1999 having satisfied the following criteria.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\n'''The place is important in demonstrating the course, or pattern, of cultural or natural history in New South Wales.'''\n\nThe Ten Tunnel Deviation is historically significant as the second phase of the Great Dividing Range railway crossing. The project was one of the great railway deviations and is still in use today. The tunnels form part of a larger railway landscape in the Lithgow area and across the Blue Mountains including the Zig Zag railway, Dargan's Creek Deviation, Eskbank Goods Yard and the State Mine Colliery railway.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\n'''The place is important in demonstrating aesthetic characteristics and/or a high degree of creative or technical achievement in New South Wales.'''\n\nThe Ten Tunnel Deviation illustrates high level technical achievement for tunnelling, engineering and railway building practices. The work included excavation of the deepest cutting on the NSW rail system. The construction involved up to 1500 employees per day. It resulted in journey times reduced by 30 minutes and the track gradient reduced from 1 in 41 to 1 in 90 which allowed a doubling in the load of trains.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\n'''The place has potential to yield information that will contribute to an understanding of the cultural or natural history of New South Wales.'''\n\nThe Ten Tunnel Deviation has research significance in providing evidence on the techniques of tunnel construction in the first decade of the 1900s.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\n'''The place possesses uncommon, rare or endangered aspects of the cultural or natural history of New South Wales.'''\n\nThe Ten Tunnel Deviation is a major engineering achievement in the early 1900s and is rare in this regard.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\n'''The place is important in demonstrating the principal characteristics of a class of cultural or natural places/environments in New South Wales.'''\n\nThe Bell to Zig Zag Ten Tunnel Deviation is representative of brick-arch construction used for tunnelling during the early 20th century railway deviations in NSW.<ref name=nswshr-1037/>\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{portal|New South Wales|Railways}}}}\n*[[List of tunnels in Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Attribution===\n{{NSW-SHR-CC-contains|name=Great Zig Zag Railway deviation tunnels|dno=5012082|id=01037|year=2018|accessdate=2 June 2018}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Citation | author1=Beckhaus, John | author2=Halgren, Stephen, (Author.) | title=Sydney's Electric Trains | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/26593412 | publication-date=2007 | publisher=Australian Railway Historical Society - New South Wales Division | isbn=978-0-9757870-8-3 }}\n* {{Citation | author1=Belbin, Phillip | author2=Burke, David, 1927- | title=Full steam across the mountains | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/9551751 | publication-date=1981 | publisher=Methuen Australia | isbn=978-0-454-00278-2 }}\n* {{Citation | author1=Langdon, Mark | title=Conquering the Blue Mountains | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/version/24447037 | publication-date=2006 | publisher=Eveleigh Press | isbn=978-1-876568-30-6 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Ten Tunnels Deviation}}\n\n{{City of Lithgow topics|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:1910 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 1910]]\n[[Category:Railway tunnels in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Regional railway lines in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Standard gauge railways in Australia]]\n[[Category:New South Wales State Heritage Register]]\n[[Category:Lithgow, New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Main Western railway line, New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Articles incorporating text from the New South Wales State Heritage Register]]\n", "name_user": "Rangasyd", "label": "safe", "comment": "removedCategory:Regional railway lines in New South WalesusingHotCatduplicated cat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ten_Tunnels_Deviation"}
{"title_page": "Arthur Percival", "text_new": "{{short description|British army officer in the First and Second World Wars}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|honorific_prefix = \n|name             = Arthur Ernest Percival\n|honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|CB|DSO1|OBE|MC|OStJ|DL}}\n|image= Arthur Percival.jpg{{!}}border\n|image_size= \n|alt= \n|caption= Percival, pictured here as [[General officer commanding|GOC]] [[Malaya Command]], December 1941\n|nickname=\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1887|12|26|df=yes}}\n|birth_place= [[Aspenden]], [[Hertfordshire]], England\n|death_date= {{death date and age|1966|1|31|1887|12|26|df=yes}}\n|death_place= [[Westminster]], [[London]], England\n|placeofburial=\n|allegiance= United Kingdom\n|branch= {{army|United Kingdom}}\n|serviceyears= 1914\u20131946\n|servicenumber= 8785\n|rank= [[Lieutenant-general (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant-General]]\n|unit= [[Essex Regiment]]<br/>[[Cheshire Regiment]]\n|commands= [[Malaya Command]] (1941\u20131942)<br/>[[44th (Home Counties) Division|44th (Home Counties) Infantry Division]] (1940\u20131941)<br/>[[43rd (Wessex) Infantry Division]] (1940)<br/>2nd Battalion, [[Cheshire Regiment]] (1932\u20131934)<br/>7th (Service) Battalion, [[Bedfordshire and Hertfordshire Regiment|Bedfordshire Regiment]] (1918)\n|battles= [[First World War]]\n* [[Battle of the Somme]]\n* [[Spring Offensive]]\n[[Russian Civil War]]\n* [[North Russia Campaign]]\n[[Anglo-Irish War]]<br/>[[Second World War]]\n* [[Malayan Campaign]]\n* [[Battle of Singapore]]{{surrendered}}\n|awards= [[Companion of the Order of the Bath]]<br/>[[Distinguished Service Order]] & [[Medal bar|Bar]]<br/>[[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]]<br/>[[Military Cross]]<br/>[[Mentioned in Despatches]] (3)<br/>[[Croix de guerre 1914\u20131918 (France)|Croix de guerre]] (France)\n| memorials     =\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Margaret Elizabeth MacGregor Greer|27 July 1927|5 October 1953|end=died}}\n| children      = {{unbulleted list|Dorinda Margery Percival (daughter)|Alfred James MacGregor Percival (son)}}\n| relations     =\n| laterwork     = \n| signature     = \n| signature_size =\n| signature_alt =\n}}\n\n[[Lieutenant-general (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant-General]] '''''Arthur Ernest Percival''''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|CB|DSO1|OBE|MC|OStJ|DL}} (26 December 1887 \u2013 31 January 1966) was a senior [[British Army]] officer. He saw service in the [[First World War]] and built a successful military career during the [[interwar period]] but is most noted for his defeat in the [[Second World War]], when he commanded [[Commonwealth of Nations|British Commonwealth]] forces during the Japanese [[Malayan Campaign]] and the subsequent [[Battle of Singapore]].\n\nPercival's surrender to the invading [[Imperial Japanese Army]] force, the largest surrender in [[Military history of the United Kingdom|British military history]], undermined Britain's prestige as an imperial power in [[East Asia]].<ref>Taylor, ''English History 1914\u20131945'', p657</ref><ref name=\"Morris\">Morris, ''Farewell the Trumpets'', p452</ref> His defenders, such as [[Sir John Smyth, 1st Baronet|Sir John Smyth]], have argued that under-funding of [[British Malaya|Malaya]]'s defences and the inexperienced, under-equipped nature of the Commonwealth army, not Percival's leadership, were ultimately to blame.<ref>Smyth, ''Percival and the Tragedy of Singapore''</ref>\n\n==Early days==\n\n===Childhood and employment===\nArthur Ernest Percival was born on 26 December 1887 in Aspenden Lodge, [[Aspenden]] near [[Buntingford]] in [[Hertfordshire]], England, the second son of Alfred Reginald and Edith Percival (n\u00e9e Miller). His father was the Land Agent of the Hamel's Park estate and his mother came from a [[Lancashire]] [[cotton]] family.<ref name=\"Officers of the British Army\">{{cite web|url=http://www.unithistories.com/officers/Army_officers_P02.html#Percival_AE|title=British Army officer histories|publisher=Unit Histories|accessdate=2017-06-23}}</ref>\n\nPercival was initially schooled locally in [[Bengeo]]. Then in 1901, he was sent to [[Rugby School|Rugby]] with his more academically successful brother, where he was a boarder in School House. A moderate pupil, he studied [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] and [[Latin]] but was described by a teacher as \"not a good classic\".<ref>Kinvig, ''Scapegoat: General Percival of Singapore'', p5</ref> Percival's only qualification on leaving in 1906 was a higher school certificate. He was a more successful sportsman, playing [[cricket]] and [[tennis]] and running [[cross-country running|cross country]].<ref>Smith, ''Singapore Burning: Heroism and Surrender in World War II'', p23</ref> He also rose to [[Colour Sergeant|colour sergeant]] in the school's Volunteer Rifle Corps. However, his military career began at a comparatively late age: although a member of Youngsbury Rifle Club, he was still working as a clerk for the iron ore merchants Naylor, Benzon & Company Limited in London, which he had joined in 1914, when the [[World War I]] broke out.\n\n===Enlistment and First World War===\nPercival enlisted on the first day of the war as a [[Private (rank)|private]] in the [[Officer Training Corps]] of the [[Inns of Court]], at the age of 26, and was promoted after five weeks' basic training to temporary [[second lieutenant]].<ref name=commission>{{London Gazette|issue=29058 |supp=y|pages=1176\u20131179|date=2 February 1915}}</ref> Nearly one third of his fellow recruits would be dead by the end of the war. By November Percival had been promoted to [[captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=29050|page=802|date=26 January 1915}}</ref>  The following year he was despatched to [[France]] with the newly formed 7th (Service) Battalion of the [[Bedfordshire Regiment]],<ref name=commission /> which became part of the 54th Brigade, [[18th (Eastern) Division]] in February 1915. The first day of the [[Battle of the Somme]] (1 July 1916) left Percival unscathed, but in September he was badly wounded in four places by [[Shrapnel shell|shrapnel]], as he led his company in an assault on the [[Schwaben Redoubt]], beyond the ruins of [[Thiepval]] village, and was awarded the [[Military Cross]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=29824 |supp=y|pages=11044\u201311063|date=14 November 1916}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Wiltshire Regiment Thiepval 7 August 1916.jpg|thumb|Near [[Thiepval]], 7 August. Photo by [[Ernest Brooks (photographer)|Ernest Brooks]].]]\n\nPercival took a regular commission as a captain with the [[Essex Regiment]] in October 1916,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=29783|page=9864|date=13 October 1916}}</ref> whilst recovering from his injuries in hospital. He was appointed a temporary [[major (United Kingdom)|major]] in his original regiment.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=30038 |supp=y|page=4042|date=27 April 1917}}</ref> In 1917, he became battalion commander with the temporary rank of [[Lieutenant-Colonel (United Kingdom)|lieutenant-colonel]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=30632 |supp=y|page=4550|date=12 April 1918}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=31003 |supp=y|page=13282|date=8 November 1918}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=31035 |supp=y|page=14044|date=26 November 1918}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=31220 |supp=y|page=3257|date=7 March 1919}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=32233 |supp=y|page=1434|date=18 February 1921}}</ref> During [[German Empire|Germany]]'s [[Spring Offensive]], Percival led a counter-attack that saved a unit of French artillery from capture, winning a [[Croix de guerre 1914\u20131918 (France)|Croix de Guerre]].<ref>Smith, p24</ref> For a short period in May 1918, he acted as commander of the 54th Brigade. He was given [[brevet (military)|brevet]] promotion to major,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=31092 |supp=y|pages=15\u201316|date=24 June 1921}}</ref> and awarded the [[Distinguished Service Order]], with his citation noting his \"power of command and knowledge of tactics\".<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=32371 |supp=y|page=5096|date=24 June 1921}}</ref> He ended the war as a respected soldier, described as \"very efficient\" and was recommended for the [[Staff College, Camberley|Staff College]].<ref>Keegan, ''Churchill's Generals'', p257</ref>\n\n==Between the wars==\n\n===Russia===\nPercival's studies were delayed in 1919 when he decided to volunteer for service with the [[Arkhangelsk|Archangel]] Command of the British Military Mission during the [[North Russia Campaign]] of the [[Russian Civil War]]. Acting as second-in-command of the 45th [[The Royal Fusiliers (City of London Regiment)|Royal Fusiliers]], he earned a bar to his DSO in August, when his attack in the Gorodok operation along the [[Northern Dvina|Dvina]] netted 400 [[Red Army]] prisoners. The citation reads:\n\n<blockquote>He commanded the Gorodok column on 9\u201310 August 1919, with great gallantry and skill, and owing to the success of this column the forces on the right bank of the Dvina were able to capture all its objectives. During the enemy counter-attack from [[Selmenga]] on Gorodok he handled his men excellently. The enemy were repulsed with great loss, leaving 400 prisoners in our hands.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=31745 |supp=y|page=923|date=20 January 1920}}</ref></blockquote>\n[[File:Major Arthur Percival in Ireland 1921.jpg|upright|left|thumb|Major Percival in Ireland]]\n\n===Ireland===\nIn 1920 Percival served in [[Ireland]] against the [[Irish Republican Army]] (IRA) during the [[Irish War of Independence]], first as a company commander and later the [[intelligence officer]] of the 1st Battalion of the [[Essex Regiment]], in [[Kinsale]], [[County Cork]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nam.ac.uk/research/famous-units/essex-regiment|title=Essex Regiment|publisher=National Army Museum|accessdate=19 October 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020040854/http://www.nam.ac.uk/research/famous-units/essex-regiment|archivedate=20 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nPercival proved himself an energetic [[Guerrilla warfare#Counter-guerrilla warfare|counter-guerrilla]], noted for his aptitude for intelligence-gathering and the establishment of bicycle-riding 'Mobile Columns'. He was accused of brutality towards prisoners,<ref>Thompson, ''The Battle for Singapore'', p. 69.</ref> including the use of strikes of a rifle butt to the head, pincers to pull fingernails and burning cigarettes on the body. These accusations were substantiated by prisoners' testimony<ref name=\"O'Brien\">Statement by witness Patrick O'Brien, Bureau of Military History, http://www.bureauofmilitaryhistory.ie/r{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ... WS0812.pdf</ref> but the veracity of the accounts has been challenged by a journalist.<ref name=Burns>John Burns, 'Tom Barry \"lied about massacre\"', ''Sunday Times'' (19 April 1998).</ref>\n\nFollowing the IRA killing of a [[Royal Irish Constabulary]] sergeant outside [[Bandon, County Cork|Bandon]] church in July 1920, Percival captured [[Tom Hales (Irish republican)|Tom Hales]], commander of the IRA's [[3rd Cork Brigade]], and Patrick Harte, the brigade's quartermaster, for which he was appointed [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE). Both prisoners later claimed to have been repeatedly beaten and tortured while in custody. Hales alleged that a pair of pliers had been used on his lower body and to extract his fingernails. Harte suffered brain injury and died in a mental hospital in 1925. The claims of torture were denied by Percival and his colleagues, Hales being unable to produce any visible wounds{{cn|date=May 2017}} beyond missing teeth and Harte's head injury being officially recorded as the result of being rifle-butted upon arrest.<ref>Michael Collins, Tim Pat Coogan page 146</ref><ref>Irish Independent 5/6/1922.</ref><ref>Kivnig;Scapegoat</ref>{{fv|date=April 2019}} [[Ormonde Winter]], the head of British Intelligence in [[Dublin Castle]], later named Hales as an informer who had invented the story as an excuse for providing the names of his fellow IRA members in return for a lesser sentence.<ref>Narratives; British Intelligence in Ireland 1920-21-The Final Reports edited by Peter Hart page 82 {{ISBN|1-85918201-1}}</ref><ref>A Winter's Tale by Sir Ormonde Winter page 300</ref>\n\nThe IRA badly wanted to kill Percival, accusing him of running what they called the 'Essex Battalion Torture Squad'. A first attempted assassination by [[Tom Barry (soldier)|Tom Barry]] in [[Bandon, County Cork|Bandon]] failed when Percival departed from his dinnertime routine. \n\nIRA intelligence reports stated that for three nights in a row Percival had left the barracks at 7:45PM and proceeded to a certain house. On the fourth night Barry and another man waited for him from 7:30PM till 8:20PM but he made no appearance. The following day Barry found out that Percival had left the barracks at 6:00PM and was out raiding IRA houses while they were waiting for him.\n\nBarry later stated that Percival was \"easily the most vicious anti-Irish of all serving British officers\". <ref>Guerilla Days in Ireland, page 57-8 </ref>\n\nA second assassination squad was dispatched{{cn|date=May 2017}} to London in March 1921, but was forced to abandon the planned attack in [[Liverpool Street Station]] when they learned that the [[Metropolitan Police]] knew of their plans. [[David Lloyd George]] and [[Winston Churchill]] met Percival in 1921, when he was called as an expert witness during an [[inquiry into the Anglo-Irish War]].<ref>Thompson, ''The Battle for Singapore'', p69\u201370</ref>\n\nPercival would later deliver a series of lectures on his experiences in Ireland in which he stressed the importance of surprise and offensive action, intelligence-gathering, maintaining security and co-operation between the security forces.<ref>Sheehan, William (2005). ''British Voices from the Irish War of Independence 1918\u20131921: the words of British servicemen who were there. Collins Press, p. 167. {{ISBN|1903464897}}</ref>\nIn his reports Percival was scathing of the government's policy of the repeated release of IRA prisoners between 1916-1920 stating \"...as these men immediately returned to their homes and organised the murder of those members of the RIC who had been instrumental in effecting their arrests\".<ref>British Voices from the Irish War of Independence by William Sheehan {{ISBN|9781905172375}} p110</ref>  \n\nHistorian [[J.B.E. Hittle]] wrote that of all the British officers in Ireland \"Percival stood out for his violent, sadistic behaviour towards IRA prisoners, suspects and innocent civilians......He also participated in reprisals, burning farms and businesses in response to IRA attacks.<ref>{{Cite web |url =https://books.google.com.au/books?id=jeP_lM2vnk0C&pg=PA124&dq=arthur+percival+michael+collins+and+the+anglo+irish+war&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi5yfrxpfvYAhULuVMKHb0iBXkQ6AEIHTAA#v=onepage&q=arthur%20percival%20michael%20collins%20and%20the%20anglo%20irish%20war&f=false |title=Michael Collins and the Anglo Irish War: Britain's Counter Insurgency Failure}}</ref> By contrast Clifford Kinvig, Percival's biographer considers him to have been unfairly vilified by Republican propaganda  due to him being \"tireless in his attempt to destroy the spirit of the people and the organisation of the IRA\"<ref>Scapegoat; General Percival of Singapore by Clifford Kivnig p75 {{ISBN|185753171 X}} Hardcover</ref>\n\n===Staff officer===\nPercival attended the [[Staff College, Camberley]] from 1923<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=32790|page=608|date=26 January 1923}}</ref> to 1924, then commanded by General [[Edmund Ironside, 1st Baron Ironside|Edmund Ironside]], where he was taught by [[J.F.C. Fuller]], who was one of the few sympathetic reviewers of his book, ''The War in Malaya'', twenty-five years later. He impressed his instructors, who picked him out as one of eight students for accelerated promotion, and his fellow students who admired his cricketing skills. Following an appointment as major with the [[Cheshire Regiment]], he spent four years with the [[Nigeria Regiment]] of the [[Royal West African Frontier Force]] in [[West Africa]] as a [[staff officer]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33043|page=2921|date=1 May 1925}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33470|page=1345|date=26 February 1929}}</ref>  He was given brevet promotion to [[Lieutenant-Colonel (United Kingdom)|lieutenant-colonel]] in 1929.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33454|page=152|date=4 January 1929}}</ref>\n\n[[File:United Kingdom - England - London - Greenwich - Old Royal Naval College.jpg|thumb|right|The Royal Naval College, where Percival studied in 1930.]]\n\nIn 1930, Percival spent a year studying at the [[Royal Naval College, Greenwich]]. From 1931 to 1932, Percival was General Staff Officer Grade 2, an instructor at the Staff College. The College's commandant General Sir [[John Dill]], became Percival's mentor over the next 10 years, helping to ensure his prot\u00e9g\u00e9's advancement. Dill regarded Percival as a promising officer and wrote that \"he has an outstanding ability, wide military knowledge, good judgment and is a very quick and accurate worker\" but added \"he has not altogether an impressive presence and one may therefore fail, at first meeting him, to appreciate his sterling worth\".<ref>Thompson, p71</ref> With Dill's support, Percival was appointed to command the 2nd Battalion, the Cheshire Regiment from 1932<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33846|page=4627|date=15 July 1932}}</ref> to 1936, initially in [[Malta]]. In 1935, he attended the [[Royal College of Defence Studies|Imperial Defence College]].<ref name=\"Officers of the British Army\" />\n\nPercival was made a full [[colonel (United Kingdom)|colonel]] in March 1936,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34264|page=1657|date=13 March 1936}}</ref> and until 1938<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34557|pages=6139\u20136140|date=30 September 1938}}</ref> he was General Staff Officer Grade 1 in [[British Malaya|Malaya]], the [[Chief of staff (military)|Chief of Staff]] to [[General (United Kingdom)|General]] [[William Dobbie|Dobbie]], the [[General Officer Commanding]] in Malaya. During this time, he recognised that Singapore was no longer an isolated fortress.<ref>Hack and Blackburn, ''Did Singapore Have to Fall?: Churchill and the Impregnable Fortress'', p39</ref> He considered the possibility of the [[Empire of Japan|Japanese]] landing in [[Thailand]] to \"burgle Malaya by the backdoor<ref>Kinvig, p106</ref> and conducted an appraisal of the possibility of an attack being launched on Singapore from the North, which was supplied to the [[War Office]], and which Percival subsequently felt was similar to the plan followed by the Japanese in 1941.<ref name=\"percival1\">Percival, ''The War in Malaya'', Chapter 1</ref> He also supported Dobbie's unexecuted plan for the construction of fixed defences in Southern [[Johore]]. In March 1938, he returned to Britain and was (temporarily) promoted to [[brigadier]] on the General Staff, [[Aldershot Garrison|Aldershot Command]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34503|page=2594|date=19 April 1938}}</ref>\n\n==Second World War==\n{{further information|South-East Asian theatre of World War II}}\n[[File:Lieutenant General Arthur Percival.jpg|thumb|upright|Lieutenant-General Percival arriving by aircraft in Singapore in 1941 as the new General Officer Commanding Malaya.]]\n\nPercival was appointed Brigadier, General Staff, of the [[I Corps (United Kingdom)|I Corps]], [[British Expeditionary Force (World War II)|British Expeditionary Force]], commanded by General Dill, from 1939 to 1940. He was then promoted to acting [[Major-General (United Kingdom)|Major-General]],<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34800 |supp=y|page=1151|date=23 February 1940}}</ref> and in February 1940 briefly became General Officer Commanding (GOC) of the [[43rd (Wessex) Infantry Division]]. He was made [[Assistant Chief of the General Staff (United Kingdom)|Assistant Chief of the Imperial General Staff]] at the [[War Office]] in 1940 but asked for a transfer to an active command after the [[Operation Dynamo|Dunkirk evacuation]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34855 |supp=y|page=3091|date=21 May 1940}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34895 |supp=y|page=4273|date=9 July 1940}}</ref> Given command of the [[44th (Home Counties) Infantry Division]], he spent 9 months organising the [[British anti-invasion preparations of World War II|protection of {{convert|62|mi|km}}]] of the [[England|English]] coast from invasion.<ref name=\"percival2\">Percival, Chapter 2</ref> He was appointed a Companion of the [[Order of the Bath]] (CB) in the 1941 [[King's Birthday Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=35204 |supp=y|pages=3735\u20133736|date=27 June 1941}}</ref>\n\n===Percival's early assessment of the vulnerability of Singapore===\nIn 1936, Major-General [[William Dobbie]], then General Officer Commanding ([[Malaya Command|Malaya]]), made an inquiry into whether more forces were required on mainland Malaya to prevent the Japanese from establishing forward bases to attack Singapore. Percival, then his Chief Staff Officer, was tasked to draw up a tactical assessment of how the Japanese were most likely to attack.\nIn late 1937, his analysis duly confirmed that north [[Malay Peninsula|Malaya]] might become the critical battleground. The Japanese were likely to seize the east coast landing sites on [[Thailand]] and Malaya in order to capture aerodromes and achieve air superiority. This could serve as a prelude to further Japanese landings in [[Johore]] to disrupt communications northwards and enable the construction of another main base in North Borneo. From North Borneo, the final sea and air assault could be launched against eastern Singapore\u2014in particular the [[Changi]] area.<ref>Ong, Chit Chung (1997) ''Operation Matador : Britain's war plans against the Japanese 1918\u20131941''. Singapore : Times Academic Press.</ref>\n\n===General Officer Commanding (Malaya)===\nIn April 1941 Percival was promoted to acting [[Lieutenant-General (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant-General]],<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=35160 |supp=y|page=2731|date=9 May 1941}}</ref> and was appointed General Officer Commanding (GOC) Malaya. This was a significant promotion for him as he had never commanded an army [[Corps]]. He left Britain in a [[Sunderland flying boat]] and embarked on an arduous two-week, multi-stage flight via [[Gibraltar]], [[Malta]], [[Alexandria]] (where he was delayed by the [[Anglo-Iraqi War]]), [[Basra]], [[Karachi]] and [[Yangon|Rangoon]], where he was met by an [[Royal Air Force|RAF]] transport.<ref name=\"percival1\" />\n\nPercival had mixed feelings about his appointment, noting that \"In going to Malaya I realised that there was the double danger either of being left in an inactive command for some years if war did not break out in the East or, if it did, of finding myself involved in a pretty sticky business with the inadequate forces which are usually to be found in the distant parts of our [[British Empire|Empire]] in the early stages of a war.\"<ref name=\"percival2\" />\n\nFor much of the interwar period, Britain's defensive plan for Malaya had centred on the dispatch of a [[Royal Navy|naval]] fleet to the newly built [[Singapore Naval Base]]. Accordingly, the army's role was to defend Singapore and Southern [[Johore]]. While this plan had seemed adequate when the nearest Japanese base had been {{convert|1700|mi|km}} away, the outbreak of war in [[European Theatre of World War II|Europe]], combined with the partial Japanese occupation of the northern part of [[French Indochina]] and the signing of the [[Tripartite Pact]] in September 1940, had underlined the difficulty of a sea-based defence. Instead it was proposed to use the RAF to defend Malaya, at least until reinforcements could be dispatched from Britain. This led to the building of airfields in northern Malaya and along its east coast and the dispersal of the available army units around the peninsula to protect them.<ref>Percival, Chapter 3</ref>\n\nOn arrival, Percival set about training his inexperienced army; his Indian troops were particularly raw, with most of their experienced officers having been withdrawn to support the formation of new units as the Indian army expanded. Relying upon commercial aircraft or the Volunteer air force to overcome the shortage of RAF planes, he toured the peninsula and encouraged the building of defensive works around [[Jitra]].<ref>Percival, Chapter 4</ref> A training manual approved by Percival, ''Tactical Notes on Malaya'', was distributed to all units.\n\nIn July 1941 when the Japanese occupied southern Indochina, Britain, the [[United States]] and the [[Netherlands]] imposed economic [[international sanctions|sanctions]], freezing Japanese financial assets and cutting Japan from its supplies of [[petroleum|oil]], [[tin]] and [[rubber]]. The sanctions were aimed at pressuring Japan to abandon its [[Second Sino-Japanese War|involvement in China]]; instead, the Japanese government planned to seize the resources of South-East Asia from the European nations by force. Both the Japanese navy and army were mobilised, but for the moment an uneasy state of cold war persisted. British Commonwealth reinforcements continued to trickle into Malaya. On 2 December, the [[battleship]] [[HMS Prince of Wales (53)|HMS ''Prince of Wales'']] and the [[battle-cruiser]] [[HMS Repulse (1916)|HMS ''Repulse'']], escorted by four [[destroyer]]s, arrived in Singapore, the first time a battle fleet had been based there. (They were to have been accompanied by the aircraft carrier {{HMS|Indomitable|92|6}} to provide air cover but she had run aground in the Caribbean en route.) The following day [[Rear-Admiral]] [[Ernest John Spooner|Spooner]] hosted a dinner attended by the newly arrived Commander-in-Chief [[Eastern Fleet]], [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]] [[Thomas Phillips (Naval officer)|Sir Tom Phillips]], and Percival.<ref>Percival, Chapter 7</ref>\n\n===Japanese attack and British surrender===\n{{main article|Japanese invasion of Malaya|Battle of Singapore}}\n[[File:Pacific War - Malaya 1941-42 - Map.jpg|thumb|350px|Malaya Command and the [[Japanese invasion of Malaya]]]]\n\nOn 8 December 1941 the [[Twenty-Fifth Army (Japan)|Japanese 25th Army]] under the command of Lieutenant-General [[Tomoyuki Yamashita]] launched an [[amphibious assault]] on the Malay Peninsula (one hour before the [[attack on Pearl Harbor]]; the difference in date was because the two places lie on opposite sides of the [[international date line]]). That night the first Japanese invasion force arrived at [[Kota Bharu]] on Malaya's east coast. This was just a diversionary force, and the main landings took place the next day at [[Singora]] and [[Pattani (town)|Pattani]] on the south-eastern coast of [[Thailand]], with troops rapidly deploying over the border into northern Malaya.\n\nOn 10 December Percival issued a stirring, if ultimately ineffective, Special Order of the Day:\n<blockquote>In this hour of trial the General Officer Commanding calls upon all ranks Malaya Command for a determined and sustained effort to safeguard Malaya and the adjoining British territories. The eyes of the Empire are upon us. Our whole position in the Far East is at stake. The struggle may be long and grim but let us all resolve to stand fast come what may and to prove ourselves worthy of the great trust which has been placed in us.<ref>Percival, chapter 9</ref></blockquote>\n\n[[File:Royal Engineers prepare to blow up a bridge in Malaya.jpg|thumb|[[Royal Engineers]] prepare to blow up a bridge during the retreat.]]\n\nThe Japanese advanced rapidly, and on 27 January 1942 Percival ordered a general retreat across the [[Johore Strait]] to the island of [[Singapore]] and organised a defence along the length of the island's {{convert|70|mi|km|sing=on}} coast line. But the Japanese did not dawdle, and on 8 February Japanese troops landed on the northwest corner of Singapore island. After a week of fighting on the island, Percival held his final command conference at 9&nbsp;am on 15 February in [[the Battle Box]] of [[Fort Canning]]. The Japanese had already occupied approximately half of Singapore and it was clear that the island would soon fall.  Having been told that ammunition and water would both run out by the following day, Percival agreed to surrender. The Japanese at this point were running low on artillery shells, but Percival did not know this.\n\nThe Japanese insisted that Percival himself march under a [[white flag]] to the [[Old Ford Motor Factory]] in [[Bukit Timah]] to negotiate the surrender. A Japanese officer present noted that he looked \"pale, thin and tired\".<ref>Warren, p265</ref> After a brief disagreement, when Percival insisted that the British keep 1,000 men under arms in Singapore to preserve order, which Yamashita finally conceded, it was agreed at 6:10&nbsp;pm that the British Empire troops would lay down their arms and cease resistance at 8:30&nbsp;pm. This was in spite of instructions from Prime Minister [[Winston Churchill]] for prolonged resistance.<ref name=\"Morris\"/> The [[Pacific War]] was just ten weeks old.\n\nA common view holds that 138,708 [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] personnel surrendered or were killed by fewer than 30,000 Japanese. However, the former figure includes nearly 50,000 troops captured or killed during the [[Battle of Malaya]], and perhaps 15,000 base troops. Many of the other troops were tired and under-equipped following their retreat from the [[Malayan peninsula]]. Conversely, the latter number represents only the front-line troops available for the invasion of Singapore. British Empire battle casualties since 8 December amounted to 7,500 killed and 11,000 wounded. Japanese losses totalled around 3,500 killed and 6,100 wounded.<ref>Thompson, p9 and p424</ref>\n\n===Culpability for the fall of Singapore===\n[[File:Singaporesurrender.jpg|thumb|Lieutenant-General Percival led by a Japanese officer, marches under a flag of [[truce]] to negotiate the capitulation of Allied forces in Singapore, on 15 February 1942. It was the largest surrender of British-led forces in history.]]\nChurchill viewed the fall of Singapore to be \"the worst disaster and largest capitulation in British history.\" However, the British defence was that the [[Middle East]] and the [[Soviet Union]] had all received higher priorities in the allocation of men and material, so the desired [[air force]] strength of 300 to 500 aircraft was never reached, and whereas the Japanese invaded with over two hundred [[tank]]s, the British Army in Malaya did not have a single tank.<ref>Kinvig.</ref> In ''The War in Malaya'' Percival himself cites this as the major factor for the defeat stating that the 'war material which might have saved Singapore was sent to Russia and the Middle East'. However he also concedes that Britain was engaged in 'a life and death struggle in the West' and that 'this decision, however painful and regrettable, was inevitable and right'.<ref>The War in Malaya; Authur Percival p306</ref>\n\nIn 1918, Percival had been described as \"a slim, soft spoken man... with a proven reputation for bravery and organisational powers\"<ref>Kinvig, p. 47.</ref> but by 1945 this description had been turned on its head with even Percival's defenders describing him as \"something of a damp squib\".<ref>Kinvig, p. 242.</ref> The fall of Singapore switched Percival's reputation to that of an ineffective \"staff wallah\", lacking ruthlessness and aggression, even though few doubted that he was a brave and determined officer. Over six feet in height and lanky, with a clipped moustache and two protruding teeth, and unphotogenic, Percival was an easy target for a caricaturist, being described as \"tall, bucktoothed and lightly built\".<ref>Warren, p. 29.</ref> There was no doubt his presentation lacked impact as \"his manner was low key and he was a poor public speaker with the cusp of a lisp\".<ref>Kinvig, ''General Percival and the Fall of Singapore'', p. 241.</ref>\n[[File:BritishSurrender.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Lieutenant-General Yamashita (seated, centre) thumps the table with his fist to emphasise his demand for unconditional surrender. Lieutenant-General Percival sits between his officers, his clenched hand to his mouth. (Photo from [[Imperial War Museum]]).]]\n\nIt has been argued{{by whom|date=November 2015}} that Percival's colleagues bear a share of the responsibility of defeat. Air Chief Marshal Sir [[Henry Robert Moore Brooke-Popham|Robert Brooke-Popham]], the [[Commander-in-Chief]] of the [[British Far East Command]], refused Percival permission to launch [[Operation Matador (1941)|Operation Matador]] in advance of the Japanese landings in Thailand, not wishing to run any risk of provoking the coming war. Brooke-Popham also had a reputation for falling asleep in meetings and not arguing forcefully for the air reinforcements required to defend Malaya. Admiral [[Thomas Spencer Vaughan Phillips|Tom Phillips]]' leadership of [[Force Z]] led to his demise and the [[Sinking of Prince of Wales and Repulse|destruction of the British fleet]] on 10 December 1941, early in the campaign.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\n[[Peter Wykeham]] suggested that the government in London was more to blame than any of the British commanders in the Far East. Despite repeated requests, the British government did not provide the necessary reinforcements and they denied Brooke-Popham \u2013 and therefore Percival \u2013 permission to enter neutral Thailand before it was too late to put in place forward defences.<ref name=\"ODNB\">{{cite journal| last =Wykeham| first =Peter| author2 =Thomas Paul Ofcansky| title =Popham, Sir (Henry) Robert Moore Brooke| work =Oxford Dictionary of National Biography| url =http://www.oxforddnb.com/index/32/101032096/| date =January 2008| doi =10.1093/ref:odnb/32096}}</ref>\n\nMoreover, Percival had difficulties with his subordinates [[Lewis Heath|Sir Lewis \"Piggy\" Heath]], commanding [[Indian III Corps]], and the independent-minded [[Gordon Bennett (general)|Gordon Bennett]], commanding the [[Australian 8th Division]]. The former officer had been senior to Percival prior to his appointment as GOC (Malaya). Bennett was full of confidence in his [[Australia]]n troops and his own ability, but faced a mixed reaction in Australia when he escaped from Singapore immediately after its surrender.\n\nPercival was ultimately responsible for the men who served under him, and with other officers \u2013 notably Major-General [[David Murray-Lyon]], commander of the [[Indian 11th Infantry Division]] \u2013 he had shown a willingness to replace them when he felt their performance was not up to scratch. Perhaps his greatest mistake was to resist the building of fixed defences in either Johore or the north shore of Singapore, dismissing them in the face of repeated requests to start construction from his Chief Engineer, Brigadier [[Ivan Simson]], with the comment \"Defences are bad for morale \u2013 for both troops and civilians\".<ref>Thompson, p. 182.</ref> In doing so, Percival threw away the potential advantages he could have derived from the 6,000 engineers under his command and perhaps missed his best chance to blunt the danger posed by the Japanese tanks.\n\nPercival also insisted on defending the north-eastern shore of Singapore most heavily, against the advice of the [[American-British-Dutch-Australian Command|Allied supreme commander in South East Asia]], General [[Archibald Percival Wavell, 1st Earl Wavell|Archibald Wavell]]. Percival was perhaps fixed on his responsibilities for defending the Singapore Naval Base.<ref>Dixon, ''[[On the Psychology of Military Incompetence]]'', p. 143.</ref> He also spread his forces thinly around the island and kept few units as a strategic reserve. When the Japanese attack came in the west, the [[Australian 22nd Brigade]] took the brunt of the assault.<ref>Thompson, p. 414.</ref> Percival refused to reinforce them as he continued to believe that the main assault would occur in the north east.<ref>Thompson, p. 430.</ref>\n\n===Captivity===\nPercival himself was briefly held prisoner in [[Changi Prison]], where \"the defeated GOC could be seen sitting head in hands, outside the married quarters he now shared with seven brigadiers, a colonel, his ADC and cook-sergeant. He discussed feelings with few, spent hours walking around the extensive compound, ruminating on the reverse and what might have been\".<ref>Kinvig, p221</ref> In the belief that it would improve discipline, he reconstituted a Malaya Command, complete with staff appointments, and helped occupy his fellow prisoners with lectures on the [[Battle of France]].<ref>MacArthur, ''Surviving the Sword: Prisoners of the Japanese 1942\u201345'', p188</ref>\n[[File:Douglas MacArthur signs formal surrender.jpg|left|thumb|The signing of the Japanese surrender; [[Douglas MacArthur|MacArthur]] (sitting), behind him are Generals Percival (background) and [[Jonathan M. Wainwright (general)|Wainwright]] (foreground).]]\n\nAlong with the other senior British captives above the rank of colonel, Percival was removed from Singapore in August 1942. First he was imprisoned in [[Taiwan|Formosa]] and then sent on to [[Manchuria]], where he was held with several dozen other VIP captives, including the [[United States|American]] General [[Jonathan M. Wainwright (general)|Jonathan Wainwright]], in a [[prisoner-of-war camp]] near [[Xi'an District, Mudanjiang|Hsian]], about {{convert|100|mi|km}} to the north east of [[Mukden]].\n\nAs the war drew to an end, an [[Office of Strategic Services|OSS]] team removed the prisoners from Hsian. Percival was then taken, along with Wainwright, to stand immediately behind General [[Douglas MacArthur]] as he confirmed the terms of the Japanese surrender aboard [[USS Missouri (BB-63)|USS ''Missouri'' (BB-63)]] in [[Tokyo Bay]] on 2 September 1945.<ref>''Battleship Missouri Memorial'', {{cite web|url=http://www.ussmissouri.org/surrender.aspx |title=Surrender |accessdate=2006-02-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051109061015/http://ussmissouri.org/surrender.aspx |archivedate=9 November 2005 |df=dmy }} , accessed 2 February 2006</ref> Afterwards, MacArthur gave Percival a pen he had used to sign the treaty.<ref>Warren, p286</ref>\n\nPercival and Wainwright then returned together to the [[Philippines]] to witness the surrender of the Japanese army there, which in a twist of fate was commanded by General Yamashita. Yamashita was momentarily surprised to see his former captive at the ceremony; on this occasion Percival refused to shake Yamashita's hand, angered by the mistreatment of POWs in Singapore. The flag carried by Percival's party on the way to Bukit Timah was also a witness to this reversal of fortunes, being flown when the Japanese formally surrendered Singapore back to Lord [[Louis Mountbatten, 1st Earl Mountbatten of Burma|Louis Mountbatten]].<ref>Morris, p458</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nPercival returned to the United Kingdom in September 1945 to write his despatch at the [[War Office]] but this was revised by the [[Her Majesty's Government|UK Government]] and only published in 1948.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=38215|pages=1245\u20131346|date=20 February 1948}}</ref> He retired from the army in 1946 with the honorary rank of lieutenant-general but the pension of his substantive rank of major-general.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=37706|page=4347|date=27 August 1946}}</ref> Thereafter, he held appointments connected with the county of Hertfordshire, where he lived at Bullards in [[Widford, Hertfordshire|Widford]]: he was Honorary Colonel of [[479th (Hertfordshire Yeomanry) Heavy Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery]], ([[Territorial Army (United Kingdom)|T.A.]]) from 1949 to 1954<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=38762|page=5465|date=18 November 1949}}</ref><ref>Col J.D. Sainsbury, ''The Hertfordshire Yeomanry Regiments, Royal Artillery, Part 2: The Heavy Anti-Aircraft Regiment 1938\u20131945 and the Searchlight Battery 1937\u20131945; Part 3: The Post-war Units 1947\u20132002'', Welwyn: Hertfordshire Yeomanry and Artillery Trust/Hart Books, 2003, {{ISBN|0-948527-06-4}}.</ref> and acted as one of the [[Deputy Lieutenant]]s of Hertfordshire in 1951.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=39412|page=6600|date=18 December 1951}}</ref> He continued his relationship with the Cheshire Regiment being appointed Colonel of the Cheshire Regiment between 1950 and 1955;<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=38940 |supp=y|page=3037|date=13 June 1950}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=40680 |supp=y|page=208|date=6 January 1956}}</ref> an association continued by his son, [[Brigadier]] James Percival who became Colonel of the Regiment between 1992 and 1999.\n\nWhile General Wainwright had become a public hero on his return to the United States, Percival found himself disparaged for his leadership in Malaya, even by Lieutenant-General Heath, his erstwhile subordinate. Percival's 1949 memoir, ''The War in Malaya'', did little to quell this criticism, being a restrained rather than self-serving account of the campaign. Unusual for a British lieutenant-general, Percival was not awarded a [[British honours system|knighthood]].\n\nPercival was respected for the time he had spent as a Japanese [[prisoner of war]]. Serving as life president of the [[Far East Prisoners of War]] Association (FEPOW), he pushed for compensation for his fellow captives, eventually helping to obtain a token \u00a35 million of frozen Japanese assets for this cause. This was distributed by the FEPOW Welfare Trust, on which Percival served as Chairman.<ref name = \"MacArthur442\">MacArthur, p. 442.</ref> He led protests against the film ''[[The Bridge on the River Kwai]]'' when it was released in 1957, obtaining the addition of an on-screen statement that the movie was a work of fiction. He also worked as President of the Hertfordshire [[British Red Cross]] and was made an Officer of the [[Venerable Order of Saint John]] in 1964.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=43367|pages=5540\u20135542|date=26 June 1964}}</ref>\n\nPercival died at the age of 78 on 31 January 1966, in [[King Edward VII's Hospital Sister Agnes|King Edward VII's Hospital for Officers]], Beaumont Street in [[City of Westminster|Westminster]], and is buried in the churchyard at [[Widford, Hertfordshire|Widford]] in Hertfordshire.<ref>http://kementah.blogspot.com.au/2017/06/battle-for-malaya-and-fall-of-singapore.html</ref> [[John Leonard Wilson|Leonard Wilson]], formerly the [[Bishop of Singapore]], gave the address at his memorial service, which was held in [[St Martin-in-the-Fields]].\n\n===Family===\nOn 27 July 1927 Percival married Margaret Elizabeth \"Betty\" MacGregor Greer in [[Holy Trinity Brompton Church|Holy Trinity Church]], [[Brompton, London|Brompton]]. She was the daughter of Thomas MacGregor Greer of Tallylagan Manor, a [[Protestantism|Protestant]] [[linen]] merchant from [[County Tyrone]] in [[Northern Ireland]]. They had met during his tour of duty in Ireland but it had taken Percival several years to propose. They had two children. A daughter, Dorinda Margery, was born in Greenwich and became [[Baron Dunleath|Lady Dunleath]]. Alfred James MacGregor, their son, was born in [[Singapore]] and served in the British Army.\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Arthur Ernest Percival}}\n* [[Operation Krohcol]]\n* [[Shenton Thomas|Sir Shenton Thomas]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* [[Tom Barry (soldier)|Barry, Tom]], ''Guerilla Days in Ireland'', Dublin, 1949\n* Bose, Romen, \"SECRETS OF THE BATTLEBOX: The role and history of Britain's Command HQ during the Malayan Campaign\", Marshall Cavendish, Singapore, 2005\n* Coogan, Tim Pat. \"Michael Collins\". {{ISBN|0-09-968580-9}}\n* Dixon, Norman F, ''On the Psychology of Military Incompetence'', London, 1976\n* Hack, Karl and Blackburn, Kevin, ''Did Singapore Have to Fall?: Churchill and the Impregnable Fortress'', RoutledgeCurzon, 2003, {{ISBN|0-415-30803-8}}\n* [[John Keegan|Keegan, John]] (editor), ''Churchill's Generals'', Abacus History, 1999, {{ISBN|0-349-11317-3}}\n* Kinvig, Clifford, ''General Percival and the Fall of Singapore'', in ''60 Years On: the Fall of Singapore Revisited'', Eastern University Press, Singapore, 2003\n* [[Kinvig, Clifford]], ''Scapegoat: General Percival of Singapore'', London, 1996. {{ISBN|0-241-10583-8}}\n* ''[[London Gazette]]''\n* MacArthur, Brian, ''Surviving the Sword: Prisoners of the Japanese 1942\u201345'', Abacus, {{ISBN|0-349-11937-6}}\n* ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'', Volume 43, available at [http://www.oxforddnb.com/ Oxford Dictionary of National Biography website]\n* [[Jan Morris|Morris, James]] ''Farewell the Trumpets'', Penguin Books, 1979\n* Percival, Arthur Ernest ''The War in Malaya'', London, Eyre & Spottiswoode, 1949. Extracts from the report used as the basis of this book are at [http://www.fepow-community.org.uk/arthur_lane/Percivals_Report/] accessed 2 February 2006 and the references here are to this report\n* Ryan, Meda. ''Tom Barry: IRA Freedom Fighter'', Cork, 2003\n* Smith, Colin, ''Singapore Burning: Heroism and Surrender in World War II'', Penguin Books, {{ISBN|0-14-101036-3}}\n* [[Sir John Smyth, 1st Baronet|Smyth, John George]], ''Percival and the Tragedy of Singapore'', MacDonald and Company, 1971. ASIN B0006CDC1Q\n* [[A. J. P. Taylor|Taylor, A. J. P.]] ''English History 1914\u20131945'', Oxford University Press, 1975\n* Thompson, Peter, ''The Battle for Singapore'', London, 2005, {{ISBN|0-7499-5068-4}} HB\n* Warren, Alan, ''Singapore 1942: Britain's Greatest Defeat'', Hambledon Continuum, 2001, {{ISBN|1-85285-328-X}}\n{{refend}}\n\n===References===\n<!--This article uses the Cite.php citation mechanism. If you would like more information on how to add footnotes to this article, please see http://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Extension:Cite/Cite.php -->\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.unithistories.com/officers/Army_officers_P02.html#Percival_AE British Army Officers 1939\u22121945]\n*[http://www.generals.dk/general/Percival/Arthur_Ernest/Great_Britain.html Generals of World War II]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Arthur Floyer-Acland]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[43rd (Wessex) Infantry Division|GOC 43rd (Wessex) Infantry Division]]|years=February\u2013April 1940}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Robert Pollok (British Army officer)|Robert Pollok]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Edmund Osborne]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[44th (Home Counties) Division|GOC 44th (Home Counties) Infantry Division]]|years=1940\u20131941}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Noel Mason-MacFarlane]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lionel Vivian Bond|Sir Lionel Bond]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Malaya Command|GOC Malaya Command]]|years=1941\u20131942}}\n{{s-aft|after=Fell to Japan}}\n|-\n{{s-hon}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Geoffrey Harding]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Cheshire Regiment|Colonel of the Cheshire Regiment]]|years=1950\u20131955}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Thomas Brodie]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n\n\n\n\n<br />\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Percival, Arthur}}\n[[Category:1887 births]]\n[[Category:1966 deaths]]\n[[Category:Bedfordshire and Hertfordshire Regiment officers]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of the Russian Civil War]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:British Army generals of World War II]]\n[[Category:People of British Malaya]]\n[[Category:British military personnel of the Irish War of Independence]]\n[[Category:British World War II prisoners of war]]\n[[Category:Cheshire Regiment officers]]\n[[Category:Essex Regiment officers]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Royal Naval College, Greenwich]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Staff College, Camberley]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal College of Defence Studies]]\n[[Category:Military of Singapore under British rule]]\n[[Category:People from Widford, Hertfordshire]]\n[[Category:People educated at Rugby School]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Croix de Guerre 1914\u20131918 (France)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Military Cross]]\n[[Category:Royal West African Frontier Force officers]]\n[[Category:World War II prisoners of war held by Japan]]\n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n  \n\n \n \n \n \n \n \n\n[[Category:Military history of Malaya during World War II]]\n[[Category:People of colonial Nigeria]]\n[[Category:British expatriates in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Hertfordshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British army officer in the First and Second World Wars}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|honorific_prefix = \n|name             = Arthur Ernest Percival\n|honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|CB|DSO1|OBE|MC|OStJ|DL}}\n|image= Arthur Percival.jpg{{!}}border\n|image_size= \n|alt= \n|caption= Percival, pictured here as [[General officer commanding|GOC]] [[Malaya Command]], December 1941\n|nickname=\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1887|12|26|df=yes}}\n|birth_place= [[Aspenden]], [[Hertfordshire]], England\n|death_date= {{death date and age|1966|1|31|1887|12|26|df=yes}}\n|death_place= [[Westminster]], [[London]], England\n|placeofburial=\n|allegiance= United Kingdom\n|branch= {{army|United Kingdom}}\n|serviceyears= 1914\u20131946\n|servicenumber= 8785\n|rank= [[Lieutenant-general (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant-General]]\n|unit= [[Essex Regiment]]<br/>[[Cheshire Regiment]]\n|commands= [[Malaya Command]] (1941\u20131942)<br/>[[44th (Home Counties) Division|44th (Home Counties) Infantry Division]] (1940\u20131941)<br/>[[43rd (Wessex) Infantry Division]] (1940)<br/>2nd Battalion, [[Cheshire Regiment]] (1932\u20131934)<br/>7th (Service) Battalion, [[Bedfordshire and Hertfordshire Regiment|Bedfordshire Regiment]] (1918)\n|battles= [[First World War]]\n* [[Battle of the Somme]]\n* [[Spring Offensive]]\n[[Russian Civil War]]\n* [[North Russia Campaign]]\n[[Anglo-Irish War]]<br/>[[Second World War]]\n* [[Malayan Campaign]]\n* [[Battle of Singapore]]{{surrendered}}\n|awards= [[Companion of the Order of the Bath]]<br/>[[Distinguished Service Order]] & [[Medal bar|Bar]]<br/>[[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]]<br/>[[Military Cross]]<br/>[[Mentioned in Despatches]] (3)<br/>[[Croix de guerre 1914\u20131918 (France)|Croix de guerre]] (France)\n| memorials     =\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Margaret Elizabeth MacGregor Greer|27 July 1927|5 October 1953|end=died}}\n| children      = {{unbulleted list|Dorinda Margery Percival (daughter)|Alfred James MacGregor Percival (son)}}\n| relations     =\n| laterwork     = \n| signature     = \n| signature_size =\n| signature_alt =\n}}\n\n[[Lieutenant-general (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant-General]] '''Arthur Ernest Percival''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|CB|DSO1|OBE|MC|OStJ|DL}} (26 December 1887 \u2013 31 January 1966) was a senior [[British Army]] officer. He saw service in the [[First World War]] and built a successful military career during the [[interwar period]] but is most noted for his defeat in the [[Second World War]], when he commanded [[Commonwealth of Nations|British Commonwealth]] forces during the Japanese [[Malayan Campaign]] and the subsequent [[Battle of Singapore]].\n\nPercival's surrender to the invading [[Imperial Japanese Army]] force, the largest surrender in [[Military history of the United Kingdom|British military history]], undermined Britain's prestige as an imperial power in [[East Asia]].<ref>Taylor, ''English History 1914\u20131945'', p657</ref><ref name=\"Morris\">Morris, ''Farewell the Trumpets'', p452</ref> His defenders, such as [[Sir John Smyth, 1st Baronet|Sir John Smyth]], have argued that under-funding of [[British Malaya|Malaya]]'s defences and the inexperienced, under-equipped nature of the Commonwealth army, not Percival's leadership, were ultimately to blame.<ref>Smyth, ''Percival and the Tragedy of Singapore''</ref>\n\n==Early days==\n\n===Childhood and employment===\nArthur Ernest Percival was born on 26 December 1887 in Aspenden Lodge, [[Aspenden]] near [[Buntingford]] in [[Hertfordshire]], England, the second son of Alfred Reginald and Edith Percival (n\u00e9e Miller). His father was the Land Agent of the Hamel's Park estate and his mother came from a [[Lancashire]] [[cotton]] family.<ref name=\"Officers of the British Army\">{{cite web|url=http://www.unithistories.com/officers/Army_officers_P02.html#Percival_AE|title=British Army officer histories|publisher=Unit Histories|accessdate=2017-06-23}}</ref>\n\nPercival was initially schooled locally in [[Bengeo]]. Then in 1901, he was sent to [[Rugby School|Rugby]] with his more academically successful brother, where he was a boarder in School House. A moderate pupil, he studied [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] and [[Latin]] but was described by a teacher as \"not a good classic\".<ref>Kinvig, ''Scapegoat: General Percival of Singapore'', p5</ref> Percival's only qualification on leaving in 1906 was a higher school certificate. He was a more successful sportsman, playing [[cricket]] and [[tennis]] and running [[cross-country running|cross country]].<ref>Smith, ''Singapore Burning: Heroism and Surrender in World War II'', p23</ref> He also rose to [[Colour Sergeant|colour sergeant]] in the school's Volunteer Rifle Corps. However, his military career began at a comparatively late age: although a member of Youngsbury Rifle Club, he was still working as a clerk for the iron ore merchants Naylor, Benzon & Company Limited in London, which he had joined in 1914, when the [[World War I]] broke out.\n\n===Enlistment and First World War===\nPercival enlisted on the first day of the war as a [[Private (rank)|private]] in the [[Officer Training Corps]] of the [[Inns of Court]], at the age of 26, and was promoted after five weeks' basic training to temporary [[second lieutenant]].<ref name=commission>{{London Gazette|issue=29058 |supp=y|pages=1176\u20131179|date=2 February 1915}}</ref> Nearly one third of his fellow recruits would be dead by the end of the war. By November Percival had been promoted to [[captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=29050|page=802|date=26 January 1915}}</ref>  The following year he was despatched to [[France]] with the newly formed 7th (Service) Battalion of the [[Bedfordshire Regiment]],<ref name=commission /> which became part of the 54th Brigade, [[18th (Eastern) Division]] in February 1915. The first day of the [[Battle of the Somme]] (1 July 1916) left Percival unscathed, but in September he was badly wounded in four places by [[Shrapnel shell|shrapnel]], as he led his company in an assault on the [[Schwaben Redoubt]], beyond the ruins of [[Thiepval]] village, and was awarded the [[Military Cross]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=29824 |supp=y|pages=11044\u201311063|date=14 November 1916}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Wiltshire Regiment Thiepval 7 August 1916.jpg|thumb|Near [[Thiepval]], 7 August. Photo by [[Ernest Brooks (photographer)|Ernest Brooks]].]]\n\nPercival took a regular commission as a captain with the [[Essex Regiment]] in October 1916,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=29783|page=9864|date=13 October 1916}}</ref> whilst recovering from his injuries in hospital. He was appointed a temporary [[major (United Kingdom)|major]] in his original regiment.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=30038 |supp=y|page=4042|date=27 April 1917}}</ref> In 1917, he became battalion commander with the temporary rank of [[Lieutenant-Colonel (United Kingdom)|lieutenant-colonel]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=30632 |supp=y|page=4550|date=12 April 1918}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=31003 |supp=y|page=13282|date=8 November 1918}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=31035 |supp=y|page=14044|date=26 November 1918}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=31220 |supp=y|page=3257|date=7 March 1919}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=32233 |supp=y|page=1434|date=18 February 1921}}</ref> During [[German Empire|Germany]]'s [[Spring Offensive]], Percival led a counter-attack that saved a unit of French artillery from capture, winning a [[Croix de guerre 1914\u20131918 (France)|Croix de Guerre]].<ref>Smith, p24</ref> For a short period in May 1918, he acted as commander of the 54th Brigade. He was given [[brevet (military)|brevet]] promotion to major,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=31092 |supp=y|pages=15\u201316|date=24 June 1921}}</ref> and awarded the [[Distinguished Service Order]], with his citation noting his \"power of command and knowledge of tactics\".<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=32371 |supp=y|page=5096|date=24 June 1921}}</ref> He ended the war as a respected soldier, described as \"very efficient\" and was recommended for the [[Staff College, Camberley|Staff College]].<ref>Keegan, ''Churchill's Generals'', p257</ref>\n\n==Between the wars==\n\n===Russia===\nPercival's studies were delayed in 1919 when he decided to volunteer for service with the [[Arkhangelsk|Archangel]] Command of the British Military Mission during the [[North Russia Campaign]] of the [[Russian Civil War]]. Acting as second-in-command of the 45th [[The Royal Fusiliers (City of London Regiment)|Royal Fusiliers]], he earned a bar to his DSO in August, when his attack in the Gorodok operation along the [[Northern Dvina|Dvina]] netted 400 [[Red Army]] prisoners. The citation reads:\n\n<blockquote>He commanded the Gorodok column on 9\u201310 August 1919, with great gallantry and skill, and owing to the success of this column the forces on the right bank of the Dvina were able to capture all its objectives. During the enemy counter-attack from [[Selmenga]] on Gorodok he handled his men excellently. The enemy were repulsed with great loss, leaving 400 prisoners in our hands.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=31745 |supp=y|page=923|date=20 January 1920}}</ref></blockquote>\n[[File:Major Arthur Percival in Ireland 1921.jpg|upright|left|thumb|Major Percival in Ireland]]\n\n===Ireland===\nIn 1920 Percival served in [[Ireland]] against the [[Irish Republican Army]] (IRA) during the [[Irish War of Independence]], first as a company commander and later the [[intelligence officer]] of the 1st Battalion of the [[Essex Regiment]], in [[Kinsale]], [[County Cork]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nam.ac.uk/research/famous-units/essex-regiment|title=Essex Regiment|publisher=National Army Museum|accessdate=19 October 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020040854/http://www.nam.ac.uk/research/famous-units/essex-regiment|archivedate=20 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nPercival proved himself an energetic [[Guerrilla warfare#Counter-guerrilla warfare|counter-guerrilla]], noted for his aptitude for intelligence-gathering and the establishment of bicycle-riding 'Mobile Columns'. He was accused of brutality towards prisoners,<ref>Thompson, ''The Battle for Singapore'', p. 69.</ref> including the use of strikes of a rifle butt to the head, pincers to pull fingernails and burning cigarettes on the body. These accusations were substantiated by prisoners' testimony<ref name=\"O'Brien\">Statement by witness Patrick O'Brien, Bureau of Military History, http://www.bureauofmilitaryhistory.ie/r{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ... WS0812.pdf</ref> but the veracity of the accounts has been challenged by a journalist.<ref name=Burns>John Burns, 'Tom Barry \"lied about massacre\"', ''Sunday Times'' (19 April 1998).</ref>\n\nFollowing the IRA killing of a [[Royal Irish Constabulary]] sergeant outside [[Bandon, County Cork|Bandon]] church in July 1920, Percival captured [[Tom Hales (Irish republican)|Tom Hales]], commander of the IRA's [[3rd Cork Brigade]], and Patrick Harte, the brigade's quartermaster, for which he was appointed [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE). Both prisoners later claimed to have been repeatedly beaten and tortured while in custody. Hales alleged that a pair of pliers had been used on his lower body and to extract his fingernails. Harte suffered brain injury and died in a mental hospital in 1925. The claims of torture were denied by Percival and his colleagues, Hales being unable to produce any visible wounds{{cn|date=May 2017}} beyond missing teeth and Harte's head injury being officially recorded as the result of being rifle-butted upon arrest.<ref>Michael Collins, Tim Pat Coogan page 146</ref><ref>Irish Independent 5/6/1922.</ref><ref>Kivnig;Scapegoat</ref>{{fv|date=April 2019}} [[Ormonde Winter]], the head of British Intelligence in [[Dublin Castle]], later named Hales as an informer who had invented the story as an excuse for providing the names of his fellow IRA members in return for a lesser sentence.<ref>Narratives; British Intelligence in Ireland 1920-21-The Final Reports edited by Peter Hart page 82 {{ISBN|1-85918201-1}}</ref><ref>A Winter's Tale by Sir Ormonde Winter page 300</ref>\n\nThe IRA badly wanted to kill Percival, accusing him of running what they called the 'Essex Battalion Torture Squad'. A first attempted assassination by [[Tom Barry (soldier)|Tom Barry]] in [[Bandon, County Cork|Bandon]] failed when Percival departed from his dinnertime routine. \n\nIRA intelligence reports stated that for three nights in a row Percival had left the barracks at 7:45PM and proceeded to a certain house. On the fourth night Barry and another man waited for him from 7:30PM till 8:20PM but he made no appearance. The following day Barry found out that Percival had left the barracks at 6:00PM and was out raiding IRA houses while they were waiting for him.\n\nBarry later stated that Percival was \"easily the most vicious anti-Irish of all serving British officers\". <ref>Guerilla Days in Ireland, page 57-8 </ref>\n\nA second assassination squad was dispatched{{cn|date=May 2017}} to London in March 1921, but was forced to abandon the planned attack in [[Liverpool Street Station]] when they learned that the [[Metropolitan Police]] knew of their plans. [[David Lloyd George]] and [[Winston Churchill]] met Percival in 1921, when he was called as an expert witness during an [[inquiry into the Anglo-Irish War]].<ref>Thompson, ''The Battle for Singapore'', p69\u201370</ref>\n\nPercival would later deliver a series of lectures on his experiences in Ireland in which he stressed the importance of surprise and offensive action, intelligence-gathering, maintaining security and co-operation between the security forces.<ref>Sheehan, William (2005). ''British Voices from the Irish War of Independence 1918\u20131921: the words of British servicemen who were there. Collins Press, p. 167. {{ISBN|1903464897}}</ref>\nIn his reports Percival was scathing of the government's policy of the repeated release of IRA prisoners between 1916-1920 stating \"...as these men immediately returned to their homes and organised the murder of those members of the RIC who had been instrumental in effecting their arrests\".<ref>British Voices from the Irish War of Independence by William Sheehan {{ISBN|9781905172375}} p110</ref>  \n\nHistorian [[J.B.E. Hittle]] wrote that of all the British officers in Ireland \"Percival stood out for his violent, sadistic behaviour towards IRA prisoners, suspects and innocent civilians......He also participated in reprisals, burning farms and businesses in response to IRA attacks.<ref>{{Cite web |url =https://books.google.com.au/books?id=jeP_lM2vnk0C&pg=PA124&dq=arthur+percival+michael+collins+and+the+anglo+irish+war&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi5yfrxpfvYAhULuVMKHb0iBXkQ6AEIHTAA#v=onepage&q=arthur%20percival%20michael%20collins%20and%20the%20anglo%20irish%20war&f=false |title=Michael Collins and the Anglo Irish War: Britain's Counter Insurgency Failure}}</ref> By contrast Clifford Kinvig, Percival's biographer considers him to have been unfairly vilified by Republican propaganda  due to him being \"tireless in his attempt to destroy the spirit of the people and the organisation of the IRA\"<ref>Scapegoat; General Percival of Singapore by Clifford Kivnig p75 {{ISBN|185753171 X}} Hardcover</ref>\n\n===Staff officer===\nPercival attended the [[Staff College, Camberley]] from 1923<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=32790|page=608|date=26 January 1923}}</ref> to 1924, then commanded by General [[Edmund Ironside, 1st Baron Ironside|Edmund Ironside]], where he was taught by [[J.F.C. Fuller]], who was one of the few sympathetic reviewers of his book, ''The War in Malaya'', twenty-five years later. He impressed his instructors, who picked him out as one of eight students for accelerated promotion, and his fellow students who admired his cricketing skills. Following an appointment as major with the [[Cheshire Regiment]], he spent four years with the [[Nigeria Regiment]] of the [[Royal West African Frontier Force]] in [[West Africa]] as a [[staff officer]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33043|page=2921|date=1 May 1925}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33470|page=1345|date=26 February 1929}}</ref>  He was given brevet promotion to [[Lieutenant-Colonel (United Kingdom)|lieutenant-colonel]] in 1929.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33454|page=152|date=4 January 1929}}</ref>\n\n[[File:United Kingdom - England - London - Greenwich - Old Royal Naval College.jpg|thumb|right|The Royal Naval College, where Percival studied in 1930.]]\n\nIn 1930, Percival spent a year studying at the [[Royal Naval College, Greenwich]]. From 1931 to 1932, Percival was General Staff Officer Grade 2, an instructor at the Staff College. The College's commandant General Sir [[John Dill]], became Percival's mentor over the next 10 years, helping to ensure his prot\u00e9g\u00e9's advancement. Dill regarded Percival as a promising officer and wrote that \"he has an outstanding ability, wide military knowledge, good judgment and is a very quick and accurate worker\" but added \"he has not altogether an impressive presence and one may therefore fail, at first meeting him, to appreciate his sterling worth\".<ref>Thompson, p71</ref> With Dill's support, Percival was appointed to command the 2nd Battalion, the Cheshire Regiment from 1932<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33846|page=4627|date=15 July 1932}}</ref> to 1936, initially in [[Malta]]. In 1935, he attended the [[Royal College of Defence Studies|Imperial Defence College]].<ref name=\"Officers of the British Army\" />\n\nPercival was made a full [[colonel (United Kingdom)|colonel]] in March 1936,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34264|page=1657|date=13 March 1936}}</ref> and until 1938<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34557|pages=6139\u20136140|date=30 September 1938}}</ref> he was General Staff Officer Grade 1 in [[British Malaya|Malaya]], the [[Chief of staff (military)|Chief of Staff]] to [[General (United Kingdom)|General]] [[William Dobbie|Dobbie]], the [[General Officer Commanding]] in Malaya. During this time, he recognised that Singapore was no longer an isolated fortress.<ref>Hack and Blackburn, ''Did Singapore Have to Fall?: Churchill and the Impregnable Fortress'', p39</ref> He considered the possibility of the [[Empire of Japan|Japanese]] landing in [[Thailand]] to \"burgle Malaya by the backdoor<ref>Kinvig, p106</ref> and conducted an appraisal of the possibility of an attack being launched on Singapore from the North, which was supplied to the [[War Office]], and which Percival subsequently felt was similar to the plan followed by the Japanese in 1941.<ref name=\"percival1\">Percival, ''The War in Malaya'', Chapter 1</ref> He also supported Dobbie's unexecuted plan for the construction of fixed defences in Southern [[Johore]]. In March 1938, he returned to Britain and was (temporarily) promoted to [[brigadier]] on the General Staff, [[Aldershot Garrison|Aldershot Command]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34503|page=2594|date=19 April 1938}}</ref>\n\n==Second World War==\n{{further information|South-East Asian theatre of World War II}}\n[[File:Lieutenant General Arthur Percival.jpg|thumb|upright|Lieutenant-General Percival arriving by aircraft in Singapore in 1941 as the new General Officer Commanding Malaya.]]\n\nPercival was appointed Brigadier, General Staff, of the [[I Corps (United Kingdom)|I Corps]], [[British Expeditionary Force (World War II)|British Expeditionary Force]], commanded by General Dill, from 1939 to 1940. He was then promoted to acting [[Major-General (United Kingdom)|Major-General]],<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34800 |supp=y|page=1151|date=23 February 1940}}</ref> and in February 1940 briefly became General Officer Commanding (GOC) of the [[43rd (Wessex) Infantry Division]]. He was made [[Assistant Chief of the General Staff (United Kingdom)|Assistant Chief of the Imperial General Staff]] at the [[War Office]] in 1940 but asked for a transfer to an active command after the [[Operation Dynamo|Dunkirk evacuation]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34855 |supp=y|page=3091|date=21 May 1940}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34895 |supp=y|page=4273|date=9 July 1940}}</ref> Given command of the [[44th (Home Counties) Infantry Division]], he spent 9 months organising the [[British anti-invasion preparations of World War II|protection of {{convert|62|mi|km}}]] of the [[England|English]] coast from invasion.<ref name=\"percival2\">Percival, Chapter 2</ref> He was appointed a Companion of the [[Order of the Bath]] (CB) in the 1941 [[King's Birthday Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=35204 |supp=y|pages=3735\u20133736|date=27 June 1941}}</ref>\n\n===Percival's early assessment of the vulnerability of Singapore===\nIn 1936, Major-General [[William Dobbie]], then General Officer Commanding ([[Malaya Command|Malaya]]), made an inquiry into whether more forces were required on mainland Malaya to prevent the Japanese from establishing forward bases to attack Singapore. Percival, then his Chief Staff Officer, was tasked to draw up a tactical assessment of how the Japanese were most likely to attack.\nIn late 1937, his analysis duly confirmed that north [[Malay Peninsula|Malaya]] might become the critical battleground. The Japanese were likely to seize the east coast landing sites on [[Thailand]] and Malaya in order to capture aerodromes and achieve air superiority. This could serve as a prelude to further Japanese landings in [[Johore]] to disrupt communications northwards and enable the construction of another main base in North Borneo. From North Borneo, the final sea and air assault could be launched against eastern Singapore\u2014in particular the [[Changi]] area.<ref>Ong, Chit Chung (1997) ''Operation Matador : Britain's war plans against the Japanese 1918\u20131941''. Singapore : Times Academic Press.</ref>\n\n===General Officer Commanding (Malaya)===\nIn April 1941 Percival was promoted to acting [[Lieutenant-General (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant-General]],<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=35160 |supp=y|page=2731|date=9 May 1941}}</ref> and was appointed General Officer Commanding (GOC) Malaya. This was a significant promotion for him as he had never commanded an army [[Corps]]. He left Britain in a [[Sunderland flying boat]] and embarked on an arduous two-week, multi-stage flight via [[Gibraltar]], [[Malta]], [[Alexandria]] (where he was delayed by the [[Anglo-Iraqi War]]), [[Basra]], [[Karachi]] and [[Yangon|Rangoon]], where he was met by an [[Royal Air Force|RAF]] transport.<ref name=\"percival1\" />\n\nPercival had mixed feelings about his appointment, noting that \"In going to Malaya I realised that there was the double danger either of being left in an inactive command for some years if war did not break out in the East or, if it did, of finding myself involved in a pretty sticky business with the inadequate forces which are usually to be found in the distant parts of our [[British Empire|Empire]] in the early stages of a war.\"<ref name=\"percival2\" />\n\nFor much of the interwar period, Britain's defensive plan for Malaya had centred on the dispatch of a [[Royal Navy|naval]] fleet to the newly built [[Singapore Naval Base]]. Accordingly, the army's role was to defend Singapore and Southern [[Johore]]. While this plan had seemed adequate when the nearest Japanese base had been {{convert|1700|mi|km}} away, the outbreak of war in [[European Theatre of World War II|Europe]], combined with the partial Japanese occupation of the northern part of [[French Indochina]] and the signing of the [[Tripartite Pact]] in September 1940, had underlined the difficulty of a sea-based defence. Instead it was proposed to use the RAF to defend Malaya, at least until reinforcements could be dispatched from Britain. This led to the building of airfields in northern Malaya and along its east coast and the dispersal of the available army units around the peninsula to protect them.<ref>Percival, Chapter 3</ref>\n\nOn arrival, Percival set about training his inexperienced army; his Indian troops were particularly raw, with most of their experienced officers having been withdrawn to support the formation of new units as the Indian army expanded. Relying upon commercial aircraft or the Volunteer air force to overcome the shortage of RAF planes, he toured the peninsula and encouraged the building of defensive works around [[Jitra]].<ref>Percival, Chapter 4</ref> A training manual approved by Percival, ''Tactical Notes on Malaya'', was distributed to all units.\n\nIn July 1941 when the Japanese occupied southern Indochina, Britain, the [[United States]] and the [[Netherlands]] imposed economic [[international sanctions|sanctions]], freezing Japanese financial assets and cutting Japan from its supplies of [[petroleum|oil]], [[tin]] and [[rubber]]. The sanctions were aimed at pressuring Japan to abandon its [[Second Sino-Japanese War|involvement in China]]; instead, the Japanese government planned to seize the resources of South-East Asia from the European nations by force. Both the Japanese navy and army were mobilised, but for the moment an uneasy state of cold war persisted. British Commonwealth reinforcements continued to trickle into Malaya. On 2 December, the [[battleship]] [[HMS Prince of Wales (53)|HMS ''Prince of Wales'']] and the [[battle-cruiser]] [[HMS Repulse (1916)|HMS ''Repulse'']], escorted by four [[destroyer]]s, arrived in Singapore, the first time a battle fleet had been based there. (They were to have been accompanied by the aircraft carrier {{HMS|Indomitable|92|6}} to provide air cover but she had run aground in the Caribbean en route.) The following day [[Rear-Admiral]] [[Ernest John Spooner|Spooner]] hosted a dinner attended by the newly arrived Commander-in-Chief [[Eastern Fleet]], [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]] [[Thomas Phillips (Naval officer)|Sir Tom Phillips]], and Percival.<ref>Percival, Chapter 7</ref>\n\n===Japanese attack and British surrender===\n{{main article|Japanese invasion of Malaya|Battle of Singapore}}\n[[File:Pacific War - Malaya 1941-42 - Map.jpg|thumb|350px|Malaya Command and the [[Japanese invasion of Malaya]]]]\n\nOn 8 December 1941 the [[Twenty-Fifth Army (Japan)|Japanese 25th Army]] under the command of Lieutenant-General [[Tomoyuki Yamashita]] launched an [[amphibious assault]] on the Malay Peninsula (one hour before the [[attack on Pearl Harbor]]; the difference in date was because the two places lie on opposite sides of the [[international date line]]). That night the first Japanese invasion force arrived at [[Kota Bharu]] on Malaya's east coast. This was just a diversionary force, and the main landings took place the next day at [[Singora]] and [[Pattani (town)|Pattani]] on the south-eastern coast of [[Thailand]], with troops rapidly deploying over the border into northern Malaya.\n\nOn 10 December Percival issued a stirring, if ultimately ineffective, Special Order of the Day:\n<blockquote>In this hour of trial the General Officer Commanding calls upon all ranks Malaya Command for a determined and sustained effort to safeguard Malaya and the adjoining British territories. The eyes of the Empire are upon us. Our whole position in the Far East is at stake. The struggle may be long and grim but let us all resolve to stand fast come what may and to prove ourselves worthy of the great trust which has been placed in us.<ref>Percival, chapter 9</ref></blockquote>\n\n[[File:Royal Engineers prepare to blow up a bridge in Malaya.jpg|thumb|[[Royal Engineers]] prepare to blow up a bridge during the retreat.]]\n\nThe Japanese advanced rapidly, and on 27 January 1942 Percival ordered a general retreat across the [[Johore Strait]] to the island of [[Singapore]] and organised a defence along the length of the island's {{convert|70|mi|km|sing=on}} coast line. But the Japanese did not dawdle, and on 8 February Japanese troops landed on the northwest corner of Singapore island. After a week of fighting on the island, Percival held his final command conference at 9&nbsp;am on 15 February in [[the Battle Box]] of [[Fort Canning]]. The Japanese had already occupied approximately half of Singapore and it was clear that the island would soon fall.  Having been told that ammunition and water would both run out by the following day, Percival agreed to surrender. The Japanese at this point were running low on artillery shells, but Percival did not know this.\n\nThe Japanese insisted that Percival himself march under a [[white flag]] to the [[Old Ford Motor Factory]] in [[Bukit Timah]] to negotiate the surrender. A Japanese officer present noted that he looked \"pale, thin and tired\".<ref>Warren, p265</ref> After a brief disagreement, when Percival insisted that the British keep 1,000 men under arms in Singapore to preserve order, which Yamashita finally conceded, it was agreed at 6:10&nbsp;pm that the British Empire troops would lay down their arms and cease resistance at 8:30&nbsp;pm. This was in spite of instructions from Prime Minister [[Winston Churchill]] for prolonged resistance.<ref name=\"Morris\"/> The [[Pacific War]] was just ten weeks old.\n\nA common view holds that 138,708 [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] personnel surrendered or were killed by fewer than 30,000 Japanese. However, the former figure includes nearly 50,000 troops captured or killed during the [[Battle of Malaya]], and perhaps 15,000 base troops. Many of the other troops were tired and under-equipped following their retreat from the [[Malayan peninsula]]. Conversely, the latter number represents only the front-line troops available for the invasion of Singapore. British Empire battle casualties since 8 December amounted to 7,500 killed and 11,000 wounded. Japanese losses totalled around 3,500 killed and 6,100 wounded.<ref>Thompson, p9 and p424</ref>\n\n===Culpability for the fall of Singapore===\n[[File:Singaporesurrender.jpg|thumb|Lieutenant-General Percival led by a Japanese officer, marches under a flag of [[truce]] to negotiate the capitulation of Allied forces in Singapore, on 15 February 1942. It was the largest surrender of British-led forces in history.]]\nChurchill viewed the fall of Singapore to be \"the worst disaster and largest capitulation in British history.\" However, the British defence was that the [[Middle East]] and the [[Soviet Union]] had all received higher priorities in the allocation of men and material, so the desired [[air force]] strength of 300 to 500 aircraft was never reached, and whereas the Japanese invaded with over two hundred [[tank]]s, the British Army in Malaya did not have a single tank.<ref>Kinvig.</ref> In ''The War in Malaya'' Percival himself cites this as the major factor for the defeat stating that the 'war material which might have saved Singapore was sent to Russia and the Middle East'. However he also concedes that Britain was engaged in 'a life and death struggle in the West' and that 'this decision, however painful and regrettable, was inevitable and right'.<ref>The War in Malaya; Authur Percival p306</ref>\n\nIn 1918, Percival had been described as \"a slim, soft spoken man... with a proven reputation for bravery and organisational powers\"<ref>Kinvig, p. 47.</ref> but by 1945 this description had been turned on its head with even Percival's defenders describing him as \"something of a damp squib\".<ref>Kinvig, p. 242.</ref> The fall of Singapore switched Percival's reputation to that of an ineffective \"staff wallah\", lacking ruthlessness and aggression, even though few doubted that he was a brave and determined officer. Over six feet in height and lanky, with a clipped moustache and two protruding teeth, and unphotogenic, Percival was an easy target for a caricaturist, being described as \"tall, bucktoothed and lightly built\".<ref>Warren, p. 29.</ref> There was no doubt his presentation lacked impact as \"his manner was low key and he was a poor public speaker with the cusp of a lisp\".<ref>Kinvig, ''General Percival and the Fall of Singapore'', p. 241.</ref>\n[[File:BritishSurrender.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Lieutenant-General Yamashita (seated, centre) thumps the table with his fist to emphasise his demand for unconditional surrender. Lieutenant-General Percival sits between his officers, his clenched hand to his mouth. (Photo from [[Imperial War Museum]]).]]\n\nIt has been argued{{by whom|date=November 2015}} that Percival's colleagues bear a share of the responsibility of defeat. Air Chief Marshal Sir [[Henry Robert Moore Brooke-Popham|Robert Brooke-Popham]], the [[Commander-in-Chief]] of the [[British Far East Command]], refused Percival permission to launch [[Operation Matador (1941)|Operation Matador]] in advance of the Japanese landings in Thailand, not wishing to run any risk of provoking the coming war. Brooke-Popham also had a reputation for falling asleep in meetings and not arguing forcefully for the air reinforcements required to defend Malaya. Admiral [[Thomas Spencer Vaughan Phillips|Tom Phillips]]' leadership of [[Force Z]] led to his demise and the [[Sinking of Prince of Wales and Repulse|destruction of the British fleet]] on 10 December 1941, early in the campaign.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\n[[Peter Wykeham]] suggested that the government in London was more to blame than any of the British commanders in the Far East. Despite repeated requests, the British government did not provide the necessary reinforcements and they denied Brooke-Popham \u2013 and therefore Percival \u2013 permission to enter neutral Thailand before it was too late to put in place forward defences.<ref name=\"ODNB\">{{cite journal| last =Wykeham| first =Peter| author2 =Thomas Paul Ofcansky| title =Popham, Sir (Henry) Robert Moore Brooke| work =Oxford Dictionary of National Biography| url =http://www.oxforddnb.com/index/32/101032096/| date =January 2008| doi =10.1093/ref:odnb/32096}}</ref>\n\nMoreover, Percival had difficulties with his subordinates [[Lewis Heath|Sir Lewis \"Piggy\" Heath]], commanding [[Indian III Corps]], and the independent-minded [[Gordon Bennett (general)|Gordon Bennett]], commanding the [[Australian 8th Division]]. The former officer had been senior to Percival prior to his appointment as GOC (Malaya). Bennett was full of confidence in his [[Australia]]n troops and his own ability, but faced a mixed reaction in Australia when he escaped from Singapore immediately after its surrender.\n\nPercival was ultimately responsible for the men who served under him, and with other officers \u2013 notably Major-General [[David Murray-Lyon]], commander of the [[Indian 11th Infantry Division]] \u2013 he had shown a willingness to replace them when he felt their performance was not up to scratch. Perhaps his greatest mistake was to resist the building of fixed defences in either Johore or the north shore of Singapore, dismissing them in the face of repeated requests to start construction from his Chief Engineer, Brigadier [[Ivan Simson]], with the comment \"Defences are bad for morale \u2013 for both troops and civilians\".<ref>Thompson, p. 182.</ref> In doing so, Percival threw away the potential advantages he could have derived from the 6,000 engineers under his command and perhaps missed his best chance to blunt the danger posed by the Japanese tanks.\n\nPercival also insisted on defending the north-eastern shore of Singapore most heavily, against the advice of the [[American-British-Dutch-Australian Command|Allied supreme commander in South East Asia]], General [[Archibald Percival Wavell, 1st Earl Wavell|Archibald Wavell]]. Percival was perhaps fixed on his responsibilities for defending the Singapore Naval Base.<ref>Dixon, ''[[On the Psychology of Military Incompetence]]'', p. 143.</ref> He also spread his forces thinly around the island and kept few units as a strategic reserve. When the Japanese attack came in the west, the [[Australian 22nd Brigade]] took the brunt of the assault.<ref>Thompson, p. 414.</ref> Percival refused to reinforce them as he continued to believe that the main assault would occur in the north east.<ref>Thompson, p. 430.</ref>\n\n===Captivity===\nPercival himself was briefly held prisoner in [[Changi Prison]], where \"the defeated GOC could be seen sitting head in hands, outside the married quarters he now shared with seven brigadiers, a colonel, his ADC and cook-sergeant. He discussed feelings with few, spent hours walking around the extensive compound, ruminating on the reverse and what might have been\".<ref>Kinvig, p221</ref> In the belief that it would improve discipline, he reconstituted a Malaya Command, complete with staff appointments, and helped occupy his fellow prisoners with lectures on the [[Battle of France]].<ref>MacArthur, ''Surviving the Sword: Prisoners of the Japanese 1942\u201345'', p188</ref>\n[[File:Douglas MacArthur signs formal surrender.jpg|left|thumb|The signing of the Japanese surrender; [[Douglas MacArthur|MacArthur]] (sitting), behind him are Generals Percival (background) and [[Jonathan M. Wainwright (general)|Wainwright]] (foreground).]]\n\nAlong with the other senior British captives above the rank of colonel, Percival was removed from Singapore in August 1942. First he was imprisoned in [[Taiwan|Formosa]] and then sent on to [[Manchuria]], where he was held with several dozen other VIP captives, including the [[United States|American]] General [[Jonathan M. Wainwright (general)|Jonathan Wainwright]], in a [[prisoner-of-war camp]] near [[Xi'an District, Mudanjiang|Hsian]], about {{convert|100|mi|km}} to the north east of [[Mukden]].\n\nAs the war drew to an end, an [[Office of Strategic Services|OSS]] team removed the prisoners from Hsian. Percival was then taken, along with Wainwright, to stand immediately behind General [[Douglas MacArthur]] as he confirmed the terms of the Japanese surrender aboard [[USS Missouri (BB-63)|USS ''Missouri'' (BB-63)]] in [[Tokyo Bay]] on 2 September 1945.<ref>''Battleship Missouri Memorial'', {{cite web|url=http://www.ussmissouri.org/surrender.aspx |title=Surrender |accessdate=2006-02-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051109061015/http://ussmissouri.org/surrender.aspx |archivedate=9 November 2005 |df=dmy }} , accessed 2 February 2006</ref> Afterwards, MacArthur gave Percival a pen he had used to sign the treaty.<ref>Warren, p286</ref>\n\nPercival and Wainwright then returned together to the [[Philippines]] to witness the surrender of the Japanese army there, which in a twist of fate was commanded by General Yamashita. Yamashita was momentarily surprised to see his former captive at the ceremony; on this occasion Percival refused to shake Yamashita's hand, angered by the mistreatment of POWs in Singapore. The flag carried by Percival's party on the way to Bukit Timah was also a witness to this reversal of fortunes, being flown when the Japanese formally surrendered Singapore back to Lord [[Louis Mountbatten, 1st Earl Mountbatten of Burma|Louis Mountbatten]].<ref>Morris, p458</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nPercival returned to the United Kingdom in September 1945 to write his despatch at the [[War Office]] but this was revised by the [[Her Majesty's Government|UK Government]] and only published in 1948.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=38215|pages=1245\u20131346|date=20 February 1948}}</ref> He retired from the army in 1946 with the honorary rank of lieutenant-general but the pension of his substantive rank of major-general.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=37706|page=4347|date=27 August 1946}}</ref> Thereafter, he held appointments connected with the county of Hertfordshire, where he lived at Bullards in [[Widford, Hertfordshire|Widford]]: he was Honorary Colonel of [[479th (Hertfordshire Yeomanry) Heavy Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery]], ([[Territorial Army (United Kingdom)|T.A.]]) from 1949 to 1954<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=38762|page=5465|date=18 November 1949}}</ref><ref>Col J.D. Sainsbury, ''The Hertfordshire Yeomanry Regiments, Royal Artillery, Part 2: The Heavy Anti-Aircraft Regiment 1938\u20131945 and the Searchlight Battery 1937\u20131945; Part 3: The Post-war Units 1947\u20132002'', Welwyn: Hertfordshire Yeomanry and Artillery Trust/Hart Books, 2003, {{ISBN|0-948527-06-4}}.</ref> and acted as one of the [[Deputy Lieutenant]]s of Hertfordshire in 1951.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=39412|page=6600|date=18 December 1951}}</ref> He continued his relationship with the Cheshire Regiment being appointed Colonel of the Cheshire Regiment between 1950 and 1955;<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=38940 |supp=y|page=3037|date=13 June 1950}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=40680 |supp=y|page=208|date=6 January 1956}}</ref> an association continued by his son, [[Brigadier]] James Percival who became Colonel of the Regiment between 1992 and 1999.\n\nWhile General Wainwright had become a public hero on his return to the United States, Percival found himself disparaged for his leadership in Malaya, even by Lieutenant-General Heath, his erstwhile subordinate. Percival's 1949 memoir, ''The War in Malaya'', did little to quell this criticism, being a restrained rather than self-serving account of the campaign. Unusual for a British lieutenant-general, Percival was not awarded a [[British honours system|knighthood]].\n\nPercival was respected for the time he had spent as a Japanese [[prisoner of war]]. Serving as life president of the [[Far East Prisoners of War]] Association (FEPOW), he pushed for compensation for his fellow captives, eventually helping to obtain a token \u00a35 million of frozen Japanese assets for this cause. This was distributed by the FEPOW Welfare Trust, on which Percival served as Chairman.<ref name = \"MacArthur442\">MacArthur, p. 442.</ref> He led protests against the film ''[[The Bridge on the River Kwai]]'' when it was released in 1957, obtaining the addition of an on-screen statement that the movie was a work of fiction. He also worked as President of the Hertfordshire [[British Red Cross]] and was made an Officer of the [[Venerable Order of Saint John]] in 1964.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=43367|pages=5540\u20135542|date=26 June 1964}}</ref>\n\nPercival died at the age of 78 on 31 January 1966, in [[King Edward VII's Hospital Sister Agnes|King Edward VII's Hospital for Officers]], Beaumont Street in [[City of Westminster|Westminster]], and is buried in the churchyard at [[Widford, Hertfordshire|Widford]] in Hertfordshire.<ref>http://kementah.blogspot.com.au/2017/06/battle-for-malaya-and-fall-of-singapore.html</ref> [[John Leonard Wilson|Leonard Wilson]], formerly the [[Bishop of Singapore]], gave the address at his memorial service, which was held in [[St Martin-in-the-Fields]].\n\n===Family===\nOn 27 July 1927 Percival married Margaret Elizabeth \"Betty\" MacGregor Greer in [[Holy Trinity Brompton Church|Holy Trinity Church]], [[Brompton, London|Brompton]]. She was the daughter of Thomas MacGregor Greer of Tallylagan Manor, a [[Protestantism|Protestant]] [[linen]] merchant from [[County Tyrone]] in [[Northern Ireland]]. They had met during his tour of duty in Ireland but it had taken Percival several years to propose. They had two children. A daughter, Dorinda Margery, was born in Greenwich and became [[Baron Dunleath|Lady Dunleath]]. Alfred James MacGregor, their son, was born in [[Singapore]] and served in the British Army.\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Arthur Ernest Percival}}\n* [[Operation Krohcol]]\n* [[Shenton Thomas|Sir Shenton Thomas]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* [[Tom Barry (soldier)|Barry, Tom]], ''Guerilla Days in Ireland'', Dublin, 1949\n* Bose, Romen, \"SECRETS OF THE BATTLEBOX: The role and history of Britain's Command HQ during the Malayan Campaign\", Marshall Cavendish, Singapore, 2005\n* Coogan, Tim Pat. \"Michael Collins\". {{ISBN|0-09-968580-9}}\n* Dixon, Norman F, ''On the Psychology of Military Incompetence'', London, 1976\n* Hack, Karl and Blackburn, Kevin, ''Did Singapore Have to Fall?: Churchill and the Impregnable Fortress'', RoutledgeCurzon, 2003, {{ISBN|0-415-30803-8}}\n* [[John Keegan|Keegan, John]] (editor), ''Churchill's Generals'', Abacus History, 1999, {{ISBN|0-349-11317-3}}\n* Kinvig, Clifford, ''General Percival and the Fall of Singapore'', in ''60 Years On: the Fall of Singapore Revisited'', Eastern University Press, Singapore, 2003\n* [[Kinvig, Clifford]], ''Scapegoat: General Percival of Singapore'', London, 1996. {{ISBN|0-241-10583-8}}\n* ''[[London Gazette]]''\n* MacArthur, Brian, ''Surviving the Sword: Prisoners of the Japanese 1942\u201345'', Abacus, {{ISBN|0-349-11937-6}}\n* ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'', Volume 43, available at [http://www.oxforddnb.com/ Oxford Dictionary of National Biography website]\n* [[Jan Morris|Morris, James]] ''Farewell the Trumpets'', Penguin Books, 1979\n* Percival, Arthur Ernest ''The War in Malaya'', London, Eyre & Spottiswoode, 1949. Extracts from the report used as the basis of this book are at [http://www.fepow-community.org.uk/arthur_lane/Percivals_Report/] accessed 2 February 2006 and the references here are to this report\n* Ryan, Meda. ''Tom Barry: IRA Freedom Fighter'', Cork, 2003\n* Smith, Colin, ''Singapore Burning: Heroism and Surrender in World War II'', Penguin Books, {{ISBN|0-14-101036-3}}\n* [[Sir John Smyth, 1st Baronet|Smyth, John George]], ''Percival and the Tragedy of Singapore'', MacDonald and Company, 1971. ASIN B0006CDC1Q\n* [[A. J. P. Taylor|Taylor, A. J. P.]] ''English History 1914\u20131945'', Oxford University Press, 1975\n* Thompson, Peter, ''The Battle for Singapore'', London, 2005, {{ISBN|0-7499-5068-4}} HB\n* Warren, Alan, ''Singapore 1942: Britain's Greatest Defeat'', Hambledon Continuum, 2001, {{ISBN|1-85285-328-X}}\n{{refend}}\n\n===References===\n<!--This article uses the Cite.php citation mechanism. If you would like more information on how to add footnotes to this article, please see http://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Extension:Cite/Cite.php -->\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.unithistories.com/officers/Army_officers_P02.html#Percival_AE British Army Officers 1939\u22121945]\n*[http://www.generals.dk/general/Percival/Arthur_Ernest/Great_Britain.html Generals of World War II]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Arthur Floyer-Acland]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[43rd (Wessex) Infantry Division|GOC 43rd (Wessex) Infantry Division]]|years=February\u2013April 1940}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Robert Pollok (British Army officer)|Robert Pollok]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Edmund Osborne]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[44th (Home Counties) Division|GOC 44th (Home Counties) Infantry Division]]|years=1940\u20131941}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Noel Mason-MacFarlane]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lionel Vivian Bond|Sir Lionel Bond]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Malaya Command|GOC Malaya Command]]|years=1941\u20131942}}\n{{s-aft|after=Fell to Japan}}\n|-\n{{s-hon}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Geoffrey Harding]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Cheshire Regiment|Colonel of the Cheshire Regiment]]|years=1950\u20131955}}