{"title_page": "Malese Jow", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name         = Malese Jow\n| image        = Malese Jow at WonderCon 2014.jpg\n| caption      = Malese Jow at WonderCon    Ugh\n2014\n| birth_name   = Elizabeth Melise Jow\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1991|02|18}}\n| birth_place  = [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]], U.S.\n| residence    = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| genre        = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| occupation   = Actress, singer\n| other_name   =\n| years_active = 1997\u2013present\n| background       =solo_singer\n}}\n\n'''Elizabeth Melise Jow''' (born February 18, 1991), best known as '''Malese Jow''' and recently '''Melise''', is an American actress and singer. She is known for her roles as Geena Fabiano on the [[Nickelodeon]] sitcom ''[[Unfabulous]]'', Lucy Stone on the Nickelodeon musical sitcom she also farted on my dads face''[[Big Time Rush]]'' and as Anna, a teenage vampire on [[The CW]]'s fantasy drama ''[[The Vampire Diaries]]''. She starred as Julia Yeung in the short-lived CW science fiction romantic drama ''[[Star-Crossed (TV series)|Star-Crossed]]''. Jow starred as Mareth Ravenlock in season two of ''[[The Shannara Chronicles]]''. She has most recently been cast in [[Invincible (TV series)|Invincible]] for ''Amazon'' set for release in 2020.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]], Jow moved to [[California]] with her mother Lanae Tillery Jow, one sister, Makenna Jow, two brothers Jensen and Braden Jow and their cousin Chris Nightingale when she was nine years old. Jow is [[Chinese American]]<ref>{{cite web |author=Michael Smith |year=2010 |url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/scene/article.aspx?subjectid=268&articleid=20100926_282_D6_CUTLIN123015 |title=Little' Tulsa Girl in Big New Movie |work=Tulsa World |accessdate=2011-12-12}}</ref> As a child, she would often sing [[The Star-Spangled Banner|the national anthem]] at local baseball games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myfanbase.de/vampire-diaries/interviews/?pid=8913|title=Interview with Malese Jow|website=myfanbase.de|accessdate=2015-06-17}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nWhen she was six years old, Jow appeared on ''Barney'' and ''Dellaventura'', but her acting career took off when she won a co-starring role in the [[Nickelodeon]] sitcom ''[[Unfabulous]]'' with [[Emma Roberts]] where she played Geena Fabiano, one of the best friends of Roberts' character Addie Singer. The show ran for three seasons from 2004 to 2007 and earned Jow several [[Young Artist Award]] nominations.\n\nWhen ''Unfabulous'' ended in 2007, Jow co-starred in the animated film ''[[Bratz (2007 film)|Bratz: The Movie]]'' as Quinn and has guest-starred on the shows ''[[Wizards of Waverly Place]]'', ''[[The Young and the Restless]]'', ''[[iCarly]]'', ''[[The Secret Life of the American Teenager]]'' and the [[Disney Channel]] series ''[[Hannah Montana]]'' and co-starred in the 2009 science fiction comedy ''[[Aliens in the Attic]]''.\n\nIn 2010, Jow appeared in the first season of [[The CW]] fantasy drama ''[[The Vampire Diaries]]''. She played Anna, a vampire. Jow briefly re-appeared in the third season.<ref>{{cite web|author=Wetpaint Visitor |url=http://www.wetpaint.com/vampire-diaries/video/malese-jow-on-tvd-season-3-im-all-for-a-love-square- |title=Malese Jow On TVD Season 3: \"I'm All For a Love Square\" &#124; The Vampire Diaries |work=Wetpaint |date=2011-07-19 |accessdate=2013-10-14}}</ref> That same year, Jow co-starred in the fantasy romance film ''You're So Cupid!'' as Megan, and the drama film ''[[The Social Network]]'' as Alice Cantwell. She also guest-starred on an episode of [[TNT (American TV network)|TNT]] crime comedy-drama ''[[Leverage (TV series)|Leverage]]''. Then she went on to star in the Nickelodeon action/science fiction sitcom ''[[The Troop]]'' as Cadence Nash.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bopandtigerbeat.com/2010/10/exclusive-matt-shively-and-malese-jow-are-joining-the-troop/ |title=EXCLUSIVE: Matt Shively and Malese Jow are Joining The Troop! &#124; BOP and Tiger Beat Online |website=BopandTigerBeat.com |date=2010-10-15 |accessdate=2013-10-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109224740/http://www.bopandtigerbeat.com/2010/10/exclusive-matt-shively-and-malese-jow-are-joining-the-troop/ |archive-date=November 9, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n[[File:Malese Jow 3, 2012.jpg|right|thumb|Jow in June 2012]]\nIn 2011, Jow began a recurring role in the second season of the Nickelodeon musical sitcom ''[[Big Time Rush]]'' as Lucy Stone, an aspiring rock musician and a brief love interest of Kendall Knight ([[Kendall Schmidt]]) and later on becomes the love interest of James Diamond ([[James Maslow]]). She guest-starred in the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] mystery comedy-drama ''[[Desperate Housewives]]'' as Violet.<ref name=\"zap2it1\">{{cite web |author= |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2013/02/vampire-diaries-alum-malese-jow-joins-the-cws-oxygen-nkotbs-joey-mcintyre-in-the-mccarthys.html |title='Vampire Diaries' alum Malese Jow joins The CW's 'Oxygen,' NKOTB's Joey McIntyre in 'The McCarthys' |work=Zap2it |date=2013-02-21 |accessdate=2013-10-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130224051751/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2013/02/vampire-diaries-alum-malese-jow-joins-the-cws-oxygen-nkotbs-joey-mcintyre-in-the-mccarthys.html |archive-date=February 24, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Jow starred in The CW drama pilot ''Shelter'', produced by [[J. J. Abrams]] and [[Mark Schwahn]], where she played Morgan. It was not picked up by the network.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2012/03/vampire-diaries-star-malese-jow-scores-shelter-role.html |title='Vampire Diaries' star Malese Jow scores 'Shelter' role - From Inside the Box |work=Zap2it |date=2012-03-30 |accessdate=2012-05-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120519211737/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2012/03/vampire-diaries-star-malese-jow-scores-shelter-role.html |archive-date=May 19, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, Jow confirmed her role in the crime comedy ''[[Plastic (2014 film)|Plastic]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://malesejow.net/2015/03/04/malese-graces-the-cover-of-nationalist-magazines-march-2015-issue/|title=Malese graces the cover of Nationalist Magazine's March 2015 Issue|website=MaleseJow.net|accessdate=2015-06-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150617171705/http://malesejow.net/2015/03/04/malese-graces-the-cover-of-nationalist-magazines-march-2015-issue/|archive-date=June 17, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> That same month, it was also announced that Jow would reprise her role as Lucy Stone on ''Big Time Rush'' in the fourth and final season.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://www.clevvertv.com/cher-lloyd/38937/cher-lloyd-to-guest-star-on-big-time-rush.html |title=Cher Lloyd to Guest Star on \"Big Time Rush\" |website=Clevvertv.com |date=2013-01-23 |accessdate=2013-10-14}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2013, Jow was revealed to be the new host of ''The Vampire Diaries'' side show, ''TVD Rehash (Re#ash)'' replacing previous host [[Arielle Kebbel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vampire-diaries.net/tv-series/tvd-rehash-with-malese-jow-a-view-to-a-kill-ep412-video |title=TVD Rehash with Malese Jow: A View to a Kill (EP412) (VIDEO) &#124; Vampire-Diaries.net &#124; A Fansite for The Vampire Diaries & The Originals |website=Vampire-Diaries.net |date=2013-02-04 |accessdate=2013-10-14}}</ref> Later that month, it was announced that Jow would be joining the CW science fiction romantic drama pilot ''Oxygen'', as Julia Yeung, a girl who has an illness which may be cured by aliens.<ref name=\"zap2it1\"/><ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/ustv/news/a460831/glee-vampire-diaries-stars-join-the-cws-oxygen.html |title='Glee', 'Vampire Diaries' stars join The CW's 'Oxygen' - US TV News |work=Digital Spy |date=2013-02-22 |accessdate=2013-10-14}}</ref> In May 2013, ''Oxygen'' was picked up and retitled ''[[Star-Crossed (TV series)|Star-Crossed]]''. The series was part of the 2013\u201314 mid season schedule.<ref>{{cite web|author=Patrick Munn |url=http://www.tvwise.co.uk/2013/05/the-cw-picks-up-the-100-the-tomorrow-people-to-series/ |title=The CW Picks Up 'The 100', 'Reign, 'Star Crossed' & 'The Tomorrow People' To Series |work=TVWise |date=2013-05-09 |accessdate=2013-10-14}}</ref> In August 2013, production began for ''Star-Crossed''. The show ran for one season from February 17 to May 12, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starcrossedfan.com/ |title=Star-Crossed Fansite \u2013 Your first source for all StarCrossed CW News |website=Starcrossedfan.com |date= |accessdate=2013-10-14}}</ref> In 2014, Jow was in the television movie ''Presumed Dead in Paradise'' and played Madison Ashland. On October 27, 2014, she was announced to have a recurring role as [[Linda Park (comics)|Linda Park]] on the CW's superhero drama ''[[The Flash (2014 TV series)|The Flash]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2014/10/27/malese-jow-the-flash-linda-park/?hootPostID=c232dd3bb19fb1ac7c0ee936a1bcea7b |title='Vampire Diaries' star Malese Jow joins 'The Flash' as Linda Park |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=2014-10-27}}</ref> In 2015, Malese was listed in ''[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]''{{'}}s Hot 10.<ref>{{cite web |author=Sean Abrams |url=http://www.maxim.com/women/article/hot-10-malese-jow |title=Hot 10: Malese Jow |work=[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]] |date=2015-03-17 |accessdate=2015-08-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150720082705/http://www.maxim.com/women/article/hot-10-malese-jow |archivedate=2015-07-20 }}</ref>  On August 25, 2015, Malese was announced to be reprising her role as [[Linda Park (comics)|Linda Park]] as a friend of Iris for multiple episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2015/08/25/flash-season-2-malese-jow-linda-park|title=The Flash season 2: Malese Jow returning to play Linda Park |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=2015-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/ustv/s246/the-flash/news/a665460/the-flash-season-2-will-bring-back-malese-jow-as-linda-park.html#~pmX0GLVJiZpUjW|title=The Flash season 2 will bring back Malese Jow as Linda Park|author=Justin Harp|date=2015-08-26|work=Digital Spy}}</ref> In the second season's fifth episode, \"The Darkness and the Light,\" Malese played villainess [[Doctor Light (Kimiyo Hoshi)|Dr. Light]], who is Earth 2 [[Linda Park (comics)|Linda Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cartermatt.com/184335/the-flash-season-2-episode-5-preview-dr-lights-arrival-barry-allen-patty-spivot-go-on-a-date|title='The Flash' season 2, episode 5 preview: Dr. Light's arrival; Barry Allen, Patty Spivot go on a date|website=CarterMatt.com|date=October 28, 2015}}</ref> On February 2, 2017, it was announced Malese would be playing Mareth Ravenlock on MTV's ''[[The Shannara Chronicles]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/tv/2017/02/01/shannara-chronicles-season-2-production-cast/}}</ref> \nOn [[NCIS: Los Angeles]], she played Jennifer Kim, who is the illegitimate daughter of late NCIS Assistant Director Owen Granger ([[Miguel Ferrer]]). \nIn September 2017, it was revealed that Malese would be playing Daya in the upcoming ''[[Escape Plan: The Extractors]]'' movie. Malese has begun filming a new feature film as of November 2017 titled ''I Wrote This For You''.\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Bratz (2007 film)|Bratz: The Movie]]''\n| Quinn\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Aliens in the Attic]]''\n| Julie\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''You're So Cupid!''\n| Megan\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| style=\"white-space:nowrap;\" | ''{{sortname|The|Social Network}}''\n| Alice Cantwell\n| [[Hollywood Film Festival]] for Ensemble of the Year<br>Nominated\u2014[[Alliance of Women Film Journalists]] for Best Ensemble Cast<br>Nominated\u2014[[Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Cast]]<br>Nominated\u2014[[San Diego Film Critics Society Award for Best Performance by an Ensemble]]\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Plastic (2014 film)|Plastic]]''\n| Beth\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n|''[[Sisters of the Groom]]''\n|Sarah Adams\n|Hallmark Movie\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[I Wrote This For You]]''\n| Ariana\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Escape Plan: The Extractors]]''\n| Daya\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Barney & Friends]]''\n| Tea party girl\n| Episode: \"Pennies, Nickels, Dimes\"\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Dellaventura]]''\n| Orphan child\n| Episode: \"Dreamers\"; uncredited{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''{{sortname|The|Brothers Garcia}}''\n| Celeste\n| Episode: \"Right Place, Right Time\"\n|-\n| 2004\u201307\n| ''[[Unfabulous]]''\n| Geena Fabiano\n| Main role; 41 episodes<br>Nominated\u2014[[Young Artist Awards|Young Artist Award]] for Best Performance in a TV Series \u2013 Supporting Young Actress<br>Nominated\u2014[[Young Artist Awards|Young Artist Award]] for Best Young Ensemble Performance in a TV Series <small>(2005, 2006, 2008)</small>\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Wizards of Waverly Place]]''\n| Ruby Donahue\n| Episode: \"Movie\"\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''{{sortname|The|Young and the Restless}}''\n| Hannah\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[iCarly]]''\n| Fake Carly Shay\n| Episode: \"[[iLook Alike]]\"\n|-\n| 2009\n| style=\"white-space:nowrap;\" | ''{{sortname|The|Secret Life of the American Teenager}}''\n| Gail\n| Episode: \"One Night at Band Camp\"\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Hannah Montana]]''\n| Rachel\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2009\u201311\n| ''{{sortname|The|Vampire Diaries}}''\n| Annabelle \"Anna\" Zhu\n| 18 episodes\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Leverage (TV series)|Leverage]]''\n| Josie\n| Episode: \"The Boost Job\"\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''{{sortname|The|Troop}}''\n| Cadence Nash\n| Main role (season 2); 13 episodes\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Desperate Housewives]]''\n| Violet\n| Episode: \"[[Then I Really Got Scared]]\"\n|-\n| 2011\u201313\n| ''[[Big Time Rush]]''\n| Lucy Stone\n| 14 episodes\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[CSI: Miami]]''\n| Amanda Reed\n| Episode: \"Friendly Fire\"\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Star-Crossed (TV series)|Star-Crossed]]''\n| Julia Yeung\n| Main role; 10 episodes\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Castle (TV series)|Castle]]''\n| Hillary Cooper\n| Episode: \"Smells Like Teen Spirit\"\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Presumed Dead in Paradise''\n| Madison Ashland\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''{{sortname|The|Flash|dab=2014 TV series}}''\n| [[Linda Park (comics)|Linda Park]], [[Doctor Light (Kimiyo Hoshi)|Doctor Light]]\n| 7 episodes\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Filthy Preppy Teen$]]''\n| Beatrix Bishop\n| 8 episodes\n|-\n| 2015\u201318\n| ''[[NCIS: Los Angeles]]''\n| Jennifer Kim\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Sweet/Vicious]]''\n| Chloe Freeman\n| Episode: \"Tragic Kingdom\"\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Sisters of the Groom]]''\n| Sarah Adams\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[The Shannara Chronicles]]''\n| Mareth Ravenlock\n| 10 episodes\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Invincible (TV series)|Invincible]]''\n| [[Dupli-Kate|Kate Cha / Dupli-Kate]] (voice)\n| 8 episodes\n|-\n|}\n\n==Discography==\n=== Singles ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Year\n!Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Trying to Sleep\" <ref>{{cite web \n|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/trying-to-sleep-single/1394235658|title=Trying To Sleep by Melise|website=itunes.apple.com}}</ref>\n| 2018\n| TBA\n|}\n\n===Music video===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Title\n!scope=\"col\"| Year\n!scope=\"col\"| Director\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Trying to Sleep\"\n| 2018\n| Melise\n|}\n;As a guest appearance\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Artist\n|-\n| 2009\n| \"When You're Around\"\n| C&C\n|-\n| 2009\n| \"The In Crowd\"\n| [[Mitchel Musso]]\n|-\n| 2010\n| \"[[Til I Forget About You]]\"\n| [[Big Time Rush]] \n|-\n| 2011\n| \"Famous\"\n| [[Lissa Lauria]]\n|-\n| 2011\n| \"Time-Bomb\"\n| [[All Time Low]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vampirediaries.alloyentertainment.com/cast-updates-malese-jow-stars-in-all-time-lows-music-video/ |title=Malese Jow Stars in All Time Low Music Video |website=Vampirediaries.alloyentertainment.com |date=2011-11-29 |accessdate=2013-10-14}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|1679802|Malese Jow}}\n* [http://malese-jow.com Malese Jow Fan Site], Malese-Jow.com\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140116234225/http://insidepunk.com/interviews/malese-jow-exclusive-interview/ Malese Jow interview], InsidePunk.com\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jow, Malese}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:American child actresses]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American people of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Tulsa, Oklahoma]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name         = Malese Jow\n| image        = Malese Jow at WonderCon 2014.jpg\n| caption      = Malese Jow at WonderCon 2014\n| birth_name   = Elizabeth Melise Jow\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1991|02|18}}\n| birth_place  = [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]], U.S.\n| residence    = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| genre        = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| occupation   = Actress, singer\n| other_name   =\n| years_active = 1997\u2013present\n| background       =solo_singer\n}}\n\n'''Elizabeth Melise Jow''' (born February 18, 1991), best known as '''Malese Jow''' and recently '''Melise''', is an American actress and singer. She is known for her roles as Geena Fabiano on the [[Nickelodeon]] sitcom ''[[Unfabulous]]'', Lucy Stone on the Nickelodeon musical sitcom ''[[Big Time Rush]]'' and as Anna, a teenage vampire on [[The CW]]'s fantasy drama ''[[The Vampire Diaries]]''. She starred as Julia Yeung in the short-lived CW science fiction romantic drama ''[[Star-Crossed (TV series)|Star-Crossed]]''. Jow starred as Mareth Ravenlock in season two of ''[[The Shannara Chronicles]]''. She has most recently been cast in [[Invincible (TV series)|Invincible]] for ''Amazon'' set for release in 2020.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]], Jow moved to [[California]] with her mother Lanae Tillery Jow, one sister, Makenna Jow, two brothers Jensen and Braden Jow and their cousin Chris Nightingale when she was nine years old. Jow is [[Chinese American]]<ref>{{cite web |author=Michael Smith |year=2010 |url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/scene/article.aspx?subjectid=268&articleid=20100926_282_D6_CUTLIN123015 |title=Little' Tulsa Girl in Big New Movie |work=Tulsa World |accessdate=2011-12-12}}</ref> As a child, she would often sing [[The Star-Spangled Banner|the national anthem]] at local baseball games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myfanbase.de/vampire-diaries/interviews/?pid=8913|title=Interview with Malese Jow|website=myfanbase.de|accessdate=2015-06-17}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nWhen she was six years old, Jow appeared on ''Barney'' and ''Dellaventura'', but her acting career took off when she won a co-starring role in the [[Nickelodeon]] sitcom ''[[Unfabulous]]'' with [[Emma Roberts]] where she played Geena Fabiano, one of the best friends of Roberts' character Addie Singer. The show ran for three seasons from 2004 to 2007 and earned Jow several [[Young Artist Award]] nominations.\n\nWhen ''Unfabulous'' ended in 2007, Jow co-starred in the animated film ''[[Bratz (2007 film)|Bratz: The Movie]]'' as Quinn and has guest-starred on the shows ''[[Wizards of Waverly Place]]'', ''[[The Young and the Restless]]'', ''[[iCarly]]'', ''[[The Secret Life of the American Teenager]]'' and the [[Disney Channel]] series ''[[Hannah Montana]]'' and co-starred in the 2009 science fiction comedy ''[[Aliens in the Attic]]''.\n\nIn 2010, Jow appeared in the first season of [[The CW]] fantasy drama ''[[The Vampire Diaries]]''. She played Anna, a vampire. Jow briefly re-appeared in the third season.<ref>{{cite web|author=Wetpaint Visitor |url=http://www.wetpaint.com/vampire-diaries/video/malese-jow-on-tvd-season-3-im-all-for-a-love-square- |title=Malese Jow On TVD Season 3: \"I'm All For a Love Square\" &#124; The Vampire Diaries |work=Wetpaint |date=2011-07-19 |accessdate=2013-10-14}}</ref> That same year, Jow co-starred in the fantasy romance film ''You're So Cupid!'' as Megan, and the drama film ''[[The Social Network]]'' as Alice Cantwell. She also guest-starred on an episode of [[TNT (American TV network)|TNT]] crime comedy-drama ''[[Leverage (TV series)|Leverage]]''. Then she went on to star in the Nickelodeon action/science fiction sitcom ''[[The Troop]]'' as Cadence Nash.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bopandtigerbeat.com/2010/10/exclusive-matt-shively-and-malese-jow-are-joining-the-troop/ |title=EXCLUSIVE: Matt Shively and Malese Jow are Joining The Troop! &#124; BOP and Tiger Beat Online |website=BopandTigerBeat.com |date=2010-10-15 |accessdate=2013-10-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109224740/http://www.bopandtigerbeat.com/2010/10/exclusive-matt-shively-and-malese-jow-are-joining-the-troop/ |archive-date=November 9, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n[[File:Malese Jow 3, 2012.jpg|right|thumb|Jow in June 2012]]\nIn 2011, Jow began a recurring role in the second season of the Nickelodeon musical sitcom ''[[Big Time Rush]]'' as Lucy Stone, an aspiring rock musician and a brief love interest of Kendall Knight ([[Kendall Schmidt]]) and later on becomes the love interest of James Diamond ([[James Maslow]]). She guest-starred in the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] mystery comedy-drama ''[[Desperate Housewives]]'' as Violet.<ref name=\"zap2it1\">{{cite web |author= |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2013/02/vampire-diaries-alum-malese-jow-joins-the-cws-oxygen-nkotbs-joey-mcintyre-in-the-mccarthys.html |title='Vampire Diaries' alum Malese Jow joins The CW's 'Oxygen,' NKOTB's Joey McIntyre in 'The McCarthys' |work=Zap2it |date=2013-02-21 |accessdate=2013-10-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130224051751/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2013/02/vampire-diaries-alum-malese-jow-joins-the-cws-oxygen-nkotbs-joey-mcintyre-in-the-mccarthys.html |archive-date=February 24, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Jow starred in The CW drama pilot ''Shelter'', produced by [[J. J. Abrams]] and [[Mark Schwahn]], where she played Morgan. It was not picked up by the network.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2012/03/vampire-diaries-star-malese-jow-scores-shelter-role.html |title='Vampire Diaries' star Malese Jow scores 'Shelter' role - From Inside the Box |work=Zap2it |date=2012-03-30 |accessdate=2012-05-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120519211737/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2012/03/vampire-diaries-star-malese-jow-scores-shelter-role.html |archive-date=May 19, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, Jow confirmed her role in the crime comedy ''[[Plastic (2014 film)|Plastic]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://malesejow.net/2015/03/04/malese-graces-the-cover-of-nationalist-magazines-march-2015-issue/|title=Malese graces the cover of Nationalist Magazine's March 2015 Issue|website=MaleseJow.net|accessdate=2015-06-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150617171705/http://malesejow.net/2015/03/04/malese-graces-the-cover-of-nationalist-magazines-march-2015-issue/|archive-date=June 17, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> That same month, it was also announced that Jow would reprise her role as Lucy Stone on ''Big Time Rush'' in the fourth and final season.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://www.clevvertv.com/cher-lloyd/38937/cher-lloyd-to-guest-star-on-big-time-rush.html |title=Cher Lloyd to Guest Star on \"Big Time Rush\" |website=Clevvertv.com |date=2013-01-23 |accessdate=2013-10-14}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2013, Jow was revealed to be the new host of ''The Vampire Diaries'' side show, ''TVD Rehash (Re#ash)'' replacing previous host [[Arielle Kebbel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vampire-diaries.net/tv-series/tvd-rehash-with-malese-jow-a-view-to-a-kill-ep412-video |title=TVD Rehash with Malese Jow: A View to a Kill (EP412) (VIDEO) &#124; Vampire-Diaries.net &#124; A Fansite for The Vampire Diaries & The Originals |website=Vampire-Diaries.net |date=2013-02-04 |accessdate=2013-10-14}}</ref> Later that month, it was announced that Jow would be joining the CW science fiction romantic drama pilot ''Oxygen'', as Julia Yeung, a girl who has an illness which may be cured by aliens.<ref name=\"zap2it1\"/><ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/ustv/news/a460831/glee-vampire-diaries-stars-join-the-cws-oxygen.html |title='Glee', 'Vampire Diaries' stars join The CW's 'Oxygen' - US TV News |work=Digital Spy |date=2013-02-22 |accessdate=2013-10-14}}</ref> In May 2013, ''Oxygen'' was picked up and retitled ''[[Star-Crossed (TV series)|Star-Crossed]]''. The series was part of the 2013\u201314 mid season schedule.<ref>{{cite web|author=Patrick Munn |url=http://www.tvwise.co.uk/2013/05/the-cw-picks-up-the-100-the-tomorrow-people-to-series/ |title=The CW Picks Up 'The 100', 'Reign, 'Star Crossed' & 'The Tomorrow People' To Series |work=TVWise |date=2013-05-09 |accessdate=2013-10-14}}</ref> In August 2013, production began for ''Star-Crossed''. The show ran for one season from February 17 to May 12, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starcrossedfan.com/ |title=Star-Crossed Fansite \u2013 Your first source for all StarCrossed CW News |website=Starcrossedfan.com |date= |accessdate=2013-10-14}}</ref> In 2014, Jow was in the television movie ''Presumed Dead in Paradise'' and played Madison Ashland. On October 27, 2014, she was announced to have a recurring role as [[Linda Park (comics)|Linda Park]] on the CW's superhero drama ''[[The Flash (2014 TV series)|The Flash]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2014/10/27/malese-jow-the-flash-linda-park/?hootPostID=c232dd3bb19fb1ac7c0ee936a1bcea7b |title='Vampire Diaries' star Malese Jow joins 'The Flash' as Linda Park |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=2014-10-27}}</ref> In 2015, Malese was listed in ''[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]''{{'}}s Hot 10.<ref>{{cite web |author=Sean Abrams |url=http://www.maxim.com/women/article/hot-10-malese-jow |title=Hot 10: Malese Jow |work=[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]] |date=2015-03-17 |accessdate=2015-08-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150720082705/http://www.maxim.com/women/article/hot-10-malese-jow |archivedate=2015-07-20 }}</ref>  On August 25, 2015, Malese was announced to be reprising her role as [[Linda Park (comics)|Linda Park]] as a friend of Iris for multiple episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2015/08/25/flash-season-2-malese-jow-linda-park|title=The Flash season 2: Malese Jow returning to play Linda Park |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=2015-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/ustv/s246/the-flash/news/a665460/the-flash-season-2-will-bring-back-malese-jow-as-linda-park.html#~pmX0GLVJiZpUjW|title=The Flash season 2 will bring back Malese Jow as Linda Park|author=Justin Harp|date=2015-08-26|work=Digital Spy}}</ref> In the second season's fifth episode, \"The Darkness and the Light,\" Malese played villainess [[Doctor Light (Kimiyo Hoshi)|Dr. Light]], who is Earth 2 [[Linda Park (comics)|Linda Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cartermatt.com/184335/the-flash-season-2-episode-5-preview-dr-lights-arrival-barry-allen-patty-spivot-go-on-a-date|title='The Flash' season 2, episode 5 preview: Dr. Light's arrival; Barry Allen, Patty Spivot go on a date|website=CarterMatt.com|date=October 28, 2015}}</ref> On February 2, 2017, it was announced Malese would be playing Mareth Ravenlock on MTV's ''[[The Shannara Chronicles]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/tv/2017/02/01/shannara-chronicles-season-2-production-cast/}}</ref> \nOn [[NCIS: Los Angeles]], she played Jennifer Kim, who is the illegitimate daughter of late NCIS Assistant Director Owen Granger ([[Miguel Ferrer]]). \nIn September 2017, it was revealed that Malese would be playing Daya in the upcoming ''[[Escape Plan: The Extractors]]'' movie. Malese has begun filming a new feature film as of November 2017 titled ''I Wrote This For You''.\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Bratz (2007 film)|Bratz: The Movie]]''\n| Quinn\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Aliens in the Attic]]''\n| Julie\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''You're So Cupid!''\n| Megan\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| style=\"white-space:nowrap;\" | ''{{sortname|The|Social Network}}''\n| Alice Cantwell\n| [[Hollywood Film Festival]] for Ensemble of the Year<br>Nominated\u2014[[Alliance of Women Film Journalists]] for Best Ensemble Cast<br>Nominated\u2014[[Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Cast]]<br>Nominated\u2014[[San Diego Film Critics Society Award for Best Performance by an Ensemble]]\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Plastic (2014 film)|Plastic]]''\n| Beth\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n|''[[Sisters of the Groom]]''\n|Sarah Adams\n|Hallmark Movie\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[I Wrote This For You]]''\n| Ariana\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Escape Plan: The Extractors]]''\n| Daya\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Barney & Friends]]''\n| Tea party girl\n| Episode: \"Pennies, Nickels, Dimes\"\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Dellaventura]]''\n| Orphan child\n| Episode: \"Dreamers\"; uncredited{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''{{sortname|The|Brothers Garcia}}''\n| Celeste\n| Episode: \"Right Place, Right Time\"\n|-\n| 2004\u201307\n| ''[[Unfabulous]]''\n| Geena Fabiano\n| Main role; 41 episodes<br>Nominated\u2014[[Young Artist Award